{"title_page": "Paul Burstow", "text_new": "{{short description|British former politician|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2012}}\n{{Use British English|date=June 2012}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n| name = Paul Burstow\n| image = Paul Burtsow Official.jpg\n| office = [[Department of Health (United Kingdom)|Minister of State for Care Services]]\n| primeminister = [[David Cameron]]\n| term_start = 11 May 2010\n| predecessor = [[Phil Hope]]\n| term_end = 4 September 2012\n| successor = [[Norman Lamb]]\n| office1 = [[Chief Whip of the Liberal Democrats]]\n| term_start1 = 22 March 2006\n| predecessor1 = [[Andrew Stunell]]\n| term_end1 = 11 May 2010\n| successor1 = [[Alistair Carmichael]]\n| office2 = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] <br /> for [[Sutton and Cheam (UK Parliament constituency)|Sutton and Cheam]]\n| term_start2 = 1 May 1997\n| term_end2 = 30 March 2015\n| predecessor2 = [[Olga Maitland]]\n| successor2 = [[Paul Scully]]\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1962|5|13|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Carshalton]], [[England]]\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n|party = [[Social Democratic Party (UK)|Social Democratic Party]] {{small|(Before 1988)}}<br />[[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]] {{small|(1988\u2013present)}}\n| spouse = Mary Everdell Kemm\n| children = 1 son<br />2 daughters\n| alma_mater = [[London South Bank University|South Bank Polytechnic]]\n}}\n\n'''Paul Kenneth Burstow''' (born 13 May 1962) is a [[United Kingdom|British]] former [[politician]] who served as the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrat]] [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for [[Sutton and Cheam (UK Parliament constituency)|Sutton and Cheam]] for 18 years, from 1997 to 2015, when he was defeated by [[Paul Scully]].\n\nHe was appointed Minister of State at the [[Department of Health (United Kingdom)|Department of Health]] in May 2010, and served in that position until September 2012.\n\n==Early life==\nBurstow was born in [[Carshalton]] in [[Surrey]], son of a [[tailor]], and was educated at Glastonbury High School for Boys,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politics.co.uk/reference/paul-kenneth-burstow|title=Paul Burstow - Biography|work=Politics.co.uk|accessdate=17 November 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180620232050/http://www.politics.co.uk/reference/paul-kenneth-burstow|archive-date=20 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> a former boys' secondary modern school in Carshalton, followed by [[Carshalton College]] and the [[London South Bank University|South Bank Polytechnic]], where he obtained a degree in business studies. He started his career as a buying assistant with Allied Shoe Repairs in 1985. The following year he worked briefly in print sales with KallKwik Printers, before becoming a research assistant at the [[London Borough of Hounslow]] in 1987.\n\n===Politics before parliament===\nHe was elected as a councillor for the [[Social Democratic Party (UK)|Social Democratic Party]] (SDP) to the [[London Borough of Sutton|Sutton Borough Council]] in 1986, and was its deputy leader from 1994 to 1997. Burstow remained a councillor for the Rosehill ward in Sutton until 2002, after his election to [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|Parliament]].\n\nIn 1988, he joined the Association of Liberal Democrat Councillors as a campaigns officer; he then became its political secretary in 1996, where he remained until becoming an MP.\n\n==Election and parliamentary career==\nBurstow first contested the Sutton and Cheam Parliamentary seat for the Liberal Democrats at the [[1992 United Kingdom general election|1992 General Election]]. He was defeated by the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] [[Lady Olga Maitland]] despite achieving one of the largest swings to the Liberal Democrats in London at that election.\n\nHe contested the seat again [[1997 United Kingdom general election|in 1997]], this time being elected as its Liberal Democrat MP with a majority of 2,097. Burstow joined several other new Liberal Democrat MPs, for the party gained many other south-west [[London]] seats at that election.\n\nHe made his [[maiden speech]] on 16 May 1997, speaking passionately about the needs of [[blindness|blind]] and [[disability|disabled people]].<ref>[https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm199798/cmhansrd/vo970516/debtext/70516-15.htm#70516-15_spnew0 Paul Burstow's Maiden Speech] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170206132639/https://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm199798/cmhansrd/vo970516/debtext/70516-15.htm#70516-15_spnew0 |date=6 February 2017 }} - ''Hansard''</ref> On his election, Burstow immediately became a party spokesman on [[Secretary of State for the Environment|the Environment]] under [[Paddy Ashdown]]. He became the spokesman on [[Department of Social Security|Social Security]] in 1999, on the election of [[Charles Kennedy]] as the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)#Leaders of the Liberal Democrats, 1988 \u2013 present|Leader of the Liberal Democrats]].\n\nAfter the [[2001 United Kingdom general election|2001 general election]], Burstow became the [[Department of Health (United Kingdom)|Health spokesman]] for the Liberal Democrats. He has been the parliamentary ambassador to the [[NSPCC]] since 2001. He was promoted to the Liberal Democrat [[Shadow Cabinet]] as the Shadow [[Secretary of State for Health]] in 2003. He stepped down from the Liberal Democrat Shadow Cabinet following the [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005 general election]], but was appointed as the spokesman on [[London]]. On 22 March 2006, Liberal Democrat MPs elected him their [[Chief Whip]].<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/4835310.stm Lib Dems name Burstow chief whip] - ''[[BBC|BBC News]]'' 22 March 2006</ref>\n\nIn 2003, ''[[The Guardian]]'' described Burstow as \"One of the most knowledgeable and effective politicians on older people's issues\".<ref>[http://society.guardian.co.uk/societyguardian/story/0,7843,1038556,00.html The opposition] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061231073450/http://society.guardian.co.uk/societyguardian/story/0,7843,1038556,00.html |date=31 December 2006 }} - ''[[The Guardian]]'' 10 September 2003</ref> He was voted by MPs as older people's champion in the epolitix [[Charity Champion awards]]<ref>[http://www.charitychampionawards.com/supporting-articles/paul_burstow.htm Paul Burstow] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20051217113019/http://www.charitychampionawards.com/supporting-articles/paul_burstow.htm |date=17 December 2005 }} - ''Charitychampionawards.com'' 2005</ref> in December 2005.\n\nBurstow introduced the Care of Older and Incapacitated People (Human Rights) Bill in January 2006. It provided proposals to increase the protection of vulnerable adults from abuse and neglect. In 2007, he introduced an [[Early Day Motion]] congratulating the [[National Benevolent Fund for the Aged]] on its 50th anniversary.<ref>{{cite web |title= National Benevolent Fund For The Aged |work= Early Day Motion number 878 in 2006-07, proposed by Paul Burstow |date= 8 February 2007 |url= http://www.edms.org.uk/2006-07/878.htm |accessdate= 5 August 2011 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20111009101143/http://www.edms.org.uk/2006-07/878.htm |archive-date= 9 October 2011 |url-status= live }}</ref>\n\n===Minister of State===\nAt the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010 general election]] Burstow was re-elected MP for Sutton and Cheam with a slim majority of 1,608 votes.<ref name=\"politics1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.politics.co.uk/reference/paul-kenneth-burstow |title=Paul Burstow |publisher=Politics.co.uk |accessdate=30 March 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131010001952/http://politics.co.uk/reference/paul-kenneth-burstow |archive-date=10 October 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> He was then appointed [[Minister of State]] in the Department of Health in the coalition government. He was responsible for care services and the elderly and mental health.  He was responsible for developing the Government's mental health strategy and drafting the care provisions of the Care Act.<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite news |last=Prince |first=Rosa |title=Paul Burstow criticises 'dangerous and flawed' plans to close hospitals after being sacked as a health minister |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/liberaldemocrats/9528849/Paul-Burstow-criticises-dangerous-and-flawed-plans-to-close-hospitals-after-being-sacked-as-a-health-minister.html |accessdate=30 March 2013 |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |date=7 September 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121106115830/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/liberaldemocrats/9528849/Paul-Burstow-criticises-dangerous-and-flawed-plans-to-close-hospitals-after-being-sacked-as-a-health-minister.html |archive-date=6 November 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn December 2010, he said he was \"embarrassed\" after being secretly taped by ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' saying voters should not trust [[David Cameron]]. Burstow told undercover reporters: \"I don't want you to trust David Cameron... in the sense that you believe he's suddenly become a cuddly Liberal. Well, he hasn't. He's still a Conservative and he has values that I don't share.\"<ref name=autogenerated2>{{cite news|title=Lib Dem minister Paul Burstow 'embarrassed' over 'can't trust Cameron' comments|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/liberaldemocrats/8221482/Lib-Dem-minister-Paul-Burstow-embarrassed-over-cant-trust-Cameron-comments.html|accessdate=30 March 2013|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph|date=23 December 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140426221425/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/liberaldemocrats/8221482/Lib-Dem-minister-Paul-Burstow-embarrassed-over-cant-trust-Cameron-comments.html|archive-date=26 April 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> He later told the [[BBC]] that he regretted the way his remarks had been construed, and that he had \"full trust\" in David Cameron.<ref name=autogenerated2 />\n\nBurstow left the government in September 2012, and was replaced as Care Minister by [[Norman Lamb]].<ref name=autogenerated1 /> Burstow criticised plans to cut hospital services in London. Burstow said that a planned closure of a casualty and maternity unit in south-west London put patient safety at risk and warned that it was likely to lead to \"more mothers giving birth in the back of their car\".<ref>{{cite news |last=Cecil |first=Nicholas |title='Dangerous and flawed': sacked minister Paul Burstow's verdict on hospital cuts |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/dangerous-and-flawed-sacked-minister-paul-burstows-verdict-on-hospital-cuts-8116891.html |accessdate=30 March 2013 |date=7 September 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120911014724/http://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/dangerous-and-flawed-sacked-minister-paul-burstows-verdict-on-hospital-cuts-8116891.html |archive-date=11 September 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Subsequent career==\nHe was appointed Chair of the [[Tavistock and Portman NHS Foundation Trust]] from November 2015, and was recently appointed for a second three-year term. He is a Trustee of [[Action on Smoking and Health]].\n\nIn 2016 he became a part-time professor of mental health policy at the University of Birmingham where he led a policy commission.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.birmingham.ac.uk/research/impact/policy-commissions/mental-health/index.aspx|title=Birmingham University Policy Commissions|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190416231325/https://www.birmingham.ac.uk/research/impact/policy-commissions/mental-health/index.aspx|archive-date=16 April 2019|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nPaul's interest in social care saw him appointed as Chair of the [[Social Care Institute for Excellence]] in July 2017 where he has worked to refresh the board of Trustees and develop the organisation's business strategy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scie.org.uk/news/mediareleases/paul-burstow-announcement|title=Paul Burstow announced as SCIE Chair|last=|first=|date=|website=Social Care Institute for Excellence|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191017160527/https://www.scie.org.uk/news/mediareleases/paul-burstow-announcement|archive-date=17 October 2019|access-date=17 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nHe married [[2014 Sutton London Borough Council election#Cheam|Mary Burstow]], a Liberal Democrat councillor for Cheam,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cheam.mycouncillor.org.uk/about/#page-content|title=CLLR Mary Burstow|access-date=9 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180409233536/https://cheam.mycouncillor.org.uk/about/#page-content|archive-date=9 April 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> in 1995; they have a son and two daughters. His interests include cooking, reading, and walking.<ref name=\"politics1\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20050404232339/http://www.paulburstow.org.uk/ Paul Burstow MP] ''official constituency website''\n* [http://www.libdems.org.uk/people_detail.aspx?name=Paul_Burstow&pPK=675c2aa8-29de-4600-8cfd-523d41838c30 Profile] at the Liberal Democrats\n*{{UK MP links | parliament = paul-burstow/204 | hansard = mr-paul-burstow | hansardcurr = 2384 | guardian = 754/paul-burstow | publicwhip = Paul_Burstow | theywork = paul_burstow | record = Paul-Burstow/Sutton-and-Cheam/1081 | bbc = 25753.stm | journalisted = paul-burstow }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Olga Maitland]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for [[Sutton and Cheam (UK Parliament constituency)|Sutton and Cheam]]|years=[[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997]]\u2013[[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015]]}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Paul Scully]]}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{succession box | title  = [[Chief Whip of the Liberal Democrats]] | years  = 2006\u20132010 | before = [[Andrew Stunell]] | after = [[Alistair Carmichael]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Burstow, Paul}}\n[[Category:Liberal Democrats (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1997\u20132001]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2001\u20132005]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2005\u20132010]]\n[[Category:Councillors in the London Borough of Sutton]]\n[[Category:Alumni of London South Bank University]]\n[[Category:1962 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the Privy Council of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:People from Carshalton]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2010\u20132015]]\n[[Category:Social Democratic Party (UK) politicians]]\n[[Category:Liberal Democrats (UK) councillors]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British former politician|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2012}}\n{{Use British English|date=June 2012}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n| name = Paul Burstow\n| image = Paul Burtsow Official.jpg\n| office = [[Department of Health (United Kingdom)|Minister of State for Care Services]]\n| primeminister = [[David Cameron]]\n| term_start = 11 May 2010\n| predecessor = [[Phil Hope]]\n| term_end = 4 September 2012\n| successor = [[Norman Lamb]]\n| office1 = [[Chief Whip of the Liberal Democrats]]\n| term_start1 = 22 March 2006\n| predecessor1 = [[Andrew Stunell]]\n| term_end1 = 11 May 2010\n| successor1 = [[Alistair Carmichael]]\n| office2 = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] <br /> for [[Sutton and Cheam (UK Parliament constituency)|Sutton and Cheam]]\n| term_start2 = 1 May 1997\n| term_end2 = 30 March 2015\n| predecessor2 = [[Olga Maitland]]\n| successor2 = [[Paul Scully]]\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1962|5|13|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Carshalton]], [[England]]\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n|party = [[Social Democratic Party (UK)|Social Democratic Party]] {{small|(Before 1988)}}<br />[[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]] {{small|(1988\u2013present)}}\n| spouse = Mary Everdell Kemm\n| children = 1 son<br />2 daughters\n| alma_mater = [[London South Bank University|South Bank Polytechnic]]\n}}\n\n'''Paul Kenneth Burstow''' (born 13 May 1962) is a [[United Kingdom|British]] former [[politician]] who served as the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrat]] [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for [[Sutton and Cheam (UK Parliament constituency)|Sutton and Cheam]] for 18 years, from 1997 to 2015, when he was defeated by [[Paul Scully]].\n\nHe was appointed Minister of State at the [[Department of Health (United Kingdom)|Department of Health]] in May 2010, and served in that position until September 2012.\n\n==Early life==\nBurstow was born in [[Carshalton]] in [[Surrey]], son of a [[tailor]], and was educated at Glastonbury High School for Boys,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politics.co.uk/reference/paul-kenneth-burstow|title=Paul Burstow - Biography|work=Politics.co.uk|accessdate=17 November 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180620232050/http://www.politics.co.uk/reference/paul-kenneth-burstow|archive-date=20 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> a former boys' secondary modern school in Carshalton, followed by [[Carshalton College]] and the [[London South Bank University|South Bank Polytechnic]], where he obtained a degree in business studies. He started his career as a buying assistant with Allied Shoe Repairs in 1985. The following year he worked briefly in print sales with KallKwik Printers, before becoming a research assistant at the [[London Borough of Hounslow]] in 1987.\n\n===Politics before parliament===\nHe was elected as a councillor for the [[Social Democratic Party (UK)|Social Democratic Party]] (SDP) to the [[London Borough of Sutton|Sutton Borough Council]] in 1986, and was its deputy leader from 1994 to 1997. Burstow remained a councillor for the Rosehill ward in Sutton until 2002, after his election to [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|Parliament]].\n\nIn 1988, he joined the Association of Liberal Democrat Councillors as a campaigns officer; he then became its political secretary in 1996, where he remained until becoming an MP.\n\n==Election and parliamentary career==\nBurstow first contested the Sutton and Cheam Parliamentary seat for the Liberal Democrats at the [[1992 United Kingdom general election|1992 General Election]]. He was defeated by the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] [[Lady Olga Maitland]] despite achieving one of the largest swings to the Liberal Democrats in London at that election.\n\nHe contested the seat again [[1997 United Kingdom general election|in 1997]], this time being elected as its Liberal Democrat MP with a majority of 2,097. Burstow joined several other new Liberal Democrat MPs, for the party gained many other south-west [[London]] seats at that election.\n\nHe made his [[maiden speech]] on 16 May 1997, speaking passionately about the needs of [[blindness|blind]] and [[disability|disabled people]].<ref>[https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm199798/cmhansrd/vo970516/debtext/70516-15.htm#70516-15_spnew0 Paul Burstow's Maiden Speech] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170206132639/https://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm199798/cmhansrd/vo970516/debtext/70516-15.htm#70516-15_spnew0 |date=6 February 2017 }} - ''Hansard''</ref> On his election, Burstow immediately became a party spokesman on [[Secretary of State for the Environment|the Environment]] under [[Paddy Ashdown]]. He became the spokesman on [[Department of Social Security|Social Security]] in 1999, on the election of [[Charles Kennedy]] as the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)#Leaders of the Liberal Democrats, 1988 \u2013 present|Leader of the Liberal Democrats]].\n\nAfter the [[2001 United Kingdom general election|2001 general election]], Burstow became the [[Department of Health (United Kingdom)|Health spokesman]] for the Liberal Democrats. He has been the parliamentary ambassador to the [[NSPCC]] since 2001. He was promoted to the Liberal Democrat [[Shadow Cabinet]] as the Shadow [[Secretary of State for Health]] in 2003. He stepped down from the Liberal Democrat Shadow Cabinet following the [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005 general election]], but was appointed as the spokesman on [[London]]. On 22 March 2006, Liberal Democrat MPs elected him their [[Chief Whip]].<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/4835310.stm Lib Dems name Burstow chief whip] - ''[[BBC|BBC News]]'' 22 March 2006</ref>\n\nIn 2003, ''[[The Guardian]]'' described Burstow as \"One of the most knowledgeable and effective politicians on older people's issues\".<ref>[http://society.guardian.co.uk/societyguardian/story/0,7843,1038556,00.html The opposition] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061231073450/http://society.guardian.co.uk/societyguardian/story/0,7843,1038556,00.html |date=31 December 2006 }} - ''[[The Guardian]]'' 10 September 2003</ref> He was voted by MPs as older people's champion in the epolitix [[Charity Champion awards]]<ref>[http://www.charitychampionawards.com/supporting-articles/paul_burstow.htm Paul Burstow] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20051217113019/http://www.charitychampionawards.com/supporting-articles/paul_burstow.htm |date=17 December 2005 }} - ''Charitychampionawards.com'' 2005</ref> in December 2005.\n\nBurstow introduced the Care of Older and Incapacitated People (Human Rights) Bill in January 2006. It provided proposals to increase the protection of vulnerable adults from abuse and neglect. In 2007, he introduced an [[Early Day Motion]] congratulating the [[National Benevolent Fund for the Aged]] on its 50th anniversary.<ref>{{cite web |title= National Benevolent Fund For The Aged |work= Early Day Motion number 878 in 2006-07, proposed by Paul Burstow |date= 8 February 2007 |url= http://www.edms.org.uk/2006-07/878.htm |accessdate= 5 August 2011 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20111009101143/http://www.edms.org.uk/2006-07/878.htm |archive-date= 9 October 2011 |url-status= live }}</ref>\n\n===Minister of State===\nAt the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010 general election]] Burstow was re-elected MP for Sutton and Cheam with a slim majority of 1,608 votes.<ref name=\"politics1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.politics.co.uk/reference/paul-kenneth-burstow |title=Paul Burstow |publisher=Politics.co.uk |accessdate=30 March 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131010001952/http://politics.co.uk/reference/paul-kenneth-burstow |archive-date=10 October 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> He was then appointed [[Minister of State]] in the Department of Health in the coalition government. He was responsible for care services and the elderly and mental health.  He was responsible for developing the Government's mental health strategy and drafting the care provisions of the Care Act.<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite news |last=Prince |first=Rosa |title=Paul Burstow criticises 'dangerous and flawed' plans to close hospitals after being sacked as a health minister |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/liberaldemocrats/9528849/Paul-Burstow-criticises-dangerous-and-flawed-plans-to-close-hospitals-after-being-sacked-as-a-health-minister.html |accessdate=30 March 2013 |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |date=7 September 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121106115830/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/liberaldemocrats/9528849/Paul-Burstow-criticises-dangerous-and-flawed-plans-to-close-hospitals-after-being-sacked-as-a-health-minister.html |archive-date=6 November 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn December 2010, he said he was \"embarrassed\" after being secretly taped by ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' saying voters should not trust [[David Cameron]]. Burstow told undercover reporters: \"I don't want you to trust David Cameron... in the sense that you believe he's suddenly become a cuddly Liberal. Well, he hasn't. He's still a Conservative and he has values that I don't share.\"<ref name=autogenerated2>{{cite news|title=Lib Dem minister Paul Burstow 'embarrassed' over 'can't trust Cameron' comments|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/liberaldemocrats/8221482/Lib-Dem-minister-Paul-Burstow-embarrassed-over-cant-trust-Cameron-comments.html|accessdate=30 March 2013|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph|date=23 December 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140426221425/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/liberaldemocrats/8221482/Lib-Dem-minister-Paul-Burstow-embarrassed-over-cant-trust-Cameron-comments.html|archive-date=26 April 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> He later told the [[BBC]] that he regretted the way his remarks had been construed, and that he had \"full trust\" in David Cameron.<ref name=autogenerated2 />\n\nBurstow left the government in September 2012, and was replaced as Care Minister by [[Norman Lamb]].<ref name=autogenerated1 /> Burstow criticised plans to cut hospital services in London. Burstow said that a planned closure of a casualty and maternity unit in south-west London put patient safety at risk and warned that it was likely to lead to \"more mothers giving birth in the back of their car\".<ref>{{cite news |last=Cecil |first=Nicholas |title='Dangerous and flawed': sacked minister Paul Burstow's verdict on hospital cuts |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/dangerous-and-flawed-sacked-minister-paul-burstows-verdict-on-hospital-cuts-8116891.html |accessdate=30 March 2013 |date=7 September 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120911014724/http://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/dangerous-and-flawed-sacked-minister-paul-burstows-verdict-on-hospital-cuts-8116891.html |archive-date=11 September 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Subsequent career==\nHe was appointed Chair of the [[Tavistock and Portman NHS Foundation Trust]] from November 2015, and was recently appointed for a second three year term. He is a Trustee of [[Action on Smoking and Health]].\n\nIn 2016 he became a part-time professor of mental health policy at the University of Birmingham where he led a policy commission.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.birmingham.ac.uk/research/impact/policy-commissions/mental-health/index.aspx|title=Birmingham University Policy Commissions|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190416231325/https://www.birmingham.ac.uk/research/impact/policy-commissions/mental-health/index.aspx|archive-date=16 April 2019|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nPaul's interest in social care saw him appointed as Chair of the [[Social Care Institute for Excellence]] in July 2017 where he has worked to refresh the board of Trustees and develop the organisation's business strategy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scie.org.uk/news/mediareleases/paul-burstow-announcement|title=Paul Burstow announced as SCIE Chair|last=|first=|date=|website=Social Care Institute for Excellence|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191017160527/https://www.scie.org.uk/news/mediareleases/paul-burstow-announcement|archive-date=17 October 2019|access-date=17 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nHe married [[2014 Sutton London Borough Council election#Cheam|Mary Burstow]], a Liberal Democrat councillor for Cheam,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cheam.mycouncillor.org.uk/about/#page-content|title=CLLR Mary Burstow|access-date=9 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180409233536/https://cheam.mycouncillor.org.uk/about/#page-content|archive-date=9 April 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> in 1995; they have a son and two daughters. His interests include cooking, reading, and walking.<ref name=\"politics1\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20050404232339/http://www.paulburstow.org.uk/ Paul Burstow MP] ''official constituency website''\n* [http://www.libdems.org.uk/people_detail.aspx?name=Paul_Burstow&pPK=675c2aa8-29de-4600-8cfd-523d41838c30 Profile] at the Liberal Democrats\n*{{UK MP links | parliament = paul-burstow/204 | hansard = mr-paul-burstow | hansardcurr = 2384 | guardian = 754/paul-burstow | publicwhip = Paul_Burstow | theywork = paul_burstow | record = Paul-Burstow/Sutton-and-Cheam/1081 | bbc = 25753.stm | journalisted = paul-burstow }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Olga Maitland]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for [[Sutton and Cheam (UK Parliament constituency)|Sutton and Cheam]]|years=[[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997]]\u2013[[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015]]}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Paul Scully]]}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{succession box | title  = [[Chief Whip of the Liberal Democrats]] | years  = 2006\u20132010 | before = [[Andrew Stunell]] | after = [[Alistair Carmichael]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Burstow, Paul}}\n[[Category:Liberal Democrats (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1997\u20132001]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2001\u20132005]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2005\u20132010]]\n[[Category:Councillors in the London Borough of Sutton]]\n[[Category:Alumni of London South Bank University]]\n[[Category:1962 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the Privy Council of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:People from Carshalton]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2010\u20132015]]\n[[Category:Social Democratic Party (UK) politicians]]\n[[Category:Liberal Democrats (UK) councillors]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSubsequent career:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: three year \u2192 three-year", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paul_Burstow"}
{"title_page": "Des Browne", "text_new": "{{short description|British Labour politician}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n|name             = The Lord Browne of Ladyton\n|honorific-suffix = [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom|PC]]\n|image            = Official portrait of Lord Browne of Ladyton crop 3, 2019.jpg\n|caption          = Lord Browne of Ladyton in 2019\n|office           = [[Secretary of State for Scotland]]\n|primeminister    = [[Gordon Brown]]\n|term_start       = 28 June 2007\n|term_end         = 3 October 2008\n|predecessor      = [[Douglas Alexander]]\n|successor        = [[Jim Murphy]]\n|office1          = [[Secretary of State for Defence]]\n|primeminister1   = [[Tony Blair]]<br />[[Gordon Brown]]\n|term_start1      = 5 May 2006\n|term_end1        = 3 October 2008\n|predecessor1     = [[John Reid, Baron Reid of Cardowan|John Reid]]\n|successor1       = [[John Hutton, Baron Hutton of Furness|John Hutton]]\n|office2          = [[Chief Secretary to the Treasury]]\n|primeminister2   = [[Tony Blair]]\n|term_start2      = 6 May 2005\n|term_end2        = 5 May 2006\n|predecessor2     = [[Paul Boateng]]\n|successor2       = [[Stephen Timms]]\n|office3          = [[Minister of State for Immigration|Minister of State for Immigration, Citizenship and Counterterrorism]]\n|primeminister3   = [[Tony Blair]]\n|term_start3      = 1 April 2004\n|term_end3        = 6 May 2005\n|predecessor3     = [[Beverley Hughes]]\n|successor3       = [[Tony McNulty]] {{small|(Immigration, Citizenship and Nationality)}}\n|office4          = [[Minister of State|Minister of State for Work & Pensions]]\n|primeminister4   = [[Tony Blair]]\n|term_start4      = May 2003\n|term_end4      = 1 April 2004\n|office5          = [[Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State|Parliamentary under-Secretary of State for Northern Ireland]]\n|primeminister5   = [[Tony Blair]]\n|term_start5      = May 2001\n|term_end5       = May 2003\n|office6          = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[Kilmarnock and Loudoun (UK Parliament constituency)|Kilmarnock and Loudoun]]\n|term_start6      = 2 May 1997\n|term_end6        = 12 April 2010\n|predecessor6     = [[William McKelvey]]\n|successor6       = [[Cathy Jamieson]]\n|birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1952|3|22|df=y}}\n|birth_place      = [[Kilwinning]], Scotland\n|death_date       = \n|death_place      = \n|party            = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]\n|alma_mater       = [[University of Glasgow]]\n|religion         = [[Catholic Church|Roman Catholicism]]<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.independent.co.uk/uk/politics/article624201.ece |work=The Independent |location=London |title=Blair to meet Pope and fuel rumours of Catholic conversion |first1=Colin |last1=Brown |date=3 June 2006 |accessdate=1 May 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080111151131/http://news.independent.co.uk/uk/politics/article624201.ece |archivedate=11 January 2008 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n}}\n'''Desmond Henry Browne, Baron Browne of Ladyton''', {{post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|PC}} (born 22 March 1952) is a [[British people|British]] [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] [[politician]] who was the [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Kilmarnock and Loudoun (UK Parliament constituency)|Kilmarnock and Loudoun]] from [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997]] to [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010]]. He was a member of the [[Cabinet of the United Kingdom]] under [[Tony Blair]] and [[Gordon Brown]], until the latter moved him from both [[Secretary of State for Defence|Defence]] and [[Secretary of State for Scotland|Scottish Secretary]] in 2008.\n\n==Early life and education==\nBrowne was born in [[Kilwinning]], [[North Ayrshire]], lived in [[Stevenston]] for the early part of his life, and was educated at the Catholic St Michael's Academy in [[Kilwinning]] and later at the [[University of Glasgow]], where he received a [[Master of Laws|degree]] in [[Scots law|law]].\n\n==Legal career==\nHe started his legal career in 1974 as an apprentice [[solicitor]] with the firm James Campbell & Co. On qualifying in 1976 he became an assistant solicitor with Ross, Harper and Murphy, and was promoted to partner in 1980. He became a partner in McCluskey Browne in 1985 and a council member of the [[Law Society of Scotland]] 1988\u20131992. He was admitted as an [[advocate]] in 1993, practising at the Scottish bar until 1997. He worked mainly in child law.\n\n==Parliamentary career==\nBrowne contested the [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|parliamentary]] seat of [[Argyll and Bute (UK Parliament constituency)|Argyll and Bute]] at the [[1992 United Kingdom general election|1992 General Election]], and finished in fourth place behind the sitting [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrat]] MP [[Ray Michie, Baroness Michie of Gallanach|Ray Michie]]. He was elected to the [[Faculty of Advocates]] in 1993. Browne was selected to contest the safe Labour seat of Kilmarnock and Loudoun following the retirement of the sitting MP [[William McKelvey]]. Browne won the seat at the [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997 General Election]] with a majority of 7,256. He made his [[maiden speech]] on 20 June 1997.\n\nBrowne joined the [[Northern Ireland Affairs Select Committee]] on his election, and became the [[Parliamentary Private Secretary]] (PPS) to the [[Secretary of State for Scotland]] [[Donald Dewar]] in 1998. After Dewar left the Cabinet in 1999, to seek election as the [[First Minister of Scotland]], Browne remained in post as PPS to the new Secretary of State [[John Reid, Baron Reid of Cardowan|John Reid]]. In 2000 he became the PPS to the [[Minister of State]] at the [[Northern Ireland Office]].\n\nOn 27 November 2009, Browne announced his intention not seek election in the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010 general election]].<ref>{{cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/politics/8383783.stm | title=Des Browne to quit House of Commons after next election | work=[[BBC News Online]] | date=27 November 2009 | accessdate=2 January 2010 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091130055004/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/politics/8383783.stm | archive-date=30 November 2009 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nBrowne currently acts as convenor of the [[Top Level Group|Top Level Group of UK Parliamentarians for Multilateral Nuclear Disarmament and Non-proliferation]], established in October 2009.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2009/sep/08/nuclear-disarmament-cross-party-group | location=London | work=The Guardian | title=Nuclear-free world ultimate aim of new cross-party pressure group | first=Julian | last=Borger | date=8 September 2009 | access-date=14 December 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090630013226/http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2009/sep/08/nuclear-disarmament-cross-party-group | archive-date=30 June 2009 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Government Minister==\n[[File:Browne and gates.jpg|thumb|left|Browne meeting [[Robert Gates]] in Edinburgh during December 2007]]\nAfter the [[2001 United Kingdom general election|2001 General Election]] Browne entered [[Tony Blair]]'s government as the [[Parliamentary Under Secretary of State]] at the [[Northern Ireland Office]]. He was promoted to Minister of State at the [[Department for Work and Pensions]] in 2003, before moving to the [[Home Office]] in 2004 as the minister with responsibility for [[immigration]]. He joined the Cabinet following the [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005 General Election]] as the [[Chief Secretary to the Treasury]] and became a [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom|Member of the Privy Council]].\n\nBrowne was appointed [[Secretary of State for Defence]] on 5 May 2006. An advocate of the [[UK Trident programme]], in 2007 he successfully persuaded Parliament to vote to replace Trident. He came under criticism, however, after allowing the [[2007 Iranian seizure of Royal Navy personnel|Royal Navy personnel captured by Iran in spring 2007]] to sell and publish their stories.<ref name=\"profile\">{{cite news\n| work = BBC News\n| title = Profile: Des Browne\n| accessdate = 2009-01-02\n| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/4977660.stm\n| date = 15 April 2007\n| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20090327002951/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/4977660.stm\n| archive-date = 27 March 2009\n| url-status = live\n}}</ref> Under [[Tony Blair]]'s premiership, Browne was considered a supporter of the [[Chancellor of the Exchequer]] [[Gordon Brown]].<ref name=\"profile\"/><ref>{{cite news|author=Sarah Hall, political correspondent |url=https://www.theguardian.com/guardianpolitics/story/0,3605,1184117,00.html |title=Brown's man Browne gets poisoned chalice &#124; Politics |newspaper=The Guardian |accessdate=2013-03-13}}</ref> He received the additional responsibilities of [[Secretary of State for Scotland]] in June 2007 after Brown became Prime Minister.\n\nIn a free parliamentary vote on 20 May 2008, Browne voted for cutting the upper limit for abortions from 24 to 12 weeks, along with two other Catholic cabinet ministers [[Ruth Kelly]] and [[Paul Murphy, Baron Murphy of Torfaen|Paul Murphy]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/7409696.stm |title=UK &#124; UK Politics &#124; MPs back 24-week abortion limit |work=BBC News |date=2008-05-20 |accessdate=2013-03-13 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090330152748/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/7409696.stm |archive-date=30 March 2009 |url-status=live }}</ref> He returned to the backbenches in October 2008 following a cabinet reshuffle.\n\nBrowne [[List of witnesses of The Iraq Inquiry#January 25|gave evidence]] to the [[Iraq Inquiry]] on 25 January 2010.<ref name=\"Iraq Inquiry\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/8479074.stm|title=Ex-defence secretary speaks of strain of Iraq losses|date=25 January 2010|work=[[BBC News]]|publisher=BBC|accessdate=29 January 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Activities post-government==\nBrowne is vice chairman of the Washington, DC-based [http://www.nti.org/ Nuclear Threat Initiative], a non-profit, nonpartisan organization founded in 2001 by former U.S. Senator [http://www.nti.org/about/leadership-staff/sam-nunn/ Sam Nunn], who serves as co-chair and CEO, and CNN founder and philanthropist Ted Turner. NTI's mission is to strengthen global security by reducing the risk of use and preventing the spread of nuclear, biological and chemical weapons.\n\nBrowne is also convener of the [[European Leadership Network for Multilateral Nuclear Disarmament and Non-proliferation]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.europeanleadershipnetwork.org/des-browne_67.html |title=Members: Lord Desmond Browne of Ladyton |publisher=European Leadership Network for Multilateral Nuclear Disarmament and Non-proliferation |accessdate=25 February 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110726042056/http://www.europeanleadershipnetwork.org/des-browne_67.html |archive-date=26 July 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> and he is convener of the [[Top Level Group]] of UK Parliamentarians for Multilateral Nuclear Disarmament and Nonproliferation.<ref>{{cite report |url=http://www.basicint.org/publications/des-browne/2010/nuclear-policy-paper-no3 |title=Current NATO Nuclear Policy |author=Des Browne |date=November 2010 |publisher=Arms Control Association et al |accessdate=25 February 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101203074650/http://www.basicint.org/publications/des-browne/2010/nuclear-policy-paper-no3 |archivedate=3 December 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nDes Browne is a signatory of [[Global Zero (campaign)]], a non-profit international initiative for the elimination of all nuclear weapons worldwide.<ref>{{cite news|title=Group Offers Plan to Eliminate Nukes by 2030|url=http://www.globalzero.org/files/pdf/NYT_Jun29_09_AP_Syndicated.pdf|newspaper=The New York Times|date=29 June 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110513205939/http://www.globalzero.org/files/pdf/NYT_Jun29_09_AP_Syndicated.pdf|archivedate=13 May 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref>  Since its launch in Paris in December 2008,<ref>{{cite news|last=Corera|first=Gordon|title=Group seeks nuclear weapons ban|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/7774584.stm|newspaper=BBC|date=10 December 2008|access-date=30 March 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110728005425/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/7774584.stm|archive-date=28 July 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Global Zero (campaign)]] has grown to 300 leaders, including current and former heads of state, national security officials and military commanders, and 400,000 citizens worldwide; developed a practical step-by-step plan to eliminate nuclear weapons; launched an international student campaign with 75 campus chapters in eight countries; and produced an acclaimed documentary film, [[Countdown to Zero]], in partnership with [[Lawrence Bender]] and [[Participant Media]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Clift|first=Eleanor|title=A Good Start: 'Global Zero' reminds us that eradicating nuclear weapons should still be our ultimate goal.|url=http://www.newsweek.com/id/236133|newspaper=Newsweek|access-date=30 March 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100413113211/http://www.newsweek.com/id/236133|archive-date=13 April 2010|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Controversy over appointment as envoy to Sri Lanka===\nIn February 2009, Browne was appointed by PM Brown as the government's [[special envoy]] to [[Sri Lanka]]. However, the government of [[Mahinda Rajapaksa]], fighting the [[LTTE]] rebel group, rejected Browne's appointment, stating that the British government made the appointment unilaterally, without consultation with the Sri Lankan government.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/7887853.stm |title=''Sri Lanka rejects UK's new envoy'' |work=BBC News |date=2009-02-13 |accessdate=2013-03-13 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090213214657/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/7887853.stm |archive-date=13 February 2009 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.desbrownemp.co.uk Des Browne MP website]\n* {{Hansard-contribs | mr-des-browne | Des Browne }}\n*[http://www.mod.uk/DefenceInternet/AboutDefence/People/Ministers/SecretaryOfStateForDefence.htm Ministry of Defence official biography]\n*[http://www.mod.uk/DefenceInternet/AboutDefence/People/Speeches/SofS/UkDefenceStrategyInIraq.htm Speech on Iraq November 2006]\n*[http://www.mod.uk/DefenceInternet/AboutDefence/People/Speeches/SofS/RusiSpeech19thSep2006.htm Speech on Afghanistan September 2006]\n*[http://www.mod.uk/DefenceInternet/AboutDefence/People/Speeches/SofS/TheUnitedKingdomsNuclearDeterrentInThe21stCentury.htm Speech on the UK's Nuclear Deterrent January 2007]\n*[http://politics.guardian.co.uk/person/0,9290,-666,00.html Guardian Unlimited Politics - Ask Aristotle: Des Browne MP]\n*[https://www.theyworkforyou.com/mp/des_browne/kilmarnock_and_loudoun TheyWorkForYou.com - Des Browne MP]\n*[http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/uk-world-news/2009/01/21/a-day-of-destiny-by-des-browne-mp-86908-21057688/ Des Browne's article] in the ''[[Daily Record (Scotland)|Daily Record]]'', covering President Obama's Inauguration 20 January 2009\n*[http://www.globalzero.org Global Zero]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20100815063542/http://www.globalzero.org/en/who/des-browne Des Browne at Global Zero]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[William McKelvey]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[Kilmarnock and Loudoun (UK Parliament constituency)|Kilmarnock and Loudoun]]|years=[[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997]]\u2013[[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010]]}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Cathy Jamieson]]}}\n{{s-break}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Beverley Hughes]]|}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister of State for Immigration|Minister of State for Immigration,<br />Citizenship and Counterterrorism]]|years=2004\u20132005}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Tony McNulty]] |as=Minister of State for Immigration,<br />Citizenship and Nationality}}\n{{s-break}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Paul Boateng]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Chief Secretary to the Treasury]]|years=2005\u20132006}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Stephen Timms]]}}\n{{s-break}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[John Reid, Baron Reid of Cardowan|John Reid]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Secretary of State for Defence]]|years=2006\u20132008}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[John Hutton, Baron Hutton of Furness|John Hutton]]}}\n{{s-break}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Douglas Alexander]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Secretary of State for Scotland]]|years=2007\u20132008}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Jim Murphy]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Brown Cabinet}}\n{{Secretary of State for Defence}}\n{{Secretaries of State for Scotland}}\n{{Minister of State for Borders and Immigration}}\n{{Chief Secretaries to the Treasury}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Browne, Des}}\n[[Category:1952 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Kilwinning]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Glasgow]]\n[[Category:Members of the Faculty of Advocates]]\n[[Category:Scottish Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:Scottish Labour Party MPs]]\n[[Category:Members of the Privy Council of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Northern Ireland Office junior ministers]]\n[[Category:Secretaries of State for Defence (UK)]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1997\u20132001]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2001\u20132005]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2005\u20132010]]\n[[Category:20th-century Scottish politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century Scottish politicians]]\n[[Category:20th-century Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:21st-century Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:Peers nominated by Gordon Brown]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British Labour politician}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n|name             = The Lord Browne of Ladyton\n|honorific-suffix = [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom|PC]]\n|image            = Official portrait of Lord Browne of Ladyton crop 3, 2019.jpg\n|caption          = Lord Browne of Ladyton in 2019\n|office           = [[Secretary of State for Scotland]]\n|primeminister    = [[Gordon Brown]]\n|term_start       = 28 June 2007\n|term_end         = 3 October 2008\n|predecessor      = [[Douglas Alexander]]\n|successor        = [[Jim Murphy]]\n|office1          = [[Secretary of State for Defence]]\n|primeminister1   = [[Tony Blair]]<br />[[Gordon Brown]]\n|term_start1      = 5 May 2006\n|term_end1        = 3 October 2008\n|predecessor1     = [[John Reid, Baron Reid of Cardowan|John Reid]]\n|successor1       = [[John Hutton, Baron Hutton of Furness|John Hutton]]\n|office2          = [[Chief Secretary to the Treasury]]\n|primeminister2   = [[Tony Blair]]\n|term_start2      = 6 May 2005\n|term_end2        = 5 May 2006\n|predecessor2     = [[Paul Boateng]]\n|successor2       = [[Stephen Timms]]\n|office3          = [[Minister of State for Immigration|Minister of State for Immigration, Citizenship and Counterterrorism]]\n|primeminister3   = [[Tony Blair]]\n|term_start3      = 1 April 2004\n|term_end3        = 6 May 2005\n|predecessor3     = [[Beverley Hughes]]\n|successor3       = [[Tony McNulty]] {{small|(Immigration, Citizenship and Nationality)}}\n|office4          = [[Minister of State|Minister of State for Work & Pensions]]\n|primeminister4   = [[Tony Blair]]\n|term_start4      = May 2003\n|term_end4      = 1 April 2004\n|office5          = [[Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State|Parliamentary under-Secretary of State for Northern Ireland]]\n|primeminister5   = [[Tony Blair]]\n|term_start5      = May 2001\n|term_end5       = May 2003\n|office6          = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[Kilmarnock and Loudoun (UK Parliament constituency)|Kilmarnock and Loudoun]]\n|term_start6      = 2 May 1997\n|term_end6        = 12 April 2010\n|predecessor6     = [[William McKelvey]]\n|successor6       = [[Cathy Jamieson]]\n|birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1952|3|22|df=y}}\n|birth_place      = [[Kilwinning]], Scotland\n|death_date       = \n|death_place      = \n|party            = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]\n|alma_mater       = [[University of Glasgow]]\n|religion         = [[Catholic Church|Roman Catholicism]]<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.independent.co.uk/uk/politics/article624201.ece |work=The Independent |location=London |title=Blair to meet Pope and fuel rumours of Catholic conversion |first1=Colin |last1=Brown |date=3 June 2006 |accessdate=1 May 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080111151131/http://news.independent.co.uk/uk/politics/article624201.ece |archivedate=11 January 2008 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n}}\n'''Desmond Henry Browne, Baron Browne of Ladyton''', {{post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|PC}} (born 22 March 1952) is a [[British people|British]] [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] [[politician]] who was the [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Kilmarnock and Loudoun (UK Parliament constituency)|Kilmarnock and Loudoun]] from [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997]] to [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010]]. He was a member of the [[Cabinet of the United Kingdom]] under [[Tony Blair]] and [[Gordon Brown]], until the latter moved him from both [[Secretary of State for Defence|Defence]] and [[Secretary of State for Scotland|Scottish Secretary]] in 2008.\n\n==Early life and education==\nBrowne was born in [[Kilwinning]], [[North Ayrshire]], lived in [[Stevenston]] for the early part of his life, and was educated at the Catholic St Michael's Academy in [[Kilwinning]] and later at the [[University of Glasgow]], where he received a [[Master of Laws|degree]] in [[Scots law|law]].\n\n==Legal career==\nHe started his legal career in 1974 as an apprentice [[solicitor]] with the firm James Campbell & Co. On qualifying in 1976 he became an assistant solicitor with Ross, Harper and Murphy, and was promoted to partner in 1980. He became a partner in McCluskey Browne in 1985 and a council member of the [[Law Society of Scotland]] 1988-1992. He was admitted as an [[advocate]] in 1993, practising at the Scottish bar until 1997. He worked mainly in child law.\n\n==Parliamentary career==\nBrowne contested the [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|parliamentary]] seat of [[Argyll and Bute (UK Parliament constituency)|Argyll and Bute]] at the [[1992 United Kingdom general election|1992 General Election]], and finished in fourth place behind the sitting [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrat]] MP [[Ray Michie, Baroness Michie of Gallanach|Ray Michie]]. He was elected to the [[Faculty of Advocates]] in 1993. Browne was selected to contest the safe Labour seat of Kilmarnock and Loudoun following the retirement of the sitting MP [[William McKelvey]]. Browne won the seat at the [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997 General Election]] with a majority of 7,256. He made his [[maiden speech]] on 20 June 1997.\n\nBrowne joined the [[Northern Ireland Affairs Select Committee]] on his election, and became the [[Parliamentary Private Secretary]] (PPS) to the [[Secretary of State for Scotland]] [[Donald Dewar]] in 1998. After Dewar left the Cabinet in 1999, to seek election as the [[First Minister of Scotland]], Browne remained in post as PPS to the new Secretary of State [[John Reid, Baron Reid of Cardowan|John Reid]]. In 2000 he became the PPS to the [[Minister of State]] at the [[Northern Ireland Office]].\n\nOn 27 November 2009, Browne announced his intention not seek election in the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010 general election]].<ref>{{cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/politics/8383783.stm | title=Des Browne to quit House of Commons after next election | work=[[BBC News Online]] | date=27 November 2009 | accessdate=2 January 2010 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091130055004/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/politics/8383783.stm | archive-date=30 November 2009 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nBrowne currently acts as convenor of the [[Top Level Group|Top Level Group of UK Parliamentarians for Multilateral Nuclear Disarmament and Non-proliferation]], established in October 2009.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2009/sep/08/nuclear-disarmament-cross-party-group | location=London | work=The Guardian | title=Nuclear-free world ultimate aim of new cross-party pressure group | first=Julian | last=Borger | date=8 September 2009 | access-date=14 December 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090630013226/http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2009/sep/08/nuclear-disarmament-cross-party-group | archive-date=30 June 2009 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Government Minister==\n[[File:Browne and gates.jpg|thumb|left|Browne meeting [[Robert Gates]] in Edinburgh during December 2007]]\nAfter the [[2001 United Kingdom general election|2001 General Election]] Browne entered [[Tony Blair]]'s government as the [[Parliamentary Under Secretary of State]] at the [[Northern Ireland Office]]. He was promoted to Minister of State at the [[Department for Work and Pensions]] in 2003, before moving to the [[Home Office]] in 2004 as the minister with responsibility for [[immigration]]. He joined the Cabinet following the [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005 General Election]] as the [[Chief Secretary to the Treasury]] and became a [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom|Member of the Privy Council]].\n\nBrowne was appointed [[Secretary of State for Defence]] on 5 May 2006. An advocate of the [[UK Trident programme]], in 2007 he successfully persuaded Parliament to vote to replace Trident. He came under criticism, however, after allowing the [[2007 Iranian seizure of Royal Navy personnel|Royal Navy personnel captured by Iran in spring 2007]] to sell and publish their stories.<ref name=\"profile\">{{cite news\n| work = BBC News\n| title = Profile: Des Browne\n| accessdate = 2009-01-02\n| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/4977660.stm\n| date = 15 April 2007\n| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20090327002951/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/4977660.stm\n| archive-date = 27 March 2009\n| url-status = live\n}}</ref> Under [[Tony Blair]]'s premiership, Browne was considered a supporter of the [[Chancellor of the Exchequer]] [[Gordon Brown]].<ref name=\"profile\"/><ref>{{cite news|author=Sarah Hall, political correspondent |url=https://www.theguardian.com/guardianpolitics/story/0,3605,1184117,00.html |title=Brown's man Browne gets poisoned chalice &#124; Politics |newspaper=The Guardian |accessdate=2013-03-13}}</ref> He received the additional responsibilities of [[Secretary of State for Scotland]] in June 2007 after Brown became Prime Minister.\n\nIn a free parliamentary vote on 20 May 2008, Browne voted for cutting the upper limit for abortions from 24 to 12 weeks, along with two other Catholic cabinet ministers [[Ruth Kelly]] and [[Paul Murphy, Baron Murphy of Torfaen|Paul Murphy]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/7409696.stm |title=UK &#124; UK Politics &#124; MPs back 24-week abortion limit |work=BBC News |date=2008-05-20 |accessdate=2013-03-13 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090330152748/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/7409696.stm |archive-date=30 March 2009 |url-status=live }}</ref> He returned to the backbenches in October 2008 following a cabinet reshuffle.\n\nBrowne [[List of witnesses of The Iraq Inquiry#January 25|gave evidence]] to the [[Iraq Inquiry]] on 25 January 2010.<ref name=\"Iraq Inquiry\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/8479074.stm|title=Ex-defence secretary speaks of strain of Iraq losses|date=25 January 2010|work=[[BBC News]]|publisher=BBC|accessdate=29 January 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Activities post-government==\nBrowne is vice chairman of the Washington, DC-based [http://www.nti.org/ Nuclear Threat Initiative], a non-profit, nonpartisan organization founded in 2001 by former U.S. Senator [http://www.nti.org/about/leadership-staff/sam-nunn/ Sam Nunn], who serves as co-chair and CEO, and CNN founder and philanthropist Ted Turner. NTI\u2019s mission is to strengthen global security by reducing the risk of use and preventing the spread of nuclear, biological and chemical weapons.\n\nBrowne is also convener of the [[European Leadership Network for Multilateral Nuclear Disarmament and Non-proliferation]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.europeanleadershipnetwork.org/des-browne_67.html |title=Members: Lord Desmond Browne of Ladyton |publisher=European Leadership Network for Multilateral Nuclear Disarmament and Non-proliferation |accessdate=25 February 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110726042056/http://www.europeanleadershipnetwork.org/des-browne_67.html |archive-date=26 July 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> and he is convener of the [[Top Level Group]] of UK Parliamentarians for Multilateral Nuclear Disarmament and Nonproliferation.<ref>{{cite report |url=http://www.basicint.org/publications/des-browne/2010/nuclear-policy-paper-no3 |title=Current NATO Nuclear Policy |author=Des Browne |date=November 2010 |publisher=Arms Control Association et al |accessdate=25 February 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101203074650/http://www.basicint.org/publications/des-browne/2010/nuclear-policy-paper-no3 |archivedate=3 December 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nDes Browne is a signatory of [[Global Zero (campaign)]], a non-profit international initiative for the elimination of all nuclear weapons worldwide.<ref>{{cite news|title=Group Offers Plan to Eliminate Nukes by 2030|url=http://www.globalzero.org/files/pdf/NYT_Jun29_09_AP_Syndicated.pdf|newspaper=The New York Times|date=29 June 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110513205939/http://www.globalzero.org/files/pdf/NYT_Jun29_09_AP_Syndicated.pdf|archivedate=13 May 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref>  Since its launch in Paris in December 2008,<ref>{{cite news|last=Corera|first=Gordon|title=Group seeks nuclear weapons ban|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/7774584.stm|newspaper=BBC|date=10 December 2008|access-date=30 March 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110728005425/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/7774584.stm|archive-date=28 July 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Global Zero (campaign)]] has grown to 300 leaders, including current and former heads of state, national security officials and military commanders, and 400,000 citizens worldwide; developed a practical step-by-step plan to eliminate nuclear weapons; launched an international student campaign with 75 campus chapters in eight countries; and produced an acclaimed documentary film, [[Countdown to Zero]], in partnership with [[Lawrence Bender]] and [[Participant Media]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Clift|first=Eleanor|title=A Good Start: 'Global Zero' reminds us that eradicating nuclear weapons should still be our ultimate goal.|url=http://www.newsweek.com/id/236133|newspaper=Newsweek|access-date=30 March 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100413113211/http://www.newsweek.com/id/236133|archive-date=13 April 2010|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Controversy over appointment as envoy to Sri Lanka===\nIn February 2009, Browne was appointed by PM Brown as the government's [[special envoy]] to [[Sri Lanka]]. However, the government of [[Mahinda Rajapaksa]], fighting the [[LTTE]] rebel group, rejected Browne's appointment, stating that the British government made the appointment unilaterally, without consultation with the Sri Lankan government.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/7887853.stm |title=''Sri Lanka rejects UK's new envoy'' |work=BBC News |date=2009-02-13 |accessdate=2013-03-13 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090213214657/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/7887853.stm |archive-date=13 February 2009 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.desbrownemp.co.uk Des Browne MP website]\n* {{Hansard-contribs | mr-des-browne | Des Browne }}\n*[http://www.mod.uk/DefenceInternet/AboutDefence/People/Ministers/SecretaryOfStateForDefence.htm Ministry of Defence official biography]\n*[http://www.mod.uk/DefenceInternet/AboutDefence/People/Speeches/SofS/UkDefenceStrategyInIraq.htm Speech on Iraq November 2006]\n*[http://www.mod.uk/DefenceInternet/AboutDefence/People/Speeches/SofS/RusiSpeech19thSep2006.htm Speech on Afghanistan September 2006]\n*[http://www.mod.uk/DefenceInternet/AboutDefence/People/Speeches/SofS/TheUnitedKingdomsNuclearDeterrentInThe21stCentury.htm Speech on the UK's Nuclear Deterrent January 2007]\n*[http://politics.guardian.co.uk/person/0,9290,-666,00.html Guardian Unlimited Politics - Ask Aristotle: Des Browne MP]\n*[https://www.theyworkforyou.com/mp/des_browne/kilmarnock_and_loudoun TheyWorkForYou.com - Des Browne MP]\n*[http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/uk-world-news/2009/01/21/a-day-of-destiny-by-des-browne-mp-86908-21057688/ Des Browne's article] in the ''[[Daily Record (Scotland)|Daily Record]]'', covering President Obama's Inauguration 20 January 2009\n*[http://www.globalzero.org Global Zero]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20100815063542/http://www.globalzero.org/en/who/des-browne Des Browne at Global Zero]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[William McKelvey]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[Kilmarnock and Loudoun (UK Parliament constituency)|Kilmarnock and Loudoun]]|years=[[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997]]\u2013[[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010]]}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Cathy Jamieson]]}}\n{