{"title_page": "October 26", "text_new": "{{pp-pc1}}\n{{pp-move-indef}}\n{{calendar}}\n{{This date in recent years}}\n{{Day}}\n\n==Events==\n*[[1185]] &ndash; The [[Uprising of Asen and Peter]] begins on the feast day of St. Demetrius of Thessaloniki and ends with the creation of the Second Bulgarian Empire.\n*[[1341]] &ndash; The [[Byzantine civil war of 1341\u201347]] formally begins with the proclamation of John VI Kantakouzenos as Byzantine Emperor.\n*[[1377]] &ndash; [[Tvrtko I of Bosnia|Tvrtko I]] is crowned the first king of Bosnia.\n*[[1520]] &ndash; [[Charles V, Holy Roman Emperor|Charles V]] is crowned as Holy Roman Emperor.\n*[[1597]] &ndash; Imjin War: Korean Admiral Yi Sun-sin routs the Japanese Navy of 300 ships with only 13 ships at the [[Battle of Myeongnyang]].\n*[[1640]] &ndash; The [[Treaty of Ripon]] is signed, restoring peace between Covenanter Scotland and King Charles.\n*[[1689]] &ndash; General Piccolomini of Austria [[Fire of Skopje 1689|burns down Skopje]] to prevent the spread of [[cholera]]; he died of the disease himself soon after.\n*[[1774]] &ndash; The first [[Continental Congress]] adjourns in Philadelphia.\n*[[1813]] &ndash; War of 1812: A combined force of British regulars, Canadian militia, and Mohawks defeat the Americans in the [[Battle of the Chateauguay]].\n*[[1825]] &ndash; The [[Erie Canal]] opens, allowing direct passage from the Hudson River to Lake Erie.\n*[[1859]] &ndash; The [[Royal Charter Storm]] kills at least eight hundred people in the British Isles.\n*[[1860]] &ndash; The [[Expedition of the Thousand]] ends when Giuseppe Garibaldi presents his conquests to King Victor Emmanuel of Sardinia.\n*[[1863]] &ndash; [[The Football Association]] is founded.\n*[[1892]] &ndash; [[Ida B. Wells]] publishes ''Southern Horrors: Lynch Law in All Its Phases.''\n*[[1905]] &ndash; King Oscar II recognizes the [[dissolution of the union between Norway and Sweden]].\n*[[1909]] &ndash; [[An Jung-geun]] assassinates Japan's Resident-General of Korea.\n*[[1912]] &ndash; [[First Balkan War]]: The Ottomans lose the cities of Thessaloniki and Skopje.\n*[[1917]] &ndash; First World War: Brazil [[Brazil during World War I|declares war]] on the Central Powers.\n*[[1918]] &ndash; [[Erich Ludendorff]], quartermaster-general of the Imperial German Army, is dismissed by Kaiser Wilhelm II for refusing to cooperate in peace negotiations.\n*[[1921]] &ndash; The [[Chicago Theatre]] opens.\n*[[1936]] &ndash; The first electric generator at [[Hoover Dam]] goes into full operation.\n*[[1942]] &ndash; World War II: In the [[Battle of the Santa Cruz Islands]] during the Guadalcanal Campaign, one U.S. aircraft carrier is sunk and another carrier is heavily damaged, while two Japanese carriers and one cruiser are heavily damaged.\n*[[1943]] &ndash; World War II: First flight of the [[Dornier Do 335]] \"Pfeil\".\n*[[1944]] &ndash; World War II: The [[Battle of Leyte Gulf]] ends with an overwhelming American victory.\n*[[1947]] &ndash; Kashmir conflict: The Maharaja of Kashmir and Jammu signs the [[Instrument of Accession (Jammu and Kashmir)|Instrument of Accession]] with India.\n*[[1955]] &ndash; After the last Allied troops have left the country, and following the provisions of the [[Austrian Independence Treaty]], Austria declares that it will never join a military alliance.\n*  1955   &ndash; [[Ngo Dinh Diem|Ng\u00f4 \u0110\u00ecnh Di\u1ec7m]] declares himself Premier of South Vietnam.\n*[[1956]] &ndash; [[Hungarian Revolution of 1956|Hungarian Revolution]]: In the towns of [[Mosonmagyar\u00f3v\u00e1r]] and [[Esztergom]], Hungarian [[\u00c1VH|secret police]] forces massacre civilians. As rebel strongholds in Budapest hold, fighting spreads throughout the country.  \n*[[1958]] &ndash; Pan American Airways makes the first commercial flight of the [[Boeing 707]] from New York City to Paris.\n*[[1967]] &ndash; [[Mohammad Reza Pahlavi]] crowns himself Emperor of Iran.\n*[[1968]] &ndash; Soviet cosmonaut [[Georgy Beregovoy]] pilots [[Soyuz 3]] into space for a four-day mission.\n*[[1970]] &ndash; [[Muhammad Ali]] boxes for the first time after Ali's three-year hiatus due to draft evasion.\n*[[1977]] &ndash; [[Ali Maow Maalin]], the last natural case of smallpox, develops a rash in Somalia. The World Health Organization and the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention consider this date to be the anniversary of the eradication of smallpox, the most spectacular success of vaccination.\n*[[1979]] &ndash; Park Chung-hee, President of South Korea, is [[Assassination of Park Chung-hee|assassinated]] by Korean CIA head Kim Jae-gyu.\n*[[1980]] &ndash; The [[Peter Muhlenberg Memorial]] in Washington, D.C. is dedicated.<ref>{{cite web|first=John|last=Kelly|title=A park on Connecticut Avenue NW has a statue of John Muhlenberg. Why?|work=[[The Washington Post]]|date=July 7, 2018|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/a-park-on-connecticut-avenue-nw-has-a-statue-of-john-muhlenberg-why/2018/07/07/ad91b498-813f-11e8-b851-5319c08f7cee_story.html|accessdate=October 28, 2019}}</ref>\n*[[1985]] &ndash; The Australian government returns ownership of [[Uluru]] to the local Pitjantjatjara Aboriginals.\n*[[1989]] &ndash; [[China Airlines Flight 204]] crashes after take off from [[Hualien Airport]] in Taiwan, killing all 54 people on board.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19891026-0|title=ASN Aircraft accident Boeing 737-209 B-180 Hualien Airport (HUN)|last=Ranter|first=Harro|website=aviation-safety.net|access-date=2019-08-25}}</ref>\n*[[1991]] &ndash; Three months after the end of the [[Ten-Day War]], the last soldier of the Yugoslav People's Army leaves the territory of the Republic of Slovenia.\n*[[1994]] &ndash; Jordan and Israel sign [[Israel\u2013Jordan peace treaty|a peace treaty]].\n*[[1995]] &ndash; Mossad agents assassinate Islamic Jihad leader [[Fathi Shaqaqi]] in his hotel in Malta.\n*  1995   &ndash; An avalanche hits the Icelandic village [[Flateyri]], destroying 29 homes and burying 45 people, 20 of whom died.<ref>http://timarit.is/view_page_init.jsp?pageId=1194992</ref>\n*[[1999]] &ndash; Britain's House of Lords [[House of Lords Act 1999|votes to end the right]] of hereditary peers to vote in Britain's upper chamber of Parliament.\n*[[2000]] &ndash; A wave of protests forces Robert Gu\u00e9\u00ef to step down as president after the [[Ivorian presidential election, 2000|Ivorian presidential election]].\n*2000 &ndash; The [[Sony]] [[PlayStation 2]] is launched in North American markets with 27 launch titles.\n*[[2001]] &ndash; The United States passes the [[USA PATRIOT Act]] into law.\n*[[2002]] &ndash; Approximately 50 Chechen terrorists and 150 hostages die when Russian special forces troops [[Moscow theater hostage crisis|storm a theater building]] in Moscow, which had been occupied by the terrorists during a musical performance three days before.\n*[[2003]] &ndash; The [[Cedar Fire (2003)|Cedar Fire]], the third-largest fire in California history, kills 15 people, consumes {{convert|250,000|acre|km2}}, and destroys 2,200 homes around San Diego.\n*[[2015]] &ndash; A 7.5 magnitude [[October 2015 Hindu Kush earthquake|earthquake]] strikes in the Hindu Kush mountain range in northeastern Afghanistan, killing 398 people and leaving 2,536 people injured.\n*[[2016]] &ndash; [[October 2016 Central Italy earthquakes|An earthquake of magnitude 6.6]] strikes central Italy.\n\n==Births==\n*[[1416]] &ndash; [[Edmund Grey, 1st Earl of Kent]], English politician, [[Lord High Treasurer]] (d. 1490)\n*[[1427]] &ndash; [[Sigismund, Archduke of Austria]] (d. 1496)\n*[[1431]] &ndash; [[Ercole I d'Este, Duke of Ferrara]], Italian politician (d. 1505)\n*[[1473]] &ndash; [[Frederick of Saxony (Teutonic Knight)|Friedrich of Saxony]], Grand Master of the Teutonic Knights (d. 1510)\n*[[1483]] &ndash; [[Hans Buchner]], German Renaissance composer (d. 1538)\n*[[1491]] &ndash; [[Zhengde Emperor]] of China (d. 1521)\n*[[1518]] &ndash; [[John Basset (1518\u20131541)|John Basset]], Devonshire gentleman (d. 1541)\n*[[1529]] &ndash; [[Anna of Hesse]], princess of Hesse (d. 1591)\n*[[1551]] &ndash; [[Charlotte de Sauve]], French courtesan (d. 1617)\n*[[1556]] &ndash; [[Ahmad Baba al Massufi]], Malian academic (d. 1627)\n*[[1564]] &ndash; [[Hans Leo Hassler]], German organist and composer (d. 1612)\n*[[1609]] &ndash; [[William Sprague (1609\u20131675)|William Sprague]], English-American settler, co-founded [[Charlestown, Massachusetts]] (d. 1675)\n*[[1612]] &ndash; [[Henry Wilmot, 1st Earl of Rochester]] (d. 1658)\n*[[1673]] &ndash; [[Dimitrie Cantemir]], Moldavian geographer, historian, and philosopher (d. 1723)\n*[[1684]] &ndash; [[Kurt Christoph Graf von Schwerin]], Prussian field marshal (d. 1757)\n*[[1685]] &ndash; [[Domenico Scarlatti]], Italian [[harpsichord]] player and composer (d. 1757)\n*[[1694]] &ndash; [[Johan Helmich Roman]], Swedish composer and academic (d. 1758)\n*[[1747]] &ndash; [[Ivan Mane Jarnovi\u0107]], Italian violinist and composer (d. 1804)\n*[[1757]] &ndash; [[Karl Leonhard Reinhold]], Austrian philosopher and academic (d. 1823)\n*[[1759]] &ndash; [[Georges Danton]], French lawyer and politician, [[Ministry of Justice (France)|French Minister of Justice]] (d. 1794)\n*[[1768]] &ndash; [[Eustachy Erazm Sanguszko]], Polish general and politician (d. 1844)\n*[[1794]] &ndash; [[Konstantin Thon]], Russian architect, designed the [[Grand Kremlin Palace]] and the [[Cathedral of Christ the Saviour]] (d. 1881)\n*[[1795]] &ndash; [[Nikolaos Mantzaros]], Greek composer and theorist (d. 1872)\n*[[1797]] &ndash; [[Giuditta Pasta]], Italian soprano (d. 1865)\n*[[1799]] &ndash; [[Margaret Agnes Bunn]], Scottish actress (d. 1883)\n*[[1800]] &ndash; [[Helmuth von Moltke the Elder]], Prussian field marshal (d. 1891)\n*[[1802]] &ndash; [[Miguel I of Portugal]] (d. 1866)\n*[[1803]] &ndash; [[Joseph Hansom]], English architect and publisher, designed [[Birmingham Town Hall]] (d. 1882)\n*[[1842]] &ndash; [[Vasily Vereshchagin]], Russian soldier and painter (d. 1904)\n*[[1849]] &ndash; [[Ferdinand Georg Frobenius]], German mathematician and academic (d. 1917)\n*[[1850]] &ndash; [[Grigore Tocilescu]], Romanian archaeologist and historian (d. 1909)\n*[[1854]] &ndash; [[C. W. Post]], American businessman, founded [[Post Foods]] (d. 1914)\n*[[1860]] &ndash; [[Frank Eaton]], American marshal and author (d. 1958)\n*[[1865]] &ndash; [[Benjamin Guggenheim]], American businessman (d. 1912)\n*[[1869]] &ndash; [[Washington Lu\u00eds]], Brazilian lawyer and politician, 13th [[President of Brazil]] (d. 1957)\n*[[1871]] &ndash; [[Guillermo Kahlo]], German-Mexican photographer (d. 1941)\n*[[1873]] &ndash; [[A. K. Fazlul Huq]], Bangladeshi-Pakistani lawyer and politician, 5th [[Ministry of Interior (Pakistan)|Pakistani Minister of Interior]] (d. 1962)\n*  1873   &ndash; [[Thorvald Stauning]], Danish union leader and politician, 24th [[Prime Minister of Denmark]] (d. 1942)\n*[[1874]] &ndash; [[Martin Lowry]], English chemist and academic (d. 1936)\n*  1874   &ndash; [[Abby Aldrich Rockefeller]], American philanthropist, founded the [[Museum of Modern Art]] (d. 1948)\n*[[1875]] &ndash; [[H.B. Warner]], English actor (d. 1958)\n*[[1880]] &ndash; [[Andrei Bely]], Russian novelist, poet, and critic (d. 1934)\n*[[1881]] &ndash; [[Louis Bastien (cyclist)|Louis Bastien]], French cyclist and fencer (d. 1963)\n*[[1883]] &ndash; [[Napoleon Hill]], American philosopher and author (d. 1970)\n*  1883   &ndash; [[Paul Pilgrim]], American runner (d. 1958)\n*[[1884]] &ndash; [[William Hogenson]], American sprinter (d. 1965)\n*[[1890]] &ndash; [[Ganesh Shankar Vidyarthi]], Indian journalist and politician (d. 1931)\n*[[1893]] &ndash; [[Milo\u0161 Crnjanski]], Serbian poet and author (d. 1977)\n*[[1894]] &ndash; [[Florence Nagle]], English trainer and breeder of [[Horse racing|racehorses]] (d. 1988)\n*[[1899]] &ndash; [[Judy Johnson]], American baseball player and coach (d. 1989)\n*[[1900]] &ndash; [[Ibrahim Abboud]], Sudanese politician and general, 1st [[President of Sudan]] (d. 1983)<ref>{{cite book|title=Reference Library of Arab America: International Arab figures|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Cy0OAQAAMAAJ|year=1999|publisher=Gale Group|isbn=978-0-7876-4176-4}}</ref>\n*  1900   &ndash; [[Karin Boye]], Swedish poet and novelist (d. 1941)<ref>{{cite book|author=Anne Commire|title=Women in World History|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=i0MOAQAAMAAJ|date=8 October 1999|publisher=Gale|isbn=978-0-7876-4061-3}}</ref>\n*[[1902]] &ndash; [[Beryl Markham]], Kenyan horse trainer and author (d. 1986)\n*  1902   &ndash; [[Jack Sharkey]], American boxer and referee (d. 1994)\n*  1902   &ndash; [[Henrietta Hill Swope]], American astronomer and academic (d. 1980)\n*[[1903]] &ndash; [[Mahn Ba Khaing]], Burmese politician (d. 1947)\n*[[1905]] &ndash; [[George Bernard Flahiff]], Canadian cardinal (d. 1989)\n*[[1906]] &ndash; [[Primo Carnera]], Italian boxer and actor (d. 1967)\n*[[1909]] &ndash; [[Ignace Lepp]], French psychologist and author (d. 1966)\n*  1909   &ndash; [[Dante Quinterno]], Argentinian author and illustrator (d. 2003)\n*[[1910]] &ndash; [[John Krol]], American cardinal (d. 1996)\n*[[1911]] &ndash; [[Sid Gillman]], American football player and coach (d. 2003)\n*  1911   &ndash; [[Mahalia Jackson]], American singer (d. 1972)\n*  1911   &ndash; [[Sorley MacLean]], Scottish poet and educator (d. 1996)\n*[[1912]] &ndash; [[Don Siegel]], American director and producer (d. 1991)\n*[[1913]] &ndash; [[Charlie Barnet]], American saxophonist, composer, and bandleader (d. 1991)\n*[[1914]] &ndash; [[Jackie Coogan]], American actor and director (d. 1984)\n*[[1915]] &ndash; [[Ray Crawford]], American race car driver, fighter ace, test pilot, and businessman (d. 1996)\n*  1915   &ndash; [[Joe Fry]], English race car driver (d. 1950)\n*[[1916]] &ndash; [[Fran\u00e7ois Mitterrand]], French lawyer and politician, 21st [[President of France]] (d. 1996)\n*  1916