attle/news-story/b3e4c51b5e5ee391e934ae375056d9cd |work=Herald Sun |location=Melbourne |date=October 27, 2014 |access-date=November 6, 2018}}</ref>\n*  2014   &ndash; [[Jeff Robinson (starting pitcher)|Jeff Robinson]], American baseball player (b. 1961)\n*  2014   &ndash; [[Gordy Soltau]], American football player and sportscaster (b. 1925)\n*  2014   &ndash; [[Oscar Taveras]], Dominican baseball player (b. 1992)\n*[[2015]] &ndash; [[Willis Carto]], American activist and theorist (b. 1926) \n*  2015   &ndash; [[Leo Kadanoff]], American physicist and academic (b. 1937)\n*  2015   &ndash; [[Giuseppe Nazzaro]], Italian-Syrian bishop and theologian (b. 1937)\n*[[2017]] &ndash; [[Ali Ashraf Darvishian]], Iranian novelist, short story writer and academic. (b. 1941)\n<!-- Do not add people without Wikipedia articles to this list. Do not trust \"this year in history\" websites for accurate date information. Do not link multiple occurrences of the same year, just link the first occurrence. -->\n\n==Holidays and observances==\n*[[Accession Day (Jammu and Kashmir)]] \n*[[Angam Day]] ([[Public holidays in Nauru|Nauru]])\n*[[Armed Forces Day (Benin)]]\n*Christian [[feast day]]:\n**[[Alfred the Great]] ([[Catholic Church]], [[Calendar of saints (Church of England)|Anglican Church]], [[Eastern Orthodox Church]])\n**[[Amandus of Strasbourg]]\n**[[Be\u00f3\u00e1n of Mortlach|Be\u00f3\u00e1n (Bean) of Mortlach]]\n**[[Beatification|Blessed]] [[Celine Borzecka]]\n**[[Cedd]]\n**[[Cuthbert of Canterbury]]\n**[[Demetrius of Thessaloniki]]\n**[[Eadfrith of Leominster]]\n**[[Eata of Hexham]]\n**Pope [[Pope Evaristus|Evaristus (Aristus)]]\n**[[Fulk of Pavia]] ([[Roman Catholic Church]])\n**[[Philipp Nicolai]], [[Johann Heermann]] and [[Paul Gerhardt]] ([[Lutheran Church]])\n**[[Saint Quadragesimus|Quadragesimus]]\n**[[Quodvultdeus]]\n**[[Rusticus of Narbonne]]\n**[[Witta of B\u00fcraburg|Witta (Albinus) of B\u00fcraburg]]\n**[[October 26 (Eastern Orthodox liturgics)|Eastern Orthodox liturgics]]\n*[[Culture of Austria#Public holidays|National Day]], celebrates the anniversary of the [[Declaration of Neutrality]] in 1955. (Austria)\n*[[Intersex Awareness Day]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://intersexday.org/en/|title=Intersex Day - Intersex Awareness Day, 26 Oct, & Intersex Day of Solidarity, 8 Nov|last=Carpenter|first=Morgan|date=2019-10-25|website=Intersex Day|language=en|access-date=2019-12-14}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons}}\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/october/26 BBC: On This Day]\n* {{NYT On this day|month=10|day=26}}\n* [http://canadachannel.ca/todayincanadianhistory/index.php/October_26 Today in Canadian History]\n\n{{months}}\n\n[[Category:Days of the year]]\n[[Category:October]]\n", "name_user": "Cnwilliams", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguated:NCT\u2192NCT (group)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/October_26"}
{"title_page": "Anne Begg", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=January 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2013}}\n\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| image=Anne Addresses May Day Rally in 2008.JPG<!-- only free-content images are allowed for depicting living people - see [[WP:NONFREE]] --> |\n| image_size = 250px\n| name = Dame Anne Begg\n| honorific-suffix =[[Order of the British Empire|DBE]]\n| office = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] <br /> for [[Aberdeen South (UK Parliament constituency)|Aberdeen South]]\n| parliament =\n| predecessor = [[Raymond Robertson (politician)|Raymond Robertson]]\n| successor = [[Callum McCaig]]\n| term_start = 1 May 1997\n| term_end = 30 March 2015\n| birth_name = Margaret Anne Begg\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1955|12|6|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Brechin]], [[Angus, Scotland]]\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| nationality = [[United Kingdom|British]]\n| party = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]\n| alma_mater = [[University of Aberdeen]]\n| website = [http://www.annebegg.com www.annebegg.com]}}\n\n'''Dame Margaret Anne Begg'''<ref>[http://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/article/oupww/whoswho/U7069 Profile], ukwhoswho.com; accessed 31 August 2014.</ref> [[Order of the British Empire|DBE]] (born 6 December 1955) is a [[British people|British]] [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] [[politician]], who served as the [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Aberdeen South (UK Parliament constituency)|Aberdeen South]] between [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997]] and [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015]].\n\nShe was the first permanent [[wheelchair]] user in the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] since 1880.<ref>{{cite news|title=Anne Begg profile|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/2051216.stm|date=21 October 2002|work=BBC News|first=Labour|last=MP|access-date=8 September 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040501160140/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/2051216.stm|archive-date=1 May 2004|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>[http://www.turtlebunbury.com/history/history_heroes/hist_hero_arthur_kavanagh.html Profile] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140309061743/http://www.turtlebunbury.com/history/history_heroes/hist_hero_arthur_kavanagh.html |date=9 March 2014 }}, turtlebunbury.com; accessed 31 August 2014.</ref>\n\n==Education and early career==\nBegg was educated at the Damacre Primary School (Brechin), [[Brechin High School]] and the [[University of Aberdeen]] where she earned an [[Master of Arts (Scotland)|MA]] in [[History]] and [[Politics]].<ref name=\"b\">{{cite news|title=VOTE 2001|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/hi/english/static/vote2001/candidates/candidates/0/00401.stm|accessdate=18 September 2007|work=BBC News|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040619175118/http://news.bbc.co.uk/hi/english/static/vote2001/candidates/candidates/0/00401.stm|archive-date=19 June 2004|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"c\">{{cite web|title=Biography of Anne Begg MP|url=http://www.annebegg.info/about.htm|accessdate=18 September 2007|publisher=Anne Begg profile|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071025050331/http://www.annebegg.info/about.htm|archivedate=25 October 2007|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> From Aberdeen College of Education (now the Faculty of Education of the University of Aberdeen), she gained a Secondary Teaching Certificate in 1978.\n\nFrom 1978, she taught history and [[English language|English]] at the [[Webster's High School]] in [[Kirriemuir]].<ref name=\"c\"/> She joined the Labour Party in 1983.<ref>{{cite web|work=ePolitix.com|title=Anne Begg profile|url=http://www.epolitix.com/EN/MPWebsites/Anne+Begg/192899D8-2381-4C12-87BB-2E6F475AD317.htm|accessdate=18 September 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080117113436/http://www.epolitix.com/EN/MPWebsites/Anne+Begg/192899D8-2381-4C12-87BB-2E6F475AD317.htm|archive-date=17 January 2008|url-status=live}}</ref> In 1988, she became the principal teacher of English at the [[Arbroath]] Academy.<ref name=\"c\"/> In the same year she won the Disabled Scot of the Year Award.<ref name=\"b\"/>\n\nBegg has been a [[wheelchair]] user since 1984 as she lives with the degenerative [[Gaucher's disease]].<ref name=\"c\"/> She was the second full-time user of a wheelchair elected to the House of Commons, after [[Arthur MacMorrough Kavanagh]] who was first elected in 1868 and sat until 1880.<ref>{{cite web|title=Interview with Anne Begg, Member of Parliament, UK |url=http://www.disabilityworld.org/12-02_05/gov/begginterview.shtml |accessdate=18 September 2007 |publisher=Disability World |date=16 June 2004 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061002152947/http://www.disabilityworld.org/12-02_05/gov/begginterview.shtml |archivedate=2 October 2006 }}</ref>\n\n==Parliamentary career==\nBegg was selected to stand for election for Labour through an [[all-women shortlists|all-women shortlist]].<ref>[http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4158/is_19960109/ai_n9634358?tag=content;col1 Find Articles]{{dead link|date=September 2010}}</ref> and when Aberdeen South (like many seats) fell to Labour in their [[landslide]] victory at the [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997 general election]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/videonation/articles/u/uk_mp.shtml|title=BBC - Video Nation - MP by Anne Begg|website=www.bbc.co.uk|access-date=4 March 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151019004157/http://www.bbc.co.uk/videonation/articles/u/uk_mp.shtml|archive-date=19 October 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> She defeated the Conservative [[Parliamentary Under Secretary of State]] at the [[Scottish Office]] [[Raymond Robertson (politician)|Raymond Robertson]].<ref>{{cite news|title=VOTE 2001 \u2013 RESULTS & CONSTITUENCIES \u2013 Aberdeen South|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/hi/english/static/vote2001/results_constituencies/constituencies/004.stm|accessdate=18 September 2007|work=BBC News|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060626181039/http://news.bbc.co.uk/hi/english/static/vote2001/results_constituencies/constituencies/004.stm|archive-date=26 June 2006|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2001, she became the first Labour MP to retain the Aberdeen South seat.\n\nShe made her [[maiden speech]] on 21 May 1997.<ref>{{cite web|title=House of Commons Hansard Debates for 21 May 1997 (pt 27) |url=https://publications.parliament.uk/cgi-bin/newhtml_hl?DB=semukparl&STEMMER=en&WORDS=begg%20ann&ALL=&ANY=&PHRASE=&CATEGORIES=&SIMPLE=&SPEAKER=begg%20anne&COLOUR=red&STYLE=s&ANCHOR=70521-27_spnew8&URL=/pa/cm199798/cmhansrd/vo970521/debtext/70521-27.htm#70521-27_spnew8 |accessdate=18 September 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071026053028/http://www.publications.parliament.uk/cgi-bin/newhtml_hl?DB=semukparl&STEMMER=en&WORDS=begg%20ann&ALL=&ANY=&PHRASE=&CATEGORIES=&SIMPLE=&SPEAKER=begg%20anne&COLOUR=red&STYLE=s&ANCHOR=70521-27_spnew8&URL=%2Fpa%2Fcm199798%2Fcmhansrd%2Fvo970521%2Fdebtext%2F70521-27.htm |archivedate=26 October 2007 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.turtlebunbury.com/history/history_heroes/hist_hero_arthur_kavanagh.html|title=Turtle Bunbury - Award-winning travel writer, historian and author based in Ireland|website=www.turtlebunbury.com|access-date=6 October 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140309061743/http://www.turtlebunbury.com/history/history_heroes/hist_hero_arthur_kavanagh.html|archive-date=9 March 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> She was Secretary of the All-Party [[BBC]] Group and Chair of the All Party Group on Equalities, the All Party Oil and Gas Industry Group, the All Party Group on Chronic Pain, and the All Party Commercial Radio group.<ref>{{cite web|title=Anne Begg biography |url=http://iwc2.labouronline.org/168348/biography |accessdate=19 December 2008 |publisher=Labour Party |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090210164041/http://iwc2.labouronline.org/168348/biography |archivedate=10 February 2009 }}</ref> \nShe was a member of the House of Commons Chairmen's Panel<ref name=\"c\"/> and Vice Chair of the Speaker's Conference which was tasked with looking at the under representation of women, ethnic minorities and disabled people in the House of Commons.<ref>{{cite web|title=Speaker's Conference:Membership |url=http://www.parliament.uk/business/speakers_conference/membership.cfm |accessdate=19 December 2008 |publisher=UK Parliament |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090522085958/http://www.parliament.uk/business/speakers_conference/membership.cfm |archivedate=22 May 2009 }}</ref> She  chaired the [[Work and Pensions Select Committee]] from July 2010.\n\nBegg lost her seat in the [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015 general election]] to [[Callum McCaig]] of the [[Scottish National Party]].\n\n===Votes and political views===\nBegg voted in favour of a bill that banned smoking in restaurants in April 2003.<ref>{{cite web|title=House of Commons Hansard Debates for 14 April 2003 (pt 15)|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200203/cmhansrd/vo030414/debtext/30414-15.htm#30414-15_div162|accessdate=17 September 2007|publisher=UK Parliament|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070630224840/http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200203/cmhansrd/vo030414/debtext/30414-15.htm#30414-15_div162|archive-date=30 June 2007|url-status=live}}</ref> In December 2004 and October 2005, she voted in favour of the [[Identity Cards Act 2006|Identity Cards Bill]].<ref>{{cite web|title=House of Commons Hansard Debates for 20 December 2004 (pt 42)|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200405/cmhansrd/vo041220/debtext/41220-42.htm#41220-42_div24|accessdate=17 September 2007|publisher=UK Parliament|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071123131524/http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200405/cmhansrd/vo041220/debtext/41220-42.htm#41220-42_div24|archive-date=23 November 2007|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=House of Commons Hansard Debates for 18 October 2005 (pt 35)|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200506/cmhansrd/vo051018/debtext/51018-35.htm#51018-35_div60|accessdate=17 September 2007|publisher=UK Parliament|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071123131539/http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200506/cmhansrd/vo051018/debtext/51018-35.htm#51018-35_div60|archive-date=23 November 2007|url-status=live}}</ref> She voted in favour of allowing unmarried heterosexual and homosexual couples to adopt,<ref>{{cite web|title=House of Commons Hansard Debates for 4 Nov 2002 (pt 28)|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200102/cmhansrd/vo021104/debtext/21104-28.htm#21104-28_div345|accessdate=17 September 2007|publisher=UK Parliament|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071123131454/http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200102/cmhansrd/vo021104/debtext/21104-28.htm#21104-28_div345|archive-date=23 November 2007|url-status=live}}</ref> and in favour of the [[Civil Partnership Act 2004|Civil Partnership Bill]].<ref>{{cite web|title=House of Commons Hansard Debates for 12 October 2004 (pt 34)|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200304/cmhansrd/vo041012/debtext/41012-34.htm#41012-34_div256|accessdate=17 September 2007|publisher=UK Parliament|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070630192558/http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200304/cmhansrd/vo041012/debtext/41012-34.htm#41012-34_div256|archive-date=30 June 2007|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2002, she voted to ban the hunting of wild mammals with dogs.<ref>{{cite web|title=House of Commons Hansard Debates for 18 March 2002 (pt 40)|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200102/cmhansrd/vo020318/debtext/20318-40.htm#20318-40_div199|accessdate=17 September 2007|publisher=UK Parliament|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070523034243/http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200102/cmhansrd/vo020318/debtext/20318-40.htm#20318-40_div199|archive-date=23 May 2007|url-status=live}}</ref> She voted in favour of the [[NHS Foundation Trust]] proposal<ref>{{cite web|title=House of Commons Hansard Debates for 8 July 2003 (pt 27)|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200203/cmhansrd/vo030708/debtext/30708-27.htm#30708-27_div280|accessdate=17 September 2007|publisher=UK Parliament|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071123131459/http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200203/cmhansrd/vo030708/debtext/30708-27.htm#30708-27_div280|archive-date=23 November 2007|url-status=live}}</ref> and against the [[British replacement of the Trident system|replacement of the Trident system]].<ref>{{cite web|title=House of Commons Hansard Debates for 14 March 2007 (pt 0022)|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200607/cmhansrd/cm070314/debtext/70314-0022.htm#07031475002466|accessdate=17 September 2007|publisher=UK Parliament|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071123131544/http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200607/cmhansrd/cm070314/debtext/70314-0022.htm#07031475002466|archive-date=23 November 2007|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nShe voted in favour of adding clauses to a bill that allow the Secretary of State to detain indefinitely, pending deportation, anyone he suspects is a terrorist, even if the law forbids that person's deportation from ever taking place.<ref>{{cite web | title=House of Commons Hansard Debates for 21 November 2001 (pt 28)|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200102/cmhansrd/vo011121/debtext/11121-28.htm#11121-28_div76|accessdate=17 September 2007|publisher=UK Parliament|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070827013607/http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200102/cmhansrd/vo011121/debtext/11121-28.htm|archivedate=27 August 2007|url-status=live}}</ref> She voted against allowing people detained at a police station to be fingerprinted and searched for identifying birthmarks unless it is in connection with a terrorism investigation.<ref>{{cite web|title=House of Commons Hansard Debates for 26 November 2001 (pt 30)|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200102/cmhansrd/vo011126/debtext/11126-30.htm#11126-30_div82|accessdate=17 September 2007|publisher=UK Parliament|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071123131449/http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200102/cmhansrd/vo011126/debtext/11126-30.htm#11126-30_div82|archive-date=23 November 2007|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2003, she voted against the declaration of war against [[Iraq]].<ref>{{cite web|title=House of Commons Hansard Debates for 18 Mar 2003 (pt 48)|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200203/cmhansrd/vo030318/debtext/30318-48.htm#30318-48_div118|accessdate=17 September 2007|publisher=UK Parliament|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070821064145/http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200203/cmhansrd/vo030318/debtext/30318-48.htm| archivedate=21 August 2007|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2003, she voted against a motion that would have recalled the Prime Minister's assertion that Iraq had weapons of mass destruction that could be used at 45 minutes' notice, and launching an independent inquiry into the intelligence received and the decisions that were based on it.<ref>{{cite web|title=House of Commons Hansard Debates for 4 Jun 2003 (pt 25)|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200203/cmhansrd/vo030604/debtext/30604-25.htm#30604-25_div217|accessdate=17 September 2007|publisher=UK Parliament|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070703064015/http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200203/cmhansrd/vo030604/debtext/30604-25.htm#30604-25_div217|archive-date=3 July 2007|url-status=live}}</ref> In June 2007, she voted against a motion calling for an independent inquiry by a committee of [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom|Privy Counsellors]] into the Iraq War.<ref>{{cite web|title=House of Commons Hansard Debates for 11 June 2007 (pt 0015)|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200607/cmhansrd/cm070611/debtext/70611-0015.htm#07061179001224|accessdate=17 September 2007|publisher=UK Parliament|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071123131554/http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200607/cmhansrd/cm070611/debtext/70611-0015.htm#07061179001224|archive-date=23 November 2007|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2008, Begg was one of 18 MPs who signed a Commons motion backing a Team GB football team at the 2012 Olympics, saying football \"should not be any different from other competing sports and our young talent should be allowed to show their skills on the world stage\". The football governing bodies of Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland are all opposed to a Great Britain team, fearing it would stop them competing as individual nations in future tournaments. {{citation needed|date=August 2014}}\n\nDuring the 2009 MPs expenses scandal, Begg was one of the first Scottish MPs to take the step of publishing all of her claims under the Additional Costs Allowance on her website before they were released by the House of Commons authorities saying that it was \"important people can see how MPs spend taxpayers' money.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Doran's books reveal repairs expenditure|url=http://www.pressandjournal.co.uk/Article.aspx/1222257|date=19 May 2009|publisher=The Press and Journal|access-date=19 May 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120306035945/http://www.pressandjournal.co.uk/Article.aspx/1222257|archive-date=6 March 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2011, Begg crossed swords with [[Philip Davies]], Conservative MP for Shipley, over the issue of disabled people being allowed to work for less than minimum wage if they so choose in order to establish themselves in employment. Davies explained that he was representing the views of constituents anxious to get a foothold on the earnings ladder, but Begg believed that this was simply an attempt to discriminate against disabled people.<ref>{{cite news|title=Tory MP Philip Davies: disabled people could work for less pay|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2011/jun/17/tory-philip-davies-disabled-people-work|location=London, UK|work=The Guardian|first=Allegra|last=Stratton|date=17 June 2011|access-date=13 December 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161221084106/https://www.theguardian.com/society/2011/jun/17/tory-philip-davies-disabled-people-work|archive-date=21 December 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===National campaigns===\nBegg is a vocal campaigner for allowing embryonic stem cells to be used in the research for treatments of diseases, including currently incurable conditions such as Alzheimer's and Parkinson's Disease.<ref>{{cite news| title=UK to extend embyo research| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/sci/tech/1078672.stm| accessdate=9 January 2009| work=BBC News| date=19 December 2000| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080320203944/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/sci/tech/1078672.stm| archive-date=20 March 2008| url-status=live}}</ref> She has also been heavily involved in lobbying the [[Department of Health]] against an all-out ban on the pain-relief drug [[co-proxamol]], used by many people who suffer from chronic pain conditions.<ref>{{cite web| title=Co-proxamol row heats up as MPs deman U-turn| url=http://www.pulsetoday.co.uk/story.asp?storycode=4011641| accessdate=9 January 2009| publisher=Pulse| date=19 January 2007| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110522034955/http://www.pulsetoday.co.uk/story.asp?storycode=4011641| archive-date=22 May 2011| url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nShe has also taken the lead in lobbying the government on issues such as the Seafarer's Earnings Deduction<ref>{{cite web|title=Minister hints seafarers will escape tax blow|url=http://www.pressandjournal.co.uk/Article.aspx/887604?UserKey&UserKey=|accessdate=20 January 2009|publisher=The Press and Journal|date=16 October 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120212233915/http://www.pressandjournal.co.uk/Article.aspx/887604?UserKey&UserKey=|archive-date=12 February 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> and compensation for trawlermen who lost their livelihoods during the [[Cod Wars]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Cod War fishermen in line for extra payouts|url=http://www.pressandjournal.co.uk/Article.aspx/984625?UserKey=|accessdate=20 January 2009|date=12 December 2008|publisher=the Press and Journal|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120403033929/http://www.pressandjournal.co.uk/Article.aspx/984625?UserKey=|archive-date=3 April 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> In the 2009 Budget, Begg also won a concession from the [[Chancellor of the Exchequer]], [[Alistair Darling]] [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MP]], that \"those caring responsibilities of grandparents of working age will count towards their entitlement to the basic state pension.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Government's plans 'a missed opportunity'|url=http://www.pressandjournal.co.uk/Article.aspx/1184362?UserKey==|accessdate=23 April 2009|publisher=Press and Journal|date=23 April 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120403033940/http://www.pressandjournal.co.uk/Article.aspx/1184362?UserKey==|archive-date=3 April 2012|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Begg had campaigned for grandparents of working age to receive National Insurance Credits in recognition of the fact that their caring role may impact on their contributions to their state pension entitlement.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ways and Means \u2013 Financial Statement| url=https://www.theyworkforyou.com/debates/?id=2009-04-22a.237.0&s=speaker%3A10153#g237.2=|accessdate=23 April 2009|publisher=TheyWorkForYou|date=22 April 2009}}</ref>\n\nOn the floor of the House of Commons, Begg vehemently criticised fraudsters who take advantage of vulnerable people in her constituency through the use of mail scams<ref>{{cite news|title=Mail scams concerns to be raised|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/north_east/7254416.stm|accessdate=9 January 2009|work=BBC News|date=20 February 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090412221731/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/north_east/7254416.stm|archive-date=12 April 2009|url-status=live}}</ref> and pyramid schemes.<ref>{{cite web|title='Women Empowering Women' scheme|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200102/cmhansrd/vo011127/debtext/11127-35.htm|accessdate=9 January 2009|publisher=UK Parliament|date=27 November 2001|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090627000134/http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200102/cmhansrd/vo011127/debtext/11127-35.htm|archive-date=27 June 2009|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Local campaigns===\nBegg was one of the most vociferous critics of Aberdeen City Council during the budget crisis of 2008, which led to many of her constituents having their services cut.<ref>{{cite news|title=\u00a350m cuts fear for city council|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/north_east/7509919.stm| accessdate=20 January 2009|date=16 July 2008|work=BBC News}}</ref> In 2009 she criticised as \"draconian\" a move by Aberdeen City Council to set a debt collection agency on an 80-year-old partially sighted woman for the sum of \u00a317.50.<ref>{{cite news|title=MP slams 'draconian' debt threat|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/north_east/7917679.stm| accessdate=15 April 2009|date=2 March 2009|work=BBC News|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090306230629/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/north_east/7917679.stm|archivedate=6 March 2009|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nBegg also wrote to the Scottish First Minister [[Alex Salmond]] requesting a change to the house buying system in [[Scotland]]. She also criticised plans to close an Aberdeen school 18 months after it had been saved, saying that they were \"closing the school by stealth.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Political outcry over school plan|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/scotland/4715476.stm|accessdate=17 September 2007|date=15 February 2006|work=BBC News|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140903203301/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/scotland/4715476.stm|archive-date=3 September 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn November 1999, Begg sustained a broken wrist and a broken leg and was knocked from her wheelchair in a road accident outside [[Aberdeen Airport]].<ref name=Accident>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/509499.stm Scotland MP injured in airport accident] BBC News, 8 November 1999.</ref> Begg was hospitalised for three months as a result of her injuries.<ref name=Accident/>\n\nShe was appointed [[Dame Commander of the Order of the British Empire]] (DBE) in the 2011 New Year Honours for services to disabled people and to equal opportunities.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=59647 |date=31 December 2010 |page=6 |supp=y }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.labouronline.org/wibs/168348 Anne Begg MP profile], LabourOnline.org; accessed 31 August 2014.\n*{{UK MP links|parliament=dame--anne-begg/572|hansard=miss-anne-begg|guardian=329/anne-begg|publicwhip=Anne_Begg|theywork=anne_begg|record=Anne-Begg/Aberdeen-South/1030|bbc=25157.stm|accessdate=31 August 2014}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100712111534/http://yourdemocracy.newstatesman.com/profile/anne-begg Anne Begg's Profile] ''[[New Statesman]]''; accessed 31 August 2014.\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef | before=[[Raymond Robertson (politician)|Raymond Robertson]] }}\n{{s-ttl\n | title = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for [[Aberdeen South (UK Parliament constituency)|Aberdeen South]]\n | years = [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997]]\u2013[[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015]]\n}}\n{{s-aft | after = [[Callum McCaig]] }}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Begg, Anne}}\n[[Category:1955 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People with paraplegia]]\n[[Category:British politicians with physical disabilities]]\n[[Category:People from Brechin]]\n[[Category:Dames Commander of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Female members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for Scottish constituencies]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for Aberdeen constituencies]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1997\u20132001]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2001\u20132005]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2005\u20132010]]\n[[Category:Scottish schoolteachers]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Aberdeen]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2010\u20132015]]\n[[Category:Scottish Labour Party MPs]]\n[[Category:People educated at Brechin High School]]\n[[Category:Royalty and nobility with disabilities]]\n[[Category:20th-century British women politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century British women politicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=January 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2013}}\n\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| image=Anne Addresses May Day Rally in 2008.JPG<!-- only free-content images are allowed for depicting living people - see [[WP:NONFREE]] --> |\n| image_size = 250px\n| name = Dame Anne Begg\n| honorific-suffix =[[Order of the British Empire|DBE]]\n| office = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] <br /> for [[Aberdeen South (UK Parliament constituency)|Aberdeen South]]\n| parliament =\n| predecessor = [[Raymond Robertson (politician)|Raymond Robertson]]\n| successor = [[Callum McCaig]]\n| term_start = 1 May 1997\n| term_end = 30 March 2015\n| birth_name = Margaret Anne Begg\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1955|12|6|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Brechin]], [[Angus, Scotland]]\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| nationality = [[United Kingdom|British]]\n| party = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]\n| alma_mater = [[University of Aberdeen]]\n| website = [http://www.annebegg.com www.annebegg.com]}}\n\n'''Dame Margaret Anne Begg'''<ref>[http://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/article/oupww/whoswho/U7069 Profile], ukwhoswho.com; accessed 31 August 2014.</ref> [[Order of the British Empire|DBE]] (born 6 December 1955) is a [[British people|British]] [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] [[politician]], who served as the [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Aberdeen South (UK Parliament constituency)|Aberdeen South]] between [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997]] and [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015]].\n\nShe was the first permanent [[wheelchair]] user in the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] since 1880.<ref>{{cite news|title=Anne Begg profile|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/2051216.stm|date=21 October 2002|work=BBC News|first=Labour|last=MP|access-date=8 September 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040501160140/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/2051216.stm|archive-date=1 May 2004|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>[http://www.turtlebunbury.com/history/history_heroes/hist_hero_arthur_kavanagh.html Profile] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140309061743/http://www.turtlebunbury.com/history/history_heroes/hist_hero_arthur_kavanagh.html |date=9 March 2014 }}, turtlebunbury.com; accessed 31 August 2014.</ref>\n\n==Education and early career==\nBegg was educated at the Damacre Primary School (Brechin), [[Brechin High School]] and the [[University of Aberdeen]] where she earned an [[Master of Arts (Scotland)|MA]] in [[History]] and [[Politics]].<ref name=\"b\">{{cite news|title=VOTE 2001|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/hi/english/static/vote2001/candidates/candidates/0/00401.stm|accessdate=18 September 2007|work=BBC News|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040619175118/http://news.bbc.co.uk/hi/english/static/vote2001/candidates/candidates/0/00401.stm|archive-date=19 June 2004|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"c\">{{cite web|title=Biography of Anne Begg MP|url=http://www.annebegg.info/about.htm|accessdate=18 September 2007|publisher=Anne Begg profile|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071025050331/http://www.annebegg.info/about.htm|archivedate=25 October 2007|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> From Aberdeen College of Education (now the Faculty of Education of the University of Aberdeen), she gained a Secondary Teaching Certificate in 1978.\n\nFrom 1978, she taught history and [[English language|English]] at the [[Webster's High School]] in [[Kirriemuir]].<ref name=\"c\"/> She joined the Labour Party in 1983.<ref>{{cite web|work=ePolitix.com|title=Anne Begg profile|url=http://www.epolitix.com/EN/MPWebsites/Anne+Begg/192899D8-2381-4C12-87BB-2E6F475AD317.htm|accessdate=18 September 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080117113436/http://www.epolitix.com/EN/MPWebsites/Anne+Begg/192899D8-2381-4C12-87BB-2E6F475AD317.htm|archive-date=17 January 2008|url-status=live}}</ref> In 1988, she became the principal teacher of English at the [[Arbroath]] Academy.<ref name=\"c\"/> In the same year she won the Disabled Scot of the Year Award.<ref name=\"b\"/>\n\nBegg has been a [[wheelchair]] user since 1984 as she lives with the degenerative [[Gaucher's disease]].<ref name=\"c\"/> She was the second full-time user of a wheelchair elected to the House of Commons, after [[Arthur MacMorrough Kavanagh]] who was first elected in 1868 and sat until 1880.<ref>{{cite web|title=Interview with Anne Begg, Member of Parliament, UK |url=http://www.disabilityworld.org/12-02_05/gov/begginterview.shtml |accessdate=18 September 2007 |publisher=Disability World |date=16 June 2004 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061002152947/http://www.disabilityworld.org/12-02_05/gov/begginterview.shtml |archivedate=2 October 2006 }}</ref>\n\n==Parliamentary career==\nBegg was selected to stand for election for Labour through an [[all-women shortlists|all-women shortlist]].<ref>[http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4158/is_19960109/ai_n9634358?tag=content;col1 Find Articles]{{dead link|date=September 2010}}</ref> and when Aberdeen South (like many seats) fell to Labour in their [[landslide]] victory at the [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997 general election]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/videonation/articles/u/uk_mp.shtml|title=BBC - Video Nation - MP by Anne Begg|website=www.bbc.co.uk|access-date=4 March 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151019004157/http://www.bbc.co.uk/videonation/articles/u/uk_mp.shtml|archive-date=19 October 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> She defeated the Conservative [[Parliamentary Under Secretary of State]] at the [[Scottish Office]] [[Raymond Robertson (politician)|Raymond Robertson]].<ref>{{cite news|title=VOTE 2001 \u2013 RESULTS & CONSTITUENCIES \u2013 Aberdeen South|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/hi/english/static/vote2001/results_constituencies/constituencies/004.stm|accessdate=18 September 2007|work=BBC News|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060626181039/http://news.bbc.co.uk/hi/english/static/vote2001/results_constituencies/constituencies/004.stm|archive-date=26 June 2006|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2001, she became the first Labour MP to retain the Aberdeen South seat.\n\nShe made her [[maiden speech]] on 21 May 1997.<ref>{{cite web|title=House of Commons Hansard Debates for 21 May 1997 (pt 27) |url=https://publications.parliament.uk/cgi-bin/newhtml_hl?DB=semukparl&STEMMER=en&WORDS=begg%20ann&ALL=&ANY=&PHRASE=&CATEGORIES=&SIMPLE=&SPEAKER=begg%20anne&COLOUR=red&STYLE=s&ANCHOR=70521-27_spnew8&URL=/pa/cm199798/cmhansrd/vo970521/debtext/70521-27.htm#70521-27_spnew8 |accessdate=18 September 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071026053028/http://www.publications.parliament.uk/cgi-bin/newhtml_hl?DB=semukparl&STEMMER=en&WORDS=begg%20ann&ALL=&ANY=&PHRASE=&CATEGORIES=&SIMPLE=&SPEAKER=begg%20anne&COLOUR=red&STYLE=s&ANCHOR=70521-27_spnew8&URL=%2Fpa%2Fcm199798%2Fcmhansrd%2Fvo970521%2Fdebtext%2F70521-27.htm |archivedate=26 October 2007 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.turtlebunbury.com/history/history_heroes/hist_hero_arthur_kavanagh.html|title=Turtle Bunbury - Award-winning travel writer, historian and author based in Ireland|website=www.turtlebunbury.com|access-date=6 October 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140309061743/http://www.turtlebunbury.com/history/history_heroes/hist_hero_arthur_kavanagh.html|archive-date=9 March 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> She was Secretary of the All-Party [[BBC]] Group and Chair of the All Party Group on Equalities, the All Party Oil and Gas Industry Group, the All Party Group on Chronic Pain, and the All Party Commercial Radio group.<ref>{{cite web|title=Anne Begg biography |url=http://iwc2.labouronline.org/168348/biography |accessdate=19 December 2008 |publisher=Labour Party |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090210164041/http://iwc2.labouronline.org/168348/biography |archivedate=10 February 2009 }}</ref> \nShe was a member of the House of Commons Chairmen\u2019s Panel<ref name=\"c\"/> and Vice Chair of the Speaker's Conference which was tasked with looking at the under representation of women, ethnic minorities and disabled people in the House of Commons.<ref>{{cite web|title=Speaker's Conference:Membership |url=http://www.parliament.uk/business/speakers_conference/membership.cfm |accessdate=19 December 2008 |publisher=UK Parliament |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090522085958/http://www.parliament.uk/business/speakers_conference/membership.cfm |archivedate=22 May 2009 }}</ref> She  chaired the [[Work and Pensions Select Committee]] from July 2010.\n\nBegg lost her seat in the [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015 general election]] to [[Callum McCaig]] of the [[Scottish National Party]].\n\n===Votes and political views===\nBegg voted in favour of a bill that banned smoking in restaurants in April 2003.<ref>{{cite web|title=House of Commons Hansard Debates for 14 April 2003 (pt 15)|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200203/cmhansrd/vo030414/debtext/30414-15.htm#30414-15_div162|accessdate=17 September 2007|publisher=UK Parliament|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070630224840/http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200203/cmhansrd/vo030414/debtext/30414-15.htm#30414-15_div162|archive-date=30 June 2007|url-status=live}}</ref> In December 2004 and October 2005, she voted in favour of the [[Identity Cards Act 2006|Identity Cards Bill]].<ref>{{cite web|title=House of Commons Hansard Debates for 20 December 2004 (pt 42)|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200405/cmhansrd/vo041220/debtext/41220-42.htm#41220-42_div24|accessdate=17 September 2007|publisher=UK Parliament|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071123131524/http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200405/cmhansrd/vo041220/debtext/41220-42.htm#41220-42_div24|archive-date=23 November 2007|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=House of Commons Hansard Debates for 18 October 2005 (pt 35)|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200506/cmhansrd/vo051018/debtext/51018-35.htm#51018-35_div60|accessdate=17 September 2007|publisher=UK Parliament|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071123131539/http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200506/cmhansrd/vo051018/debtext/51018-35.htm#51018-35_div60|archive-date=23 November 2007|url-status=live}}</ref> She voted in favour of allowing unmarried heterosexual and homosexual couples to adopt,<ref>{{cite web|title=House of Commons Hansard Debates for 4 Nov 2002 (pt 28)|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200102/cmhansrd/vo021104/debtext/21104-28.htm#21104-28_div345|accessdate=17 September 2007|publisher=UK Parliament|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071123131454/http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200102/cmhansrd/vo021104/debtext/21104-28.htm#21104-28_div345|archive-date=23 November 2007|url-status=live}}</ref> and in favour of the [[Civil Partnership Act 2004|Civil Partnership Bill]].<ref>{{cite web|title=House of Commons Hansard Debates for 12 October 2004 (pt 34)|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200304/cmhansrd/vo041012/debtext/41012-34.htm#41012-34_div256|accessdate=17 September 2007|publisher=UK Parliament|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070630192558/http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200304/cmhansrd/vo041012/debtext/41012-34.htm#41012-34_div256|archive-date=30 June 2007|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2002, she voted to ban the hunting of wild mammals with dogs.<ref>{{cite web|title=House of Commons Hansard Debates for 18 March 2002 (pt 40)|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200102/cmhansrd/vo020318/debtext/20318-40.htm#20318-40_div199|accessdate=17 September 2007|publisher=UK Parliament|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070523034243/http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200102/cmhansrd/vo020318/debtext/20318-40.htm#20318-40_div199|archive-date=23 May 2007|url-status=live}}</ref> She voted in favour of the [[NHS Foundation Trust]] proposal<ref>{{cite web|title=House of Commons Hansard Debates for 8 July 2003 (pt 27)|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200203/cmhansrd/vo030708/debtext/30708-27.htm#30708-27_div280|accessdate=17 September 2007|publisher=UK Parliament|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071123131459/http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200203/cmhansrd/vo030708/debtext/30708-27.htm#30708-27_div280|archive-date=23 November 2007|url-status=live}}</ref> and against the [[British replacement of the Trident system|replacement of the Trident system]].<ref>{{cite web|title=House of Commons Hansard Debates for 14 March 2007 (pt 0022)|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200607/cmhansrd/cm070314/debtext/70314-0022.htm#07031475002466|accessdate=17 September 2007|publisher=UK Parliament|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071123131544/http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200607/cmhansrd/cm070314/debtext/70314-0022.htm#07031475002466|archive-date=23 November 2007|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nShe voted in favour of adding clauses to a bill that allow the Secretary of State to detain indefinitely, pending deportation, anyone he suspects is a terrorist, even if the law forbids that person's deportation from ever taking place.<ref>{{cite web | title=House of Commons Hansard Debates for 21 November 2001 (pt 28)|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200102/cmhansrd/vo011121/debtext/11121-28.htm#11121-28_div76|accessdate=17 September 2007|publisher=UK Parliament|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070827013607/http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200102/cmhansrd/vo011121/debtext/11121-28.htm|archivedate=27 August 2007|url-status=live}}</ref> She voted against allowing people detained at a police station to be fingerprinted and searched for identifying birthmarks unless it is in connection with a terrorism investigation.<ref>{{cite web|title=House of Commons Hansard Debates for 26 November 2001 (pt 30)|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200102/cmhansrd/vo011126/debtext/11126-30.htm#11126-30_div82|accessdate=17 September 2007|publisher=UK Parliament|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071123131449/http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200102/cmhansrd/vo011126/debtext/11126-30.htm#11126-30_div82|archive-date=23 November 2007|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2003, she voted against the declaration of war against [[Iraq]].<ref>{{cite web|title=House of Commons Hansard Debates for 18 Mar 2003 (pt 48)|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200203/cmhansrd/vo030318/debtext/30318-48.htm#30318-48_div118|accessdate=17 September 2007|publisher=UK Parliament|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070821064145/http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200203/cmhansrd/vo030318/debtext/30318-48.htm| archivedate=21 August 2007|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2003, she voted against a motion that would have recalled the Prime Minister's assertion that Iraq had weapons of mass destruction that could be used at 45 minutes' notice, and launching an independent inquiry into the intelligence received and the decisions that were based on it.<ref>{{cite web|title=House of Commons Hansard Debates for 4 Jun 2003 (pt 25)|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200203/cmhansrd/vo030604/debtext/30604-25.htm#30604-25_div217|accessdate=17 September 2007|publisher=UK Parliament|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070703064015/http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200203/cmhansrd/vo030604/debtext/30604-25.htm#30604-25_div217|archive-date=3 July 2007|url-status=live}}</ref> In June 2007, she voted against a motion calling for an independent inquiry by a committee of [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom|Privy Counsellors]] into the Iraq War.<ref>{{cite web|title=House of Commons Hansard Debates for 11 June 2007 (pt 0015)|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200607/cmhansrd/cm070611/debtext/70611-0015.htm#07061179001224|accessdate=17 September 2007|publisher=UK Parliament|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071123131554/http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200607/cmhansrd/cm070611/debtext/70611-0015.htm#07061179001224|archive-date=23 November 2007|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2008, Begg was one of 18 MPs who signed a Commons motion backing a Team GB football team at the 2012 Olympics, saying football \"should not be any different from other competing sports and our young talent should be allowed to show their skills on the world stage\". The football governing bodies of Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland are all opposed to a Great Britain team, fearing it would stop them competing as individual nations in future tournaments. {{citation needed|date=August 2014}}\n\nDuring the 2009 MPs expenses scandal, Begg was one of the first Scottish MPs to take the step of publishing all of her claims under the Additional Costs Allowance on her website before they were released by the House of Commons authorities saying that it was \"important people can see how MPs spend taxpayers' money.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Doran's books reveal repairs expenditure|url=http://www.pressandjournal.co.uk/Article.aspx/1222257|date=19 May 2009|publisher=The Press and Journal|access-date=19 May 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120306035945/http://www.pressandjournal.co.uk/Article.aspx/1222257|archive-date=6 March 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2011, Begg crossed swords with [[Philip Davies]], Conservative MP for Shipley, over the issue of disabled people being allowed to work for less than minimum wage if they so choose in order to establish themselves in employment. Davies explained that he was representing the views of constituents anxious to get a foothold on the earnings ladder, but Begg believed that this was simply an attempt to discriminate against disabled people.<ref>{{cite news|title=Tory MP Philip Davies: disabled people could work for less pay|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2011/jun/17/tory-philip-davies-disabled-people-work|location=London, UK|work=The Guardian|first=Allegra|last=Stratton|date=17 June 2011|access-date=13 December 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161221084106/https://www.theguardian.com/society/2011/jun/17/tory-philip-davies-disabled-people-work|archive-date=21 December 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===National campaigns===\nBegg is a vocal campaigner for allowing embryonic stem cells to be used in the research for treatments of diseases, including currently incurable conditions such as Alzheimer's and Parkinson's Disease.<ref>{{cite news| title=UK to extend embyo research| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/sci/tech/1078672.stm| accessdate=9 January 2009| work=BBC News| date=19 December 2000| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080320203944/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/sci/tech/1078672.stm| archive-date=20 March 2008| url-status=live}}</ref> She has also been heavily involved in lobbying the [[Department of Health]] against an all-out ban on the pain-relief drug [[co-proxamol]], used by many people who suffer from chronic pain conditions.<ref>{{cite web| title=Co-proxamol row heats up as MPs deman U-turn| url=http://www.pulsetoday.co.uk/story.asp?storycode=4011641| accessdate=9 January 2009| publisher=Pulse| date=19 January 2007| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110522034955/http://www.pulsetoday.co.uk/story.asp?storycode=4011641| archive-date=22 May 2011| url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nShe has also taken the lead in lobbying the government on issues such as the Seafarer's Earnings Deduction<ref>{{cite web|title=Minister hints seafarers will escape tax blow|url=http://www.pressandjournal.co.uk/Article.aspx/887604?UserKey&UserKey=|accessdate=20 January 2009|publisher=The Press and Journal|date=16 October 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120212233915/http://www.pressandjournal.co.uk/Article.aspx/887604?UserKey&UserKey=|archive-date=12 February 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> and compensation for trawlermen who lost their livelihoods during the [[Cod Wars]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Cod War fishermen in line for extra payouts|url=http://www.pressandjournal.co.uk/Article.aspx/984625?UserKey=|accessdate=20 January 2009|date=12 December 2008|publisher=the Press and Journal|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120403033929/http://www.pressandjournal.co.uk/Article.aspx/984625?UserKey=|archive-date=3 April 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> In the 2009 Budget, Begg also won a concession from the [[Chancellor of the Exchequer]], [[Alistair Darling]] [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MP]], that \"those caring responsibilities of grandparents of working age will count towards their entitlement to the basic state pension.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Government's plans 'a missed opportunity'|url=http://www.pressandjournal.co.uk/Article.aspx/1184362?UserKey==|accessdate=23 April 2009|publisher=Press and Journal|date=23 April 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120403033940/http://www.pressandjournal.co.uk/Article.aspx/1184362?UserKey==|archive-date=3 April 2012|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Begg had campaigned for grandparents of working age to receive National Insurance Credits in recognition of the fact that their caring role may impact on their contributions to their state pension entitlement.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ways and Means \u2013 Financial Statement| url=https://www.theyworkforyou.com/debates/?id=2009-04-22a.237.0&s=speaker%3A10153#g237.2=|accessdate=23 April 2009|publisher=TheyWorkForYou|date=22 April 2009}}</ref>\n\nOn the floor of the House of Commons, Begg vehemently criticised fraudsters who take advantage of vulnerable people in her constituency through the use of mail scams<ref>{{cite news|title=Mail scams concerns to be raised|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/north_east/7254416.stm|accessdate=9 January 2009|work=BBC News|date=20 February 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090412221731/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/north_east/7254416.stm|archive-date=12 April 2009|url-status=live}}</ref> and pyramid schemes.<ref>{{cite web|title='Women Empowering Women' scheme|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200102/cmhansrd/vo011127/debtext/11127-35.htm|accessdate=9 January 2009|publisher=UK Parliament|date=27 November 2001|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090627000134/http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200102/cmhansrd/vo011127/debtext/11127-35.htm|archive-date=27 June 2009|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Local campaigns===\nBegg was one of the most vociferous critics of Aberdeen City Council during the budget crisis of 2008, which led to many of her constituents having their services cut.<ref>{{cite news|title=\u00a350m cuts fear for city council|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/north_east/7509919.stm| accessdate=20 January 2009|date=16 July 2008|work=BBC News}}</ref> In 2009 she criticised as \"draconian\" a move by Aberdeen City Council to set a debt collection agency on an 80-year-old partially sighted woman for the sum of \u00a317.50.<ref>{{cite news|title=MP slams 'draconian' debt threat|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/north_east/7917679.stm| accessdate=15 April 2009|date=2 March 2009|work=BBC News|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090306230629/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/north_east/7917679.stm|archivedate=6 March 2009|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nBegg also wrote to the Scottish First Minister [[Alex Salmond]] requesting a change to the house buying system in [[Scotland]]. She also criticised plans to close an Aberdeen school 18 months after it had been saved, saying that they were \"closing the school by stealth.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Political outcry over school plan|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/scotland/4715476.stm|accessdate=17 September 2007|date=15 February 2006|work=BBC News|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140903203301/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/scotland/4715476.stm|archive-date=3 September 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn November 1999, Begg sustained a broken wrist and a broken leg and was knocked from her wheelchair in a road accident outside [[Aberdeen Airport]].<ref name=Accident>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/509499.stm Scotland MP injured in airport accident] BBC News, 8 November 1999.</ref> Begg was hospitalised for three months as a result of her injuries.<ref name=Accident/>\n\nShe was appointed [[Dame Commander of the Order of the British Empire]] (DBE) in the 2011 New Year Honours for services to disabled people and to equal opportunities.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=59647 |date=31 December 2010 |page=6 |supp=y }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.labouronline.org/wibs/168348 Anne Begg MP profile], LabourOnline.org; accessed 31 August 2014.\n*{{UK MP links|parliament=dame--anne-begg/572|hansard=miss-anne-begg|guardian=329/anne-begg|publicwhip=Anne_Begg|theywork=anne_begg|record=Anne-Begg/Aberdeen-South/1030|bbc=25157.stm|accessdate=31 August 2014}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100712111534/http://yourdemocracy.newstatesman.com/profile/anne-begg Anne Begg's Profile] ''[[New Statesman]]''; accessed 31 August 2014.\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef | before=[[Raymond Robertson (politician)|Raymond Robertson]] }}\n{{s-ttl\n | title = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for [[Aberdeen South (UK Parliament constituency)|Aberdeen South]]\n | years = [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997]]\u2013[[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015]]\n}}\n{{s-aft | after = [[Callum McCaig]] }}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Begg, Anne}}\n[[Category:1955 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People with paraplegia]]\n[[Category:British politicians with physical disabilities]]\n[[Category:People from Brechin]]\n[[Category:Dames Commander of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Female members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for Scottish constituencies]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for Aberdeen constituencies]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1997\u20132001]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2001\u20132005]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2005\u20132010]]\n[[Category:Scottish schoolteachers]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Aberdeen]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2010\u20132015]]\n[[Category:Scottish Labour Party MPs]]\n[[Category:People educated at Brechin High School]]\n[[Category:Royalty and nobility with disabilities]]\n[[Category:20th-century British women politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century British women politicians]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eParliamentary career:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anne_Begg"}
{"title_page": "Paul Marsden", "text_new": "{{For|the Emmerdale character|Paul Marsden (Emmerdale)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2017}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix =\n| name = Paul Marsden\n| honorific-suffix =\n| party = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] (1983\u20132001, 2005)<br />[[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]] (2001\u20132005)\n| image = Paul Marsden.jpeg\n| office = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] <br /> for [[Shrewsbury and Atcham (UK Parliament constituency)|Shrewsbury and Atcham]]\n| term_start = 1 May 1997\n| term_end = 11 April 2005\n| parliament = \n| majority = \n| predecessor = [[Derek Conway]]\n| successor = [[Daniel Kawczynski]]\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1968|3|18|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Frodsham]], [[Cheshire]]\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| nationality = [[United Kingdom|British]]\n| parents = Thomas Darlington Marsden (father), Audrey Stott (mother)\n| spouse = \n| relations =\n| children = Alexander Marsden, Richard Marsden\n| residence =\n| alma_mater = [[University of Teesside|Teesside Polytechnic]]\n| occupation = International Business Consultant\n| profession = \n| religion = Church of England\n| signature =\n| website = http://paulwbmarsden.blogspot.com\n| footnotes =\n}}\n\n'''Paul William Barry Marsden''' (born 18 March 1968) is a [[United Kingdom|British]] writer, businessman and former politician. He was the [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Shrewsbury and Atcham (UK Parliament constituency)|Shrewsbury and Atcham]] from 1997 until 2005. He was most prominently known for his anti-war views and [[crossing the floor]] twice (the first to do so since [[Winston Churchill]]<ref>[http://www.futermanrose.co.uk/marsden.html Futerman, Rose & Associates profile of Paul Marsden]</ref>), from [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] to the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]] in 2001 and returning to Labour in 2005. He instructed a solicitor in 2010 to begin action for phone hacking that allegedly took place back in 2003 by a newspaper. In 2012, Marsden was appointed to draft the parliamentary inquiry report into VIP security at the Olympic and Paralympic Games in London. Currently Marsden is Head of Business Intelligence at the construction company [[MWH Global]].<ref>[https://www.linkedin.com/in/paulwbmarsden LinkedIN profile]</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nMarsden was born in [[Frodsham]] in [[Cheshire]] to Thomas Darlington Marsden, a distribution manager and Labour councillor<ref>[http://cdnedge.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/1613340.stm ''BBC'' From disaffection to defection]</ref> and Audrey Stott, a school teacher. He was educated at [[Helsby High School]]. Marsden completed a diploma in building studies at [[Mid Cheshire College|Mid-Cheshire College]] in 1986, but withdrew from completing a civil engineering degree after the first three years at [[University of Teesside|Teesside Polytechnic]] in 1990. Studying part-time, he passed a diploma in management at the [[Open University]] and a diploma in business excellence at [[Newcastle College]].\n\nBefore his political career, Marsden worked as a quality manager at [[Taylor Woodrow]] (1990\u20131994), a management consultant at [[NatWest Bank]] (1994\u20131996) and as a total quality facilitator at [[Mitel]] from 1996 until the general election in 1997.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/2172996.stm ''BBC'' Profile of Paul Marsden 2005]</ref>\n\n== Labour Member of Parliament ==\nMarsden was elected as the first (and thus far only) Labour MP for [[Shrewsbury and Atcham (UK Parliament constituency)|Shrewsbury and Atcham]] at the [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997 general election]] with a swing of 11.4%; a seat which he held at the [[2001 United Kingdom general election|2001 election]] with a further swing of 5.5%. At 29 years of age, he was one of the youngest MP's elected in 1997. He spoke in the Commons for the first time on 21 May 1997 and in an otherwise traditional maiden speech, joked prophetically about refusing to be intimidated by the Whips.<ref>[http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/commons/1997/may/21/adjournment-of-the-house ''Hansard'' Maiden speech by Paul Marsden 21/05/97]</ref> He was nominated to serve on the Agriculture Select Committee and remained for four years quietly serving on the committee.\n\nOn 14 April 1999, Marsden introduced the Cancer Care Bill<ref>[http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/commons/1999/apr/14/cancer-care ''Hansard'' Cancer Care 14/04/99]</ref> with backing from cancer charities including [[Macmillan Cancer Support]], under the Ten Minute Rule that would create the first comprehensive directory of cancer services in the UK to aid patients in identifying the location and type of cancer care available.<ref>[http://www.hsj.co.uk/news/astonished-mp-pushes-for-cancer-register/29792.article ''Health Service Journal'' Astonished MP pushes for cancer register 29/04/99]</ref> The Bill prompted Ruth Fermor Allan to create such a directory called 'Cancer Care 2000',<ref>[http://www.whsmith.co.uk/CatalogAndSearch/SearchWithinCategory.aspx?as_Publisher=Cambridge+Healthcare+Publishing+Ltd&cat=\\Books Cancer Care 2000 by Ruth Fermor Allan]{{dead link|date=March 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> which was published by Cambridge Healthcare Publishing Ltd in November 2000.\n\nIn March 2001, Marsden with cross party support put forward a Doorstep Recycling Bill,<ref>[http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/commons/2001/mar/13/recycling-doorstep-collection ''Hansard'' Recycling (Doorstep Collection) Bill 13/03/01]</ref> mandating the collection of recyclable materials from streets. The Bill was backed by [[Friends of the Earth]]. The Bill did not succeed that year but the Government eventually backed a similar Bill by [[Joan Ruddock]] and the Municipal Waste Recycling Bill was passed in October 2003, increasing the levels of recycling of residential waste.<ref>[http://www.foe.co.uk/news/recycling_bill_success.html FoE Recycling Bill success 30/10/03]</ref>\n\nAfter a first term loyally supporting the Government, Marsden began to question the Labour Government's foreign policy following [[9/11]]. On 8 October 2001, he was the first MP in the Commons to publicly call for a vote on any [[War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)|military action]] in Afghanistan.<ref>[http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/commons/2001/oct/08/sittings-of-the-house ''Hansard'' 8 October 2001]</ref> Marsden took to sitting in [[Tony Benn]]'s former Commons seat below the gangway on the second row from the back.<ref>[http://news.scotsman.com/topstories/Unlikely-rebel-keeping-up-the.2267783.jp ''The Scotsman'' Unlikely rebel keeping up the Benn tradition 18/10/01]</ref> Two weeks later, Marsden was instructed to attend a meeting with the Labour [[Parliamentary Secretary to the Treasury|Chief Whip]], [[Hilary Armstrong]]. As [[Jeremy Paxman]] wrote, \"the Labour MP Paul Marsden took the unprecedented step of recording the dressing-down\",<ref>''The Political Animal'' by Jeremy Paxman, page 166</ref> where he said that he had been confronted with accusations that \"those aren't with us are against us,\" \"war is not a matter of conscience\" and \"it was people like you who appeased Hitler in 1938\", infuriating Marsden to going public.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2001/oct/22/uk.september11 ''The Guardian'' 'Those that are not with us are against us' 22/10/01]</ref><ref>[http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/comment/article726868.ece ''The Times'' report 5 February 2006 on Labour Chief Whip and Marsden]</ref>\n\n[[Tony Benn]] described in his diary that \"The pressure on the anti-war MPs is growing. Apparently Paul Marsden, the Labour MP for Shrewsbury and Atcham, had three-quarters-of-an-hour being bullied by the Chief Whip, Hilary Armstrong.\"<ref>[http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-483210/Tony-Benns-diaries-Blair-absolutely-capacity-deliver-promise.html ''More Time For Politics: Diaries 2001\u20132007'' by Tony Benn]</ref>\nNumber 10 were forced to put out a statement that dissenting backbenchers would be allowed to speak out on the war.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/1612211.stm ''BBC News'' 22/10/01]</ref><ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/main.jhtml?xml=/news/2001/10/23/nspin23.xml ''Daily Telegraph'' report 23 October 2001 on Marsden speaking out]</ref> The Guardian in its Leader praised Marsden for having called for a vote on the war and publishing the Chief Whip's response to it and stated, \"On both counts he has done British democracy a service.\"<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2001/oct/23/labour.terrorism ''The Guardian'' Marsden's Victory 23/10/01]</ref>\n\nUndeterred by the Whip's criticism, Marsden then spoke out against the press officer [[Jo Moore]] who had said, that [[9/11]] was \"a very good day to get out anything we want to bury\"; he and [[Tam Dalyell]] were the only two Labour MPs to vote against the Government.<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1360241/MPs-to-vote-on-Jo-Moore-row.html ''Daily Telegraph'' MPs to vote on Jo Moore row 23/10/01]</ref><ref>[http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/commons/2001/oct/23/ministerial-conduct-dtlr ''Hansard Ministerial Conduct'' 23/10/01]</ref>\n\nIn November 2001, Marsden visited [[Pakistan]] and the Afghan border to highlight the plight of [[Afghan refugees]] living in camps who had fled the war.<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/asia/afghanistan/1361987/Refugee-camps-are-hell-says-Labour-rebel.html ''Daily Telegraph'' report on Marsden being first to visit refugee camp 09/11/01]</ref> Marsden also negotiated the release of ''[[Sunday Telegraph]]'' journalist [[Christina Lamb]] and photographer Justin Sutcliffe, who had been arrested and held by the Pakistan Police and [[Inter-Services Intelligence]] secret service.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/south_asia/1651861.stm BBC News - Deported journalist 'uncovered collusion']</ref><ref>[http://articles.cnn.com/2001-11-09/world/gen.uk.journalists_1_islamabad-pakistan-quetta?_s=PM:asiapcf CNN: Pakistan detains UK journalists 09/11/01] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111123161852/http://articles.cnn.com/2001-11-09/world/gen.uk.journalists_1_islamabad-pakistan-quetta?_s=PM:asiapcf |date=23 November 2011 }}</ref> [[Christina Lamb]] thanked Marsden in the acknowledgements of her biographical book, ''The Sewing Circles of Herat'', \"Paul Marsden MP for Shrewsbury, helped rescue us from the ISI, being manhandled by Baluchistan police in the process, and kindly rearranged his whole schedule to stay in Pakistan until we were safely out.\"<ref>''The Sewing Circles of Herat'' by Christina Lamb, page x [http://www.christinalamb.net/pages/sewingcircles.html 2002] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110930112738/http://www.christinalamb.net/pages/sewingcircles.html |date=30 September 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 November 2001, Marsden was one of the leaders of the Stop the War demonstration against the war in Afghanistan in London. Marsden was one of the principal speakers along with [[Tony Benn]] and [[George Galloway]] in Trafalgar Square with 100,000 protesters.<ref>[[Protests against the War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)#2001|Protests against the war in Afghanistan 2001-]]</ref> He accused Blair of being \"drunk with power\" and \"we are not simply going to allow the atrocities of September 11 to be replaced with further atrocities in Afghanistan\".<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/1662656.stm ''BBC News'' - Thousands join anti-war march - 18/11/01]</ref>\n\nMarsden complained bitterly that he had been subjected to late night physical attacks by some Labour Whips, which were vigorously denied.<ref>[https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/top-stories/2002/04/30/john-pilger-tony-blair-s-great-betrayal-115875-21775311/ John Pilger: Tony Blair's great betrayal 30/04/02]</ref><ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/1694282.stm BBC News Colleagues 'attacked' me, says MP 05/12/01]</ref> Five days later, he [[crossing the floor|defected]] to the Liberal Democrats on 10 December 2001, citing his disagreements with Labour whips over his opposition to military action in [[Afghanistan]] and the resulting civilian casualties.<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/paul-marsden-the-oddball-and-loner-who-became-focus-of-resistance-to-blairs-allpowerful-party-machine-748033.html ''The Independent'' report leaving Labour 11/12/01]</ref><ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2001/dec/10/labour.uk2 ''The Guardian'' Key quotes from Paul Marsden 10/12/01]</ref> By crossing the floor of the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]], his actions contributed to a parliamentary vote being granted before the 2003 [[Iraq War]].{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}} The ''[[Big Issue]]'' magazine's readers voted Marsden 'Hero of the Year' in 2001 for his opposition to the war in Afghanistan.\n\n== Liberal Democrat MP and Shadow Minister ==\nIn May 2002, Marsden was promoted to Shadow Health Minister for the Liberal Democrats reporting to [[Evan Harris]], in charge of a portfolio covering mental health, prison health and aspects of cancer care.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20040225193355/http://www.libdems.org.uk/index.cfm/page.whois/section.people/wid.795/wgroup.mp Lib Dem Profile of Paul Marsden 2003]</ref>\n\nIn June 2002, Marsden presented the Prescriptions (Chronic Diseases) Bill, which aimed to introduce a fairer system for issuing prescriptions' exemptions for patients with acute conditions.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/health/2052409.stm BBC News \u2013 MP bids to scrap prescription charges \u2013 19/06/02]</ref> Although the Bill received cross party support it ran out of parliamentary time before the summer recess. The Bill received backing from the [[Cystic Fibrosis Trust]] and the National Asthma Campaign.<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/comment/letters/3578053/Prescription-injustice.html ''Daily Telegraph'' 18/06/02]</ref>\n\nIn August 2002 he visited [[Malawi]] to turn the media spotlight on the southern African famine and later he travelled to [[Johannesburg]] to lobby the [[United Nations]] conference discussing the famine affecting Southern Africa. His accusations that the failures of the [[International Monetary Fund]] had exacerbated the famine caused a public argument with the IMF Director.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/science/2002/nov/01/gm.guardianletters ''The Guardian'' Letters 01/11/02]</ref><ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2002/nov/07/famine.guardianletters?INTCMP=ILCNETTXT3487 ''The Guardian'' Letters 02/11/02]</ref>\n\nIn February 2003, prior to the [[Iraq War]], he visited the [[United States|USA]] to give a speaking tour opposing the impending war and laid a Union flag and wreath in commemoration of the victims of the [[September 11, 2001 attacks]] at Ground Zero. He also attended the [[United Nations Security Council]] session considering the looming war on 14 February. Marsden strongly opposed the war in Iraq and repeatedly voted for an inquiry into the alleged intelligence failings and concerns that parliament was misled.<ref>[http://www.publicwhip.org.uk/mp.php?mpn=Paul_Marsden&mpc=Shrewsbury_and_Atcham&house=commons&dmp=975&display=motions Public Whip votes on Iraq \u2013 Paul Marsden MP]</ref>\n\nOn the second anniversary of [[9/11]], he visited the [[Slobodan Milosevic]] trial in The Hague and met with prosecution lawyers at the [[International Criminal Court]].\n\nMarsden was declared the leading rebel on all parliamentary votes by ''The Times'' in 2003.<ref>[http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/life_and_style/article1002354.ece ''The Times'' report 28 October 2003 on website search and leading rebel]</ref>\n\nIn October 2003, Marsden was appointed the number two behind [[John Thurso]] as Shadow Transport Minister for the Liberal Democrats and nominated as a member of the Transport Select Committee.<ref>[http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/commons/2003/nov/10/transport ''Hansard'' Appointment of Paul Marsden to Transport Select Committee 10/11/03]</ref>\n\nIn April 2004, Marsden set the fifth fastest time for MPs completing the [[London Marathon]] out of forty two that have taken part since it began in 1981, with a time of 3 hours 18 minutes 1 second.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/programmes/politics_show/8017098.stm BBC News: MPs and the London Marathon 24/04/09]</ref>\n\nOn 26 August 2004, Marsden became one of only twenty cross party MPs to back the [[Impeach Blair campaign]] with the aim of holding Blair to account over the highly controversial war in Iraq. The campaign used legal counsel for advice but was unable to secure enough support for progressing the impeachment in parliament.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/3600438.stm Blair impeachment campaign starts]</ref>\n\n== Announces retirement as MP and rejoins Labour ==\nIn July 2004 Marsden announced that he was retiring from politics and would not contest the [[2005 United Kingdom general election|May 2005 general election]].<ref>[http://www.epolitix.com/latestnews/article-detail/newsarticle/marsden-to-quit-as-mp/ ''ePolitix'' - Marsden quits 28/07/04]</ref> He cited the toll suffered as a result of admissions about his private life and the effects on his family. He reduced his Liberal Democrat political duties and on 5 April 2005, within hours of the start of the election campaign, Marsden announced his intention to rejoin the Labour Party, stating that although he still disagreed with the government over the war and levels of investment in public services, he did not want to see Labour MPs who shared his views, to lose their seats.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/vote_2005/frontpage/4414967.stm ''BBC News'' MP Marsden defects back to Labour 06/04/05]</ref><ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2005/apr/08/iraq.comment Letter to ''The Guardian'' by Paul Marsden 08/04/05]</ref> He later apologised to Liberal Democrat supporters for leaving the party. He was the first British politician since [[Winston Churchill]] to re-cross the floor of the House of Commons and return to his original party, in Marsden's case to sit on the Labour benches.<ref>[http://www.futermanrose.co.uk/marsden.html Futerman, Rose & Associates profile of Paul Marsden]</ref>\n\nDuring his Parliamentary career Marsden raised over \u00a310K for local and international charities through sponsored [[Marathon|marathon running]], [[abseiling]] and [[Swimming (sport)|swimming]].<ref>[http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/uk/article826231.ece ''The Times''  More charity events hit by VAT cash grab 16/04/04]</ref>\n\nIn the [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005 general election]] the Conservative, [[Daniel Kawczynski]] won back the Shrewsbury and Atcham seat from the subsequent Labour candidate, Michael Ion.\n\n== Expenses ==\nAlthough MPs expenses were published after Marsden had left parliament, expenses claims were backdated to the time when he was a sitting MP. [[Sir Thomas Legg]] gave Marsden a clean bill of health and reported that he was one of only a minority of MPs and ex-MPs with \"no issues\".<ref>[https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200910/cmselect/cmmemest/348/348.pdf Review of Past ACA Payments by Sir Thomas Legg 2010 page 162]</ref>\n\n== Post-Parliamentary career ==\nBefore retiring from politics, Marsden co-authored the book ''Voices for Peace'' published by [[Simon & Schuster]] in 2001. Four years later he researched and published a local history book, ''[[The Blackfriars of Shrewsbury]]'' and returned to business consultancy in 2005.  He also wrote more anti-war poetry.\n\nIn December 2005, Marsden caused a row when he publicly confirmed [[Charles Kennedy]]'s drinking problems and that Kennedy had not been telling the truth about his illness. Kennedy's press secretary vehemently denied Marsden's story.<ref>[http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/news/politics/article2031886.ece ''The Times'' 19/12/05]</ref> However, by 5 January 2006, Kennedy admitted he had \"a drink problem\" and had sought \"professional help\".<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/4582930.stm BBC News 05/01/06]</ref> He resigned two days later as leader.\n\nIn 2007, Marsden was appointed Director of Policy at the [[British Union for the Abolition of Vivisection]]<ref>[https://archive.is/20120913024153/http://www.thirdsector.co.uk/news/archive/754107/Movers-Paul-Marsden-policy-director-BUAV/ Movers: Paul Marsden, Policy Director, BUAV Third Sector 24/10/07]</ref> and between 2008 and 2010 was the CEO of the Painting and Decorating Association.<ref>[http://www.journalism.co.uk/press-releases/trade-body-appoints-new-chief-executive/s66/a533204/ Trade body appoints new Chief Executive 13/01/09]</ref>\n\nIn May 2009, Marsden applied to rejoin the Labour Party but was provisionally blocked by the National Executive and is not presently a member of any political party.\n\nIn September 2010, Marsden's war poem, ''Eighty at Ligny'' was used in l'exposition historique for the British World War I war cemetery in memory of the eighty British, Irish and Canadian soldiers who are buried in [[Ligny-sur-Canche]]. In 2010, Marsden returned to business consultancy, working as a consultant for a trade conference.\n\nIn January 2011, it was reported that Marsden had commenced legal enquiries into allegations of hacking into his phone back in 2003. A suspended reporter who worked at the ''[[Sunday Mirror]]'' and then the ''[[News of the World]]'' was claimed to be involved.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-12271690 BBC News: report 24 January 2011 on phone hacking]</ref> A Channel 4 ''Dispatches'' programme interviewed Marsden and it was revealed that the reporter in question, had been suspended for phone hacking, although he denied it.<ref>[http://www.channel4.com/programmes/dispatches/episode-guide/series-79/episode-1 Channel 4 ''Dispatches'' 07/02/11]</ref> It was the first time that a newspaper other than the ''[[News of the World]]'' had been cited in connection with allegations of phone hacking.<ref>[[News of the World phone hacking affair]]</ref>{{better source|reason=Wikipedia is not a reliable source!|date=July 2018}}\n\nIn May 2011, Marsden wrote on his Blog, www.paulwbmarsden.blogspot.com,<ref>[http://paulwbmarsden.blogspot.com/2011/05/privacy-vs-public-interest.html]</ref> an article about the debate on public interest vs privacy in which he mentioned the allegations that [[Ryan Giggs]] was the footballer who had taken out a [[Injunction#UK superinjunctions|super injunction]] against [[Imogen Thomas]]. His Blog was written before [[John Hemming (politician)|John Hemming]] revealed the [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] player's name under parliamentary privilege.<ref>[http://www.shropshirestar.com/news/2011/05/26/former-shrewsbury-mp-defiant-over-giggs-naming/]</ref>\n\nIn July 2012, Marsden was appointed as a consultant to the All Party Parliamentary Group on Specialist Security and was employed to draft the inquiry report on VIP Security at the Olympic and Paralympic Games in London.<ref>[http://appgsecurity.com/downloads/VIPSecurityAtLondon2012OlympicGames.pdf VIP Security at the London 2012 Olympic and Paralympic Games, published July 2012] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140715152913/http://appgsecurity.com/downloads/VIPSecurityAtLondon2012OlympicGames.pdf |date=15 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019 Paul joined the TransPennine Route Upgrade Alliance as Business Systems Manager.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://paulwbmarsden.blogspot.com/ Paul Marsden's Blog]\n* [http://paulmarsdenmp.yolasite.com/ Paul Marsden MPs website]\n* [http://www.publicwhip.org.uk/mp.php?id=uk.org.publicwhip/member/1367&showall=yes Paul Marsden Public Whip voting record]\n* [http://politics.guardian.co.uk/person/0,9290,-3371,00.html Guardian Politics Ask Aristotle Paul Marsden]\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/2172996.stm BBC Profile of Paul Marsden]\n* [https://www.theyworkforyou.com/mp/paul_marsden/shrewsbury_and_atcham Record in Parliament for Paul Marsden]\n* [https://twitter.com/paulwbmarsden Paul Marsden on Twitter]\n* [http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/people/mr-paul-marsden Hansard 1803\u20132005: Contributions in Parliament by Paul Marsden]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{succession box\n  | title  = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for [[Shrewsbury and Atcham (UK Parliament constituency)|Shrewsbury and Atcham]]\n  | years  = [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997]]\u2013[[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005]]\n  | before = [[Derek Conway]]\n  | after  = [[Daniel Kawczynski]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Marsden, Paul}}\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:English Anglicans]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Liberal Democrats (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:People from Frodsham]]\n[[Category:Politics of Shropshire]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Teesside University]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the Open University]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1997\u20132001]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2001\u20132005]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for constituencies in Shropshire]]\n[[Category:Independent members of the House of Commons of the United Kingdom]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|the Emmerdale character|Paul Marsden (Emmerdale)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2017}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix =\n| name = Paul Marsden\n| honorific-suffix =\n| party = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] (1983\u20132001, 2005)<br />[[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]] (2001\u20132005)\n| image = Paul Marsden.jpeg\n| office = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] <br /> for [[Shrewsbury and Atcham (UK Parliament constituency)|Shrewsbury and Atcham]]\n| term_start = 1 May 1997\n| term_end = 11 April 2005\n| parliament = \n| majority = \n| predecessor = [[Derek Conway]]\n| successor = [[Daniel Kawczynski]]\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1968|3|18|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Frodsham]], [[Cheshire]]\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| nationality = [[United Kingdom|British]]\n| parents = Thomas Darlington Marsden (father), Audrey Stott (mother)\n| spouse = \n| relations =\n| children = Alexander Marsden, Richard Marsden\n| residence =\n| alma_mater = [[University of Teesside|Teesside Polytechnic]]\n| occupation = International Business Consultant\n| profession = \n| religion = Church of England\n| signature =\n| website = http://paulwbmarsden.blogspot.com\n| footnotes =\n}}\n\n'''Paul William Barry Marsden''' (born 18 March 1968) is a [[United Kingdom|British]] writer, businessman and former politician. He was the [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Shrewsbury and Atcham (UK Parliament constituency)|Shrewsbury and Atcham]] from 1997 until 2005. He was most prominently known for his anti-war views and [[crossing the floor]] twice (the first to do so since [[Winston Churchill]]<ref>[http://www.futermanrose.co.uk/marsden.html Futerman, Rose & Associates profile of Paul Marsden]</ref>), from [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] to the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]] in 2001 and returning to Labour in 2005. He instructed a solicitor in 2010 to begin action for phone hacking that allegedly took place back in 2003 by a newspaper. In 2012, Marsden was appointed to draft the parliamentary inquiry report into VIP security at the Olympic and Paralympic Games in London. Currently Marsden is Head of Business Intelligence at the construction company [[MWH Global]].<ref>[https://www.linkedin.com/in/paulwbmarsden LinkedIN profile]</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nMarsden was born in [[Frodsham]] in [[Cheshire]] to Thomas Darlington Marsden, a distribution manager and Labour councillor<ref>[http://cdnedge.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/1613340.stm ''BBC'' From disaffection to defection]</ref> and Audrey Stott, a school teacher. He was educated at [[Helsby High School]]. Marsden completed a diploma in building studies at [[Mid Cheshire College|Mid-Cheshire College]] in 1986, but withdrew from completing a civil engineering degree after the first three years at [[University of Teesside|Teesside Polytechnic]] in 1990. Studying part-time, he passed a diploma in management at the [[Open University]] and a diploma in business excellence at [[Newcastle College]].\n\nBefore his political career, Marsden worked as a quality manager at [[Taylor Woodrow]] (1990\u20131994), a management consultant at [[NatWest Bank]] (1994\u20131996) and as a total quality facilitator at [[Mitel]] from 1996 until the general election in 1997.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/2172996.stm ''BBC'' Profile of Paul Marsden 2005]</ref>\n\n== Labour Member of Parliament ==\nMarsden was elected as the first (and thus far only) Labour MP for [[Shrewsbury and Atcham (UK Parliament constituency)|Shrewsbury and Atcham]] at the [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997 general election]] with a swing of 11.4%; a seat which he held at the [[2001 United Kingdom general election|2001 election]] with a further swing of 5.5%. At 29 years of age, he was one of the youngest MP\u2019s elected in 1997. He spoke in the Commons for the first time on 21 May 1997 and in an otherwise traditional maiden speech, joked prophetically about refusing to be intimidated by the Whips.<ref>[http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/commons/1997/may/21/adjournment-of-the-house ''Hansard'' Maiden speech by Paul Marsden 21/05/97]</ref> He was nominated to serve on the Agriculture Select Committee and remained for four years quietly serving on the committee.\n\nOn 14 April 1999, Marsden introduced the Cancer Care Bill<ref>[http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/commons/1999/apr/14/cancer-care ''Hansard'' Cancer Care 14/04/99]</ref> with backing from cancer charities including [[Macmillan Cancer Support]], under the Ten Minute Rule that would create the first comprehensive directory of cancer services in the UK to aid patients in identifying the location and type of cancer care available.<ref>[http://www.hsj.co.uk/news/astonished-mp-pushes-for-cancer-register/29792.article ''Health Service Journal'' Astonished MP pushes for cancer register 29/04/99]</ref> The Bill prompted Ruth Fermor Allan to create such a directory called 'Cancer Care 2000',<ref>[http://www.whsmith.co.uk/CatalogAndSearch/SearchWithinCategory.aspx?as_Publisher=Cambridge+Healthcare+Publishing+Ltd&cat=\\Books Cancer Care 2000 by Ruth Fermor Allan]{{dead link|date=March 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> which was published by Cambridge Healthcare Publishing Ltd in November 2000.\n\nIn March 2001, Marsden with cross party support put forward a Doorstep Recycling Bill,<ref>[http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/commons/2001/mar/13/recycling-doorstep-collection ''Hansard'' Recycling (Doorstep Collection) Bill 13/03/01]</ref> mandating the collection of recyclable materials from streets. The Bill was backed by [[Friends of the Earth]]. The Bill did not succeed that year but the Government eventually backed a similar Bill by [[Joan Ruddock]] and the Municipal Waste Recycling Bill was passed in October 2003, increasing the levels of recycling of residential waste.<ref>[http://www.foe.co.uk/news/recycling_bill_success.html FoE Recycling Bill success 30/10/03]</ref>\n\nAfter a first term loyally supporting the Government, Marsden began to question the Labour Government's foreign policy following [[9/11]]. On 8 October 2001, he was the first MP in the Commons to publicly call for a vote on any [[War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)|military action]] in Afghanistan.<ref>[http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/commons/2001/oct/08/sittings-of-the-house ''Hansard'' 8 October 2001]</ref> Marsden took to sitting in [[Tony Benn]]'s former Commons seat below the gangway on the second row from the back.<ref>[http://news.scotsman.com/topstories/Unlikely-rebel-keeping-up-the.2267783.jp ''The Scotsman'' Unlikely rebel keeping up the Benn tradition 18/10/01]</ref> Two weeks later, Marsden was instructed to attend a meeting with the Labour [[Parliamentary Secretary to the Treasury|Chief Whip]], [[Hilary Armstrong]]. As [[Jeremy Paxman]] wrote, \"the Labour MP Paul Marsden took the unprecedented step of recording the dressing-down\",<ref>''The Political Animal'' by Jeremy Paxman, page 166</ref> where he said that he had been confronted with accusations that \"those aren't with us are against us,\" \"war is not a matter of conscience\" and \"it was people like you who appeased Hitler in 1938\", infuriating Marsden to going public.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2001/oct/22/uk.september11 ''The Guardian'' 'Those that are not with us are against us' 22/10/01]</ref><ref>[http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/comment/article726868.ece ''The Times'' report 5 February 2006 on Labour Chief Whip and Marsden]</ref>\n\n[[Tony Benn]] described in his diary that \"The pressure on the anti-war MPs is growing. Apparently Paul Marsden, the Labour MP for Shrewsbury and Atcham, had three-quarters-of-an-hour being bullied by the Chief Whip, Hilary Armstrong.\"<ref>[http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-483210/Tony-Benns-diaries-Blair-absolutely-capacity-deliver-promise.html ''More Time For Politics: Diaries 2001\u20132007'' by Tony Benn]</ref>\nNumber 10 were forced to put out a statement that dissenting backbenchers would be allowed to speak out on the war.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/1612211.stm ''BBC News'' 22/10/01]</ref><ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/main.jhtml?xml=/news/2001/10/23/nspin23.xml ''Daily Telegraph'' report 23 October 2001 on Marsden speaking out]</ref> The Guardian in its Leader praised Marsden for having called for a vote on the war and publishing the Chief Whip's response to it and stated, \"On both counts he has done British democracy a service.\"<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2001/oct/23/labour.terrorism ''The Guardian'' Marsden's Victory 23/10/01]</ref>\n\nUndeterred by the Whip's criticism, Marsden then spoke out against the press officer [[Jo Moore]] who had said, that [[9/11]] was \"a very good day to get out anything we want to bury\"; he and [[Tam Dalyell]] were the only two Labour MPs to vote against the Government.<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1360241/MPs-to-vote-on-Jo-Moore-row.html ''Daily Telegraph'' MPs to vote on Jo Moore row 23/10/01]</ref><ref>[http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/commons/2001/oct/23/ministerial-conduct-dtlr ''Hansard Ministerial Conduct'' 23/10/01]</ref>\n\nIn November 2001, Marsden visited [[Pakistan]] and the Afghan border to highlight the plight of [[Afghan refugees]] living in camps who had fled the war.<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/asia/afghanistan/1361987/Refugee-camps-are-hell-says-Labour-rebel.html ''Daily Telegraph'' report on Marsden being first to visit refugee camp 09/11/01]</ref> Marsden also negotiated the release of ''[[Sunday Telegraph]]'' journalist [[Christina Lamb]] and photographer Justin Sutcliffe, who had been arrested and held by the Pakistan Police and [[Inter-Services Intelligence]] secret service.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/south_asia/1651861.stm BBC News - Deported journalist 'uncovered collusion']</ref><ref>[http://articles.cnn.com/2001-11-09/world/gen.uk.journalists_1_islamabad-pakistan-quetta?_s=PM:asiapcf CNN: Pakistan detains UK journalists 09/11/01] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111123161852/http://articles.cnn.com/2001-11-09/world/gen.uk.journalists_1_islamabad-pakistan-quetta?_s=PM:asiapcf |date=23 November 2011 }}</ref> [[Christina Lamb]] thanked Marsden in the acknowledgements of her biographical book, ''The Sewing Circles of Herat'', \"Paul Marsden MP for Shrewsbury, helped rescue us from the ISI, being manhandled by Baluchistan police in the process, and kindly rearranged his whole schedule to stay in Pakistan until we were safely out.\"<ref>''The Sewing Circles of Herat'' by Christina Lamb, page x [http://www.christinalamb.net/pages/sewingcircles.html 2002] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110930112738/http://www.christinalamb.net/pages/sewingcircles.html |date=30 September 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 November 2001, Marsden was one of the leaders of the Stop the War demonstration against the war in Afghanistan in London. Marsden was one of the principal speakers along with [[Tony Benn]] and [[George Galloway]] in Trafalgar Square with 100,000 protesters.<ref>[[Protests against the War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)#2001|Protests against the war in Afghanistan 2001-]]</ref> He accused Blair of being \"drunk with power\" and \"we are not simply going to allow the atrocities of September 11 to be replaced with further atrocities in Afghanistan\".<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/1662656.stm ''BBC News'' - Thousands join anti-war march - 18/11/01]</ref>\n\nMarsden complained bitterly that he had been subjected to late night physical attacks by some Labour Whips, which were vigorously denied.<ref>[https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/top-stories/2002/04/30/john-pilger-tony-blair-s-great-betrayal-115875-21775311/ John Pilger: Tony Blair's great betrayal 30/04/02]</ref><ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/1694282.stm BBC News Colleagues 'attacked' me, says MP 05/12/01]</ref> Five days later, he [[crossing the floor|defected]] to the Liberal Democrats on 10 December 2001, citing his disagreements with Labour whips over his opposition to military action in [[Afghanistan]] and the resulting civilian casualties.<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/paul-marsden-the-oddball-and-loner-who-became-focus-of-resistance-to-blairs-allpowerful-party-machine-748033.html ''The Independent'' report leaving Labour 11/12/01]</ref><ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2001/dec/10/labour.uk2 ''The Guardian'' Key quotes from Paul Marsden 10/12/01]</ref> By crossing the floor of the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]], his actions contributed to a parliamentary vote being granted before the 2003 [[Iraq War]].{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}} The ''[[Big Issue]]'' magazine's readers voted Marsden 'Hero of the Year' in 2001 for his opposition to the war in Afghanistan.\n\n== Liberal Democrat MP and Shadow Minister ==\nIn May 2002, Marsden was promoted to Shadow Health Minister for the Liberal Democrats reporting to [[Evan Harris]], in charge of a portfolio covering mental health, prison health and aspects of cancer care.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20040225193355/http://www.libdems.org.uk/index.cfm/page.whois/section.people/wid.795/wgroup.mp Lib Dem Profile of Paul Marsden 2003]</ref>\n\nIn June 2002, Marsden presented the Prescriptions (Chronic Diseases) Bill, which aimed to introduce a fairer system for issuing prescriptions' exemptions for patients with acute conditions.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/health/2052409.stm BBC News \u2013 MP bids to scrap prescription charges \u2013 19/06/02]</ref> Although the Bill received cross party support it ran out of parliamentary time before the summer recess. The Bill received backing from the [[Cystic Fibrosis Trust]] and the National Asthma Campaign.<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/comment/letters/3578053/Prescription-injustice.html ''Daily Telegraph'' 18/06/02]</ref>\n\nIn August 2002 he visited [[Malawi]] to turn the media spotlight on the southern African famine and later he travelled to [[Johannesburg]] to lobby the [[United Nations]] conference discussing the famine affecting Southern Africa. His accusations that the failures of the [[International Monetary Fund]] had exacerbated the famine caused a public argument with the IMF Director.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/science/2002/nov/01/gm.guardianletters ''The Guardian'' Letters 01/11/02]</ref><ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2002/nov/07/famine.guardianletters?INTCMP=ILCNETTXT3487 ''The Guardian'' Letters 02/11/02]</ref>\n\nIn February 2003, prior to the [[Iraq War]], he visited the [[United States|USA]] to give a speaking tour opposing the impending war and laid a Union flag and wreath in commemoration of the victims of the [[September 11, 2001 attacks]] at Ground Zero. He also attended the [[United Nations Security Council]] session considering the looming war on 14 February. Marsden strongly opposed the war in Iraq and repeatedly voted for an inquiry into the alleged intelligence failings and concerns that parliament was misled.<ref>[http://www.publicwhip.org.uk/mp.php?mpn=Paul_Marsden&mpc=Shrewsbury_and_Atcham&house=commons&dmp=975&display=motions Public Whip votes on Iraq \u2013 Paul Marsden MP]</ref>\n\nOn the second anniversary of [[9/11]], he visited the [[Slobodan Milosevic]] trial in The Hague and met with prosecution lawyers at the [[International Criminal Court]].\n\nMarsden was declared the leading rebel on all parliamentary votes by ''The Times'' in 2003.<ref>[http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/life_and_style/article1002354.ece ''The Times'' report 28 October 2003 on website search and leading rebel]</ref>\n\nIn October 2003, Marsden was appointed the number two behind [[John Thurso]] as Shadow Transport Minister for the Liberal Democrats and nominated as a member of the Transport Select Committee.<ref>[http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/commons/2003/nov/10/transport ''Hansard'' Appointment of Paul Marsden to Transport Select Committee 10/11/03]</ref>\n\nIn April 2004, Marsden set the fifth fastest time for MPs completing the [[London Marathon]] out of forty two that have taken part since it began in 1981, with a time of 3 hours 18 minutes 1 second.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/programmes/politics_show/8017098.stm BBC News: MPs and the London Marathon 24/04/09]</ref>\n\nOn 26 August 2004, Marsden became one of only twenty cross party MPs to back the [[Impeach Blair campaign]] with the aim of holding Blair to account over the highly controversial war in Iraq. The campaign used legal counsel for advice but was unable to secure enough support for progressing the impeachment in parliament.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/3600438.stm Blair impeachment campaign starts]</ref>\n\n== Announces retirement as MP and rejoins Labour ==\nIn July 2004 Marsden announced that he was retiring from politics and would not contest the [[2005 United Kingdom general election|May 2005 general election]].<ref>[http://www.epolitix.com/latestnews/article-detail/newsarticle/marsden-to-quit-as-mp/ ''ePolitix'' - Marsden quits 28/07/04]</ref> He cited the toll suffered as a result of admissions about his private life and the effects on his family. He reduced his Liberal Democrat political duties and on 5 April 2005, within hours of the start of the election campaign, Marsden announced his intention to rejoin the Labour Party, stating that although he still disagreed with the government over the war and levels of investment in public services, he did not want to see Labour MPs who shared his views, to lose their seats.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/vote_2005/frontpage/4414967.stm ''BBC News'' MP Marsden defects back to Labour 06/04/05]</ref><ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2005/apr/08/iraq.comment Letter to ''The Guardian'' by Paul Marsden 08/04/05]</ref> He later apologised to Liberal Democrat supporters for leaving the party. He was the first British politician since [[Winston Churchill]] to re-cross the floor of the House of Commons and return to his original party, in Marsden's case to sit on the Labour benches.<ref>[http://www.futermanrose.co.uk/marsden.html Futerman, Rose & Associates profile of Paul Marsden]</ref>\n\nDuring his Parliamentary career Marsden raised over \u00a310K for local and international charities through sponsored [[Marathon|marathon running]], [[abseiling]] and [[Swimming (sport)|swimming]].<ref>[http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/uk/article826231.ece ''The Times''  More charity events hit by VAT cash grab 16/04/04]</ref>\n\nIn the [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005 general election]] the Conservative, [[Daniel Kawczynski]] won back the Shrewsbury and Atcham seat from the subsequent Labour candidate, Michael Ion.\n\n== Expenses ==\nAlthough MPs expenses were published after Marsden had left parliament, expenses claims were backdated to the time when he was a sitting MP. [[Sir Thomas Legg]] gave Marsden a clean bill of health and reported that he was one of only a minority of MPs and ex-MPs with \"no issues\".<ref>[https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200910/cmselect/cmmemest/348/348.pdf Review of Past ACA Payments by Sir Thomas Legg 2010 page 162]</ref>\n\n== Post-Parliamentary career ==\nBefore retiring from politics, Marsden co-authored the book ''Voices for Peace'' published by [[Simon & Schuster]] in 2001. Four years later he researched and published a local history book, ''[[The Blackfriars of Shrewsbury]]'' and returned to business consultancy in 2005.  He also wrote more anti-war poetry.\n\nIn December 2005, Marsden caused a row when he publicly confirmed [[Charles Kennedy]]'s drinking problems and that Kennedy had not been telling the truth about his illness. Kennedy's press secretary vehemently denied Marsden's story.<ref>[http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/news/politics/article2031886.ece ''The Times'' 19/12/05]</ref> However, by 5 January 2006, Kennedy admitted he had \"a drink problem\" and had sought \"professional help\".<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/4582930.stm BBC News 05/01/06]</ref> He resigned two days later as leader.\n\nIn 2007, Marsden was appointed Director of Policy at the [[British Union for the Abolition of Vivisection]]<ref>[https://archive.is/20120913024153/http://www.thirdsector.co.uk/news/archive/754107/Movers-Paul-Marsden-policy-director-BUAV/ Movers: Paul Marsden, Policy Director, BUAV Third Sector 24/10/07]</ref> and between 2008 and 2010 was the CEO of the Painting and Decorating Association.<ref>[http://www.journalism.co.uk/press-releases/trade-body-appoints-new-chief-executive/s66/a533204/ Trade body appoints new Chief Executive 13/01/09]</ref>\n\nIn May 2009, Marsden applied to rejoin the Labour Party but was provisionally blocked by the National Executive and is not presently a member of any political party.\n\nIn September 2010, Marsden's war poem, ''Eighty at Ligny'' was used in l'exposition historique for the British World War I war cemetery in memory of the eighty British, Irish and Canadian soldiers who are buried in [[Ligny-sur-Canche]]. In 2010, Marsden returned to business consultancy, working as a consultant for a trade conference.\n\nIn January 2011, it was reported that Marsden had commenced legal enquiries into allegations of hacking into his phone back in 2003. A suspended reporter who worked at the ''[[Sunday Mirror]]'' and then the ''[[News of the World]]'' was claimed to be involved.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-12271690 BBC News: report 24 January 2011 on phone hacking]</ref> A Channel 4 ''Dispatches'' programme interviewed Marsden and it was revealed that the reporter in question, had been suspended for phone hacking, although he denied it.<ref>[http://www.channel4.com/programmes/dispatches/episode-guide/series-79/episode-1 Channel 4 ''Dispatches'' 07/02/11]</ref> It was the first time that a newspaper other than the ''[[News of the World]]'' had been cited in connection with allegations of phone hacking.<ref>[[News of the World phone hacking affair]]</ref>{{better source|reason=Wikipedia is not a reliable source!|date=July 2018}}\n\nIn May 2011, Marsden wrote on his Blog, www.paulwbmarsden.blogspot.com,<ref>[http://paulwbmarsden.blogspot.com/2011/05/privacy-vs-public-interest.html]</ref> an article about the debate on public interest vs privacy in which he mentioned the allegations that [[Ryan Giggs]] was the footballer who had taken out a [[Injunction#UK superinjunctions|super injunction]] against [[Imogen Thomas]]. His Blog was written before [[John Hemming (politician)|John Hemming]] revealed the [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] player's name under parliamentary privilege.<ref>[http://www.shropshirestar.com/news/2011/05/26/former-shrewsbury-mp-defiant-over-giggs-naming/]</ref>\n\nIn July 2012, Marsden was appointed as a consultant to the All Party Parliamentary Group on Specialist Security and was employed to draft the inquiry report on VIP Security at the Olympic and Paralympic Games in London.<ref>[http://appgsecurity.com/downloads/VIPSecurityAtLondon2012OlympicGames.pdf VIP Security at the London 2012 Olympic and Paralympic Games, published July 2012] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140715152913/http://appgsecurity.com/downloads/VIPSecurityAtLondon2012OlympicGames.pdf |date=15 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019 Paul joined the TransPennine Route Upgrade Alliance as Business Systems Manager.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://paulwbmarsden.blogspot.com/ Paul Marsden's Blog]\n* [http://paulmarsdenmp.yolasite.com/ Paul Marsden MPs website]\n* [http://www.publicwhip.org.uk/mp.php?id=uk.org.publicwhip/member/1367&showall=yes Paul Marsden Public Whip voting record]\n* [http://politics.guardian.co.uk/person/0,9290,-3371,00.html Guardian Politics Ask Aristotle Paul Marsden]\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/2172996.stm BBC Profile of Paul Marsden]\n* [https://www.theyworkforyou.com/mp/paul_marsden/shrewsbury_and_atcham Record in Parliament for Paul Marsden]\n* [https://twitter.com/paulwbmarsden Paul Marsden on Twitter]\n* [http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/people/mr-paul-marsden Hansard 1803\u20132005: Contributions in Parliament by Paul Marsden]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{succession box\n  | title  = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for [[Shrewsbury and Atcham (UK Parliament constituency)|Shrewsbury and Atcham]]\n  | years  = [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997]]\u2013[[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005]]\n  | before = [[Derek Conway]]\n  | after  = [[Daniel Kawczynski]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Marsden, Paul}}\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:English Anglicans]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Liberal Democrats (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:People from Frodsham]]\n[[Category:Politics of Shropshire]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Teesside University]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the Open University]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1997\u20132001]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2001\u20132005]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for constituencies in Shropshire]]\n[[Category:Independent members of the House of Commons of the United Kingdom]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLabour Member of Parliament:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paul_Marsden"}
{"title_page": "Linda Tripp", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2015}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name          = Linda Tripp\n|image         = \n|image_size    = \n|caption       = \n|birth_name    = Linda Rose Carotenuto\n|birth_date    = {{birth date|1949|11|24}}\n|birth_place   = [[Jersey City, New Jersey]], U.S.\n|death_date    = {{death date and age|2020|04|08|1949|11|24}}\n|death_place   = \n|other_names   = \n|citizenship   = \n|education     = [[Hanover Park High School]]\n|alma_mater    = \n|occupation    = [[Civil servant|Former civil servant]], [[small business|small business owner]]\n|employer      = \n|known_for     = Whistleblower in Clinton-Lewinsky Scandal\n|ethnicity     = \n}}\n\n'''Linda Rose Tripp''' (n\u00e9e '''Carotenuto'''; November 24, 1949 \u2013 April 8, 2020) was an American [[civil servant]] who played a prominent role in the [[Clinton\u2013Lewinsky scandal]] of 1998. Tripp's action in secretly recording [[Monica Lewinsky]]'s confidential phone calls about her relationship with the president caused a sensation with their links to the earlier ''[[Clinton v. Jones]]'' lawsuit and with the disclosing of notably intimate details. Tripp claimed that her motives were purely patriotic, and she was able to avoid a wiretap charge in exchange for handing in the tapes. She then claimed that her firing from [[the Pentagon]] at the end of the Clinton administration was vindictive, while the administration claimed it to be a standard routine. Since then, Tripp worked with her husband in a retail business in [[Middleburg, Virginia]].{{Citation needed|date=September 2018}}\n\n==Early life==\nTripp graduated in 1968 from [[Hanover Park High School]] in [[East Hanover, New Jersey]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://infoweb.newsbank.com/iw-search/we/InfoWeb?p_action=doc&p_docid=0EFD502D5C99C190&p_docnum=2&p_queryname=NaN&p_product=NewsBank&p_theme=aggregated4&p_nbid=J4BH4EDFMTE4NTg0NzQ0OS4yODY4NjU6MTo3OnJhLTE4ODg|title=The Ultimate New Jersey High School Yearbook: T-Z And Also...|work=[[The Star-Ledger]]|date=June 27, 1999|accessdate=August 4, 2007|publisher=Newsbank.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100804161334/http://infoweb.newsbank.com/iw-search/we/InfoWeb?p_action=doc|archive-date=August 4, 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref> She was an [[Military Intelligence Corps (United States Army)|Army Intelligence]] secretary at [[Fort George G. Meade|Fort Meade]] before being transferred to [[the Pentagon]] in 1987.\n\n==Government employment==\nTripp was a [[White House]] employee in the [[George H. W. Bush]] administration, and kept her job when [[Bill Clinton]] took over in 1993. During the summer of 1994, senior White House aides wanted Tripp out, so they arranged a job for her in the public affairs office in the Pentagon which gave her a raise of $20,000 per year.<ref>Goldstein, Amy; and Sanchez, Rene. [https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/politics/special/clinton/stories/tripp020798.htm \"Tripp's Curious Path to the Pentagon\"], ''[[The Washington Post]]'', February 7, 1998, p. A12. Accessed October 9, 2007.</ref>\n\n==Involvement in the Clinton\u2013Lewinsky scandal==\nTripp became a close confidante of another former White House employee, [[Monica Lewinsky]], while they both worked in the Pentagon's public affairs office. According to Tripp, who is about 24 years older than Lewinsky, they knew one another for a year and a half before the scandal began to reach its critical stage. After Lewinsky revealed to Tripp that she had been in a physical relationship with President Clinton, Tripp, acting on the advice of literary agent [[Lucianne Goldberg]], began to secretly record phone conversations with Lewinsky while encouraging Lewinsky to document details of her relationship with the president.\n\nIn August 1997, [[Michael Isikoff]], from ''[[Newsweek]]'', reported that Tripp said that she had encountered [[Kathleen Willey]] coming out of the Oval Office \"disheveled,\" with \"her face red and her lipstick was off.\" Willey alleged that Clinton groped her. Clinton's lawyer [[Robert S. Bennett]] said in the ''Newsweek'' article, \"Linda Tripp is not to be believed.\"<ref>[[Michael Isikoff|Isikoff, Michael]] and Thomas, Evan. [https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/politics/special/clinton/stories/nwcover012698b.htm \"Clinton and the Intern\"], ''[[Newsweek]]'', February 2, 1998. Accessed October 9, 2007.</ref>\n\nIn January 1998, Tripp gave the surreptitiously recorded tapes to then-[[Independent Counsel]] [[Kenneth Starr]] in exchange for [[immunity from prosecution]]. Tripp disclosed to Starr that she was aware of the relationship between Lewinsky and President Clinton, that Lewinsky had executed a false [[affidavit]] denying the relationship that was submitted to the federal court in Arkansas in the ''[[Clinton v. Jones]]'' lawsuit, and that Lewinsky had attempted to [[Subornation of perjury|suborn]] Tripp's [[perjury]] in the ''Clinton v. Jones'' suit to conceal the Clinton-Lewinsky relationship as well as Tripp's claim regarding Kathleen Willey from the federal court. As Tripp explained, she was being solicited to commit a crime to conceal evidence in the Jones civil rights case.<ref name=LarryKing>[http://www.cnn.com/ALLPOLITICS/stories/1999/02/16/tripp.transcript/ Transcript: Linda Tripp on 'Larry King Live'], ''[[CNN]]'', February 16, 1999. Accessed October 9, 2007.</ref> Jones\u2019 lawsuit, initially filed in April 1994 through her attorneys Joseph Cammarata and Gilbert K. Davis, eventually resulted in the [[landmark]] [[U.S. Supreme Court]] decision in [[Clinton v. Jones]] that a sitting President of the United States does not have [[Legal immunity|immunity]] against civil lawsuits for acts done before taking office, and unrelated to the office.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/520/681/|title=Clinton v. Jones, 520 U.S. 681 (1997)|website=Justia Law}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://law.justia.com/cases/federal/district-courts/FSupp/858/902/2253460/|title=Jones v. Clinton, 858 F. Supp. 902 (E.D. Ark. 1994)|website=Justia Law}}</ref>\n\nTripp also informed Starr of the existence of a navy blue dress that Lewinsky owned that was soiled with Clinton's [[semen]]. During their friendship, Lewinsky had shown the dress to Tripp and said she intended to have it [[Dry cleaning|dry-cleaned]]; Tripp convinced her not to.\n\nBased on Tripp's tapes, Starr obtained approval from [[United States Attorney General|Attorney General]] [[Janet Reno]] and the special court overseeing the Independent Counsel to expand Starr's investigation into the Clinton-Lewinsky relationship, looking for potential incidents of perjury, to investigate Lewinsky for perjury and suborning perjury as a witness in the lawsuit [[Paula Jones]] had brought against Clinton.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/politics/special/clinton/stories/text012998.htm |title=Text of Reno's Petition for Starr |date=January 29, 1998 |accessdate=May 1, 2008 | work=The Washington Post}}</ref>\n\nTripp also told Starr that she had evidence directly linking the White House to the [[Travelgate]], [[Filegate]], and [[1996 United States campaign finance controversy|Chinagate]] affairs, but Starr chose not to act on that, preferring to pursue the sex-related allegations.\n\nTripp maintains she acted out of \"patriotic duty.\" Tripp has claimed that she taped Lewinsky out of self-defense, as she feared retaliation from the Clinton administration, also claiming Lewinsky had assured President Clinton that she had told only Tripp about their affair (which was untrue), thus making her a target since she refused to go along with perjuring herself to protect Lewinsky and the President.\n\nEventually both Clinton and Lewinsky had to appear before a [[Washington, D.C.]], [[grand jury]] to answer questions, although Clinton appeared via [[closed circuit television]]. After the round of interrogation, the jurors offered Lewinsky the chance to offer any last words. \"I hate Linda Tripp,\" she said.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/ALLPOLITICS/stories/1998/09/22/tripp/ |title=What goes around comes around? Tripp's under investigation |date=September 22, 1998 |accessdate=February 4, 2016 | work=CNN | first=Brooks | last=Jackson}}</ref>\n\n===Indictment by the state of Maryland===\nTripp was a resident of [[Columbia, Maryland]], at the time she made her surreptitious recordings of the conversations with Lewinsky, and 49 Democrats in the [[Maryland Legislature]] signed a letter to the state prosecutor demanding that Tripp be prosecuted under Maryland's [[telephone tapping|wiretap]] law.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/politics/special/clinton/stories/starr072398.htm |title=Grand Jury Hears Currie; Official Defends Tripp Probe |accessdate=May 1, 2008 |date=July 23, 1998 |publisher=The Washington Post}}</ref> Before the trial, the state court ruled that because of the immunity agreements which the Independent Counsel's office entered into with Tripp, Lewinsky, and others, a substantial amount of the evidence which the prosecution intended to use was inadmissible.\n\nAt a pre-trial hearing, the prosecution called Lewinsky as a witness to try to establish that her testimony against Tripp was untainted by the Independent Counsel investigation. However, the Maryland state court ruled that Lewinsky, who \"admitted that she lied under oath in a federal proceeding and has stated that lying has been a part of her life,\" was not credible and Lewinsky's proposed testimony against Tripp was \"bathed in impermissible taint.\" As a result, all charges against Tripp were dismissed on May 26, 2000, when the prosecution decided not to proceed with the trial of the case.<ref>Lewis, Neil A. [https://www.nytimes.com/2000/05/06/us/judge-allows-maryland-to-proceed-in-tripp-case.html \u201cJudge Allows Maryland To Proceed in Tripp Case\u201d], \u201c[[The New York Times]]\u201d, May 6, 2000. Accessed November 28, 2018.</ref>\n\n===Arrest record controversy===\nOn March 14, 1998, it was revealed that Linda Tripp was arrested when she was 19 years old in [[Greenwood Lake, New York]], in 1969 on charges of [[Larceny|stealing]] $263 in cash as well as a wristwatch worth about $600. The charges were eventually dismissed before coming to trial.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cnn.com/ALLPOLITICS/1998/03/14/tripp.lewinsky/ |date=March 14, 1998 |accessdate=May 1, 2008 |title=Report: Tripp Didn't Disclose Arrest On Pentagon Job Form | work=CNN}}</ref> Years later, Tripp answered \"no\" to the question \"Have you ever been either charged or arrested for a crime?\" on her [[United States Department of Defense|Department of Defense]] security clearance form.<ref>[http://www.cnn.com/ALLPOLITICS/1998/06/29/tripp.bio/ Tripp: No Stranger To Controversy \u2013 June 29, 1998]. Cnn.com (June 29, 1998). Retrieved on 2015-10-14.</ref>\n\nShortly before Tripp was scheduled to appear before the [[grand jury]] in the Lewinsky investigation, in March 1998, Assistant Secretary of Defense for Public Affairs [[Kenneth Bacon]] and his deputy, Clifford Bernath, leaked to reporter [[Jane Mayer]] of ''[[The New Yorker]]'' Tripp's answer to the arrest question on her security clearance form. Following the Bacon\u2013Bernath leak to Mayer, the Department of Defense leaked to the news media other confidential information from Tripp's personnel and security files. The Department of Defense Inspector General investigated the leak of Tripp's security clearance form information and found that Bacon and Bernath violated the Privacy Act, and the DoD IG concluded that Bacon and Bernath should have known that the release of information from Tripp's security file was improper.<ref>Becker, Elizabeth. [https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9403E6D7123DF935A15756C0A9669C8B63 \"2 Officials Rebuked for Tripp Disclosures\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', May 26, 2000. Accessed November 12, 2007.</ref>\n\n===Termination from government employment===\nOn January 19, 2001, the last full day of the [[Clinton Administration]], Linda Tripp was fired from her job in the Pentagon.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archives.cnn.com/2001/ALLPOLITICS/stories/01/19/tripp.fired.03/index.html |title=Linda Tripp, like many others, loses federal job |publisher=[[CNN]] |date=January 19, 2001 |accessdate=2016-02-04 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20041207191131/http://archives.cnn.com/2001/ALLPOLITICS/stories/01/19/tripp.fired.03/index.html |archivedate=December 7, 2004 }}</ref> Tripp claimed that the firing was vindictive, but the Clinton administration said that all political appointees such as Tripp are normally asked to submit their resignation upon a new administration taking over.<ref>{{cite web | title=U.S. ambassadors appointed by Obama must quit by Inauguration Day | website=[[Reuters]] | date=January 6, 2017 | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-diplomats/u-s-envoys-appointed-by-obama-denied-extensions-past-inauguration-day-new-york-times-idUSKBN14Q0DU | access-date=November 15, 2017}}</ref> Those who refuse may be fired.\n\n===Lawsuit and settlement===\nTripp sued the [[United States Department of Defense|Department of Defense]] and the Justice Department for releasing information from her security file and employment file to the news media in violation of the [[Privacy Act of 1974]]. On November 3, 2003, Tripp reached a settlement with the federal government.<ref>\"[https://www.usatoday.com/news/washington/2003-11-03-tripp-lawsuit_x.htm Defense Department settles with Linda Tripp],\" ''USA Today'' (11/3/2003 9:35 PM).</ref>  The settlement included a one-time payment of more than $595,000, a retroactive promotion, and retroactive pay at the highest salary for 1998, 1999, and 2000. She also received a pension and was cleared to work for the federal government again. Her rights to remain part of a [[class action]] against the government were also preserved.\n\n==Life after the Clinton\u2013Lewinsky scandal==\nTripp was portrayed by [[John Goodman]] in recurring ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'' sketches. Tripp was amused by most of Goodman's impersonations of her, except for one, which hurt her feelings.<ref name=LarryKing/>\n\nSince the Clinton\u2013Lewinsky scandal, Tripp moved to Northern Virginia, married German architect Dieter Rausch in 2004 and later relocated to [[Middleburg, Virginia]].{{Citation needed|date=September 2018}}\n\nIn an appearance with [[Larry King]] on ''[[Larry King Live]]'' on December 1, 2003, Tripp talked about living with [[breast cancer]]. On the subject of her successful invasion of privacy lawsuit against the federal government, Tripp claimed that she actually came out behind financially because of attorneys' fees and the derailment of her government career. She also claimed that her violations of Lewinsky's privacy and the Clinton administration's violations of her privacy were not equivalent, as the Clinton administration's leaking of her employment history was illegal \u2014 noting that although her wiretapping was also illegal, she was able to avoid prosecution for such by accepting immunity in exchange for her testimony.<ref>[http://transcripts.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/0312/01/lkl.00.html CNN Larry King Live Interview With Linda Tripp] (Aired December 1, 2003)</ref>\n\n''[[The Washington Post]]'' reported that at an event in 2018, Tripp \u2014 in her first public address since 2000 \u2014 said \"she was the victim of 'a real high-tech lynching'\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Andrews-Dyer |first1=Helena |title=Linda Tripp says she was the victim of \u2018a real high-tech lynching\u2019 in first public address since 2000 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/reliable-source/wp/2018/07/30/linda-tripp-says-she-was-the-victim-of-a-real-high-tech-lynching-in-first-public-address-since-2000/?noredirect=on |work=Washington Post |date=July 30, 2018 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn the upcoming television series ''[[American Crime Story|Impeachment: American Crime Story]]'', Tripp will be portrayed by [[Sarah Paulson]].{{citation needed|date = April 2020}}</ref>\n\nTripp died from [[pancreatic cancer]] at the age of 70 on April 8, 2020.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Moore |first1=Mark |last2=Nelson |first2=Steven |title=Linda Tripp, whistleblower in Clinton-Lewinsky sex scandal, dead at 70 |url=https://nypost.com/2020/04/08/linda-tripp-whistleblower-in-lewinsky-scandal-near-death/ |website=New York Post |language=en |date= April 8, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url = https://www.ajc.com/news/breaking-linda-tripp-whistleblower-clinton-sex-scandal-dead-from-pancreatic-cancer/LGXMbINXPoywbGzpOJCHuI/|title = BREAKING: Linda Tripp, whistleblower in Clinton sex scandal, dead at 70 from cancer |last = Darnell|first = Tim|date = April 8, 2020|accessdate = April 8, 2020|work = [[The Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite encyclopedia| title=Linda Tripp (Biography)| author=Scott P. Johnson| encyclopedia=Trials of the Century: An Encyclopedia of Popular Culture and the Law, Volume 1 ([[ABC-CLIO]] 2010) | pages=654\u2013655 }}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{Cite news|url=http://www.slate.com/articles/podcasts/slow_burn/2018/09/linda_tripp_who_taped_monica_lewinsky_on_slow_burn.html|title=Tell-All. Linda Tripp exposed Bill Clinton\u2019s affair with Monica Lewinsky. What was she thinking?|last=Neyfakh|first=Leon|date=2018-09-12|work=Slate|language=en-US|issn=1091-2339}} (Podcast based on a 2018 interview with Tripp)\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tripp, Linda}}\n[[Category:1949 births]]\n[[Category:American civil servants]]\n[[Category:Breast cancer survivors]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from East Hanover, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:People from Jersey City, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:People from Middleburg, Virginia]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Virginia]]\n[[Category:Women whistleblowers]]\n[[Category:Clinton\u2013Lewinsky scandal]]\n[[Category:Deaths from pancreatic cancer]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2015}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name          = Linda Tripp\n|image         = \n|image_size    = \n|caption       = \n|birth_name    = Linda Rose Carotenuto\n|birth_date    = {{birth date|1949|11|24}}\n|birth_place   = [[Jersey City, New Jersey]], U.S.\n|death_date    = {{death date and age|2020|04|08|1949|11|24}}\n|death_place   = \n|other_names   = \n|citizenship   = \n|education     = [[Hanover Park High School]]\n|alma_mater    = \n|occupation    = [[Civil servant|Former civil servant]], [[small business|small business owner]]\n|employer      = \n|known_for     = Whistleblower in Clinton-Lewinsky Scandal\n|ethnicity     = \n}}\n\n'''Linda Rose Tripp''' (n\u00e9e '''Carotenuto'''; November 24, 1949 \u2013 April 8, 2020) was an American [[civil servant]] who played a prominent role in the [[Clinton\u2013Lewinsky scandal]] of 1998. Tripp's action in secretly recording [[Monica Lewinsky]]'s confidential phone calls about her relationship with the president caused a sensation with their links to the earlier ''[[Clinton v. Jones]]'' lawsuit and with the disclosing of notably intimate details. Tripp claimed that her motives were purely patriotic, and she was able to avoid a wiretap charge in exchange for handing in the tapes. She then claimed that her firing from [[the Pentagon]] at the end of the Clinton administration was vindictive, while the administration claimed it to be a standard routine. Since then, Tripp worked with her husband in a retail business in [[Middleburg, Virginia]].{{Citation needed|date=September 2018}}\n\n==Early life==\nTripp graduated in 1968 from [[Hanover Park High School]] in [[East Hanover, New Jersey]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://infoweb.newsbank.com/iw-search/we/InfoWeb?p_action=doc&p_docid=0EFD502D5C99C190&p_docnum=2&p_queryname=NaN&p_product=NewsBank&p_theme=aggregated4&p_nbid=J4BH4EDFMTE4NTg0NzQ0OS4yODY4NjU6MTo3OnJhLTE4ODg|title=The Ultimate New Jersey High School Yearbook: T-Z And Also...|work=[[The Star-Ledger]]|date=June 27, 1999|accessdate=August 4, 2007|publisher=Newsbank.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100804161334/http://infoweb.newsbank.com/iw-search/we/InfoWeb?p_action=doc|archive-date=August 4, 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref> She was an [[Military Intelligence Corps (United States Army)|Army Intelligence]] secretary at [[Fort George G. Meade|Fort Meade]] before being transferred to [[the Pentagon]] in 1987.\n\n==Government employment==\nTripp was a [[White House]] employee in the [[George H. W. Bush]] administration, and kept her job when [[Bill Clinton]] took over in 1993. During the summer of 1994, senior White House aides wanted Tripp out, so they arranged a job for her in the public affairs office in the Pentagon which gave her a raise of $20,000 per year.<ref>Goldstein, Amy; and Sanchez, Rene. [https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/politics/special/clinton/stories/tripp020798.htm \"Tripp's Curious Path to the Pentagon\"], ''[[The Washington Post]]'', February 7, 1998, p. A12. Accessed October 9, 2007.</ref>\n\n==Involvement in the Clinton\u2013Lewinsky scandal==\nTripp became a close confidante of another former White House employee, [[Monica Lewinsky]], while they both worked in the Pentagon's public affairs office. According to Tripp, who is about 24 years older than Lewinsky, they knew one another for a year and a half before the scandal began to reach its critical stage. After Lewinsky revealed to Tripp that she had been in a physical relationship with President Clinton, Tripp, acting on the advice of literary agent [[Lucianne Goldberg]], began to secretly record phone conversations with Lewinsky while encouraging Lewinsky to document details of her relationship with the president.\n\nIn August 1997, [[Michael Isikoff]], from ''[[Newsweek]]'', reported that Tripp said that she had encountered [[Kathleen Willey]] coming out of the Oval Office \"disheveled,\" with \"her face red and her lipstick was off.\" Willey alleged that Clinton groped her. Clinton's lawyer [[Robert S. Bennett]] said in the ''Newsweek'' article, \"Linda Tripp is not to be believed.\"<ref>[[Michael Isikoff|Isikoff, Michael]] and Thomas, Evan. [https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/politics/special/clinton/stories/nwcover012698b.htm \"Clinton and the Intern\"], ''[[Newsweek]]'', February 2, 1998. Accessed October 9, 2007.</ref>\n\nIn January 1998, Tripp gave the surreptitiously recorded tapes to then-[[Independent Counsel]] [[Kenneth Starr]] in exchange for [[immunity from prosecution]]. Tripp disclosed to Starr that she was aware of the relationship between Lewinsky and President Clinton, that Lewinsky had executed a false [[affidavit]] denying the relationship that was submitted to the federal court in Arkansas in the ''[[Clinton v. Jones]]'' lawsuit, and that Lewinsky had attempted to [[Subornation of perjury|suborn]] Tripp's [[perjury]] in the ''Clinton v. Jones'' suit to conceal the Clinton-Lewinsky relationship as well as Tripp's claim regarding Kathleen Willey from the federal court. As Tripp explained, she was being solicited to commit a crime to conceal evidence in the Jones civil rights case.<ref name=LarryKing>[http://www.cnn.com/ALLPOLITICS/stories/1999/02/16/tripp.transcript/ Transcript: Linda Tripp on 'Larry King Live'], ''[[CNN]]'', February 16, 1999. Accessed October 9, 2007.</ref> Jones\u2019 lawsuit, initially filed in April 1994 through her attorneys Joseph Cammarata and Gilbert K. Davis, eventually resulted in the [[landmark]] [[U.S. Supreme Court]] decision in [[Clinton v. Jones]] that a sitting President of the United States does not have [[Legal immunity|immunity]] against civil lawsuits for acts done before taking office, and unrelated to the office.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/520/681/|title=Clinton v. Jones, 520 U.S. 681 (1997)|website=Justia Law}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://law.justia.com/cases/federal/district-courts/FSupp/858/902/2253460/|title=Jones v. Clinton, 858 F. Supp. 902 (E.D. Ark. 1994)|website=Justia Law}}</ref>\n\nTripp also informed Starr of the existence of a navy blue dress that Lewinsky owned that was soiled with Clinton's [[semen]]. During their friendship, Lewinsky had shown the dress to Tripp and said she intended to have it [[Dry cleaning|dry-cleaned]]; Tripp convinced her not to.\n\nBased on Tripp's tapes, Starr obtained approval from [[United States Attorney General|Attorney General]] [[Janet Reno]] and the special court overseeing the Independent Counsel to expand Starr's investigation into the Clinton-Lewinsky relationship, looking for potential incidents of perjury, to investigate Lewinsky for perjury and suborning perjury as a witness in the lawsuit [[Paula Jones]] had brought against Clinton.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/politics/special/clinton/stories/text012998.htm |title=Text of Reno's Petition for Starr |date=January 29, 1998 |accessdate=May 1, 2008 | work=The Washington Post}}</ref>\n\nTripp also told Starr that she had evidence directly linking the White House to the [[Travelgate]], [[Filegate]], and [[1996 United States campaign finance controversy|Chinagate]] affairs, but Starr chose not to act on that, preferring to pursue the sex-related allegations.\n\nTripp maintains she acted out of \"patriotic duty.\" Tripp has claimed that she taped Lewinsky out of self-defense, as she feared retaliation from the Clinton administration, also claiming Lewinsky had assured President Clinton that she had told only Tripp about their affair (which was untrue), thus making her a target since she refused to go along with perjuring herself to protect Lewinsky and the President.\n\nEventually both Clinton and Lewinsky had to appear before a [[Washington, D.C.]], [[grand jury]] to answer questions, although Clinton appeared via [[closed circuit television]]. After the round of interrogation, the jurors offered Lewinsky the chance to offer any last words. \"I hate Linda Tripp,\" she said.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/ALLPOLITICS/stories/1998/09/22/tripp/ |title=What goes around comes around? Tripp's under investigation |date=September 22, 1998 |accessdate=February 4, 2016 | work=CNN | first=Brooks | last=Jackson}}</ref>\n\n===Indictment by the state of Maryland===\nTripp was a resident of [[Columbia, Maryland]], at the time she made her surreptitious recordings of the conversations with Lewinsky, and 49 Democrats in the [[Maryland Legislature]] signed a letter to the state prosecutor demanding that Tripp be prosecuted under Maryland's [[telephone tapping|wiretap]] law.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/politics/special/clinton/stories/starr072398.htm |title=Grand Jury Hears Currie; Official Defends Tripp Probe |accessdate=May 1, 2008 |date=July 23, 1998 |publisher=The Washington Post}}</ref> Before the trial, the state court ruled that because of the immunity agreements which the Independent Counsel's office entered into with Tripp, Lewinsky, and others, a substantial amount of the evidence which the prosecution intended to use was inadmissible.\n\nAt a pre-trial hearing, the prosecution called Lewinsky as a witness to try to establish that her testimony against Tripp was untainted by the Independent Counsel investigation. However, the Maryland state court ruled that Lewinsky, who \"admitted that she lied under oath in a federal proceeding and has stated that lying has been a part of her life,\" was not credible and Lewinsky's proposed testimony against Tripp was \"bathed in impermissible taint.\" As a result, all charges against Tripp were dismissed on May 26, 2000, when the prosecution decided not to proceed with the trial of the case.<ref>Lewis, Neil A. [https://www.nytimes.com/2000/05/06/us/judge-allows-maryland-to-proceed-in-tripp-case.html \u201cJudge Allows Maryland To Proceed in Tripp Case\u201d], \u201c[[The New York Times]]\u201d, May 6, 2000. Accessed November 28, 2018.</ref>\n\n===Arrest record controversy===\nOn March 14, 1998, it was revealed that Linda Tripp was arrested when she was 19 years old in [[Greenwood Lake, New York]], in 1969 on charges of [[Larceny|stealing]] $263 in cash as well as a wristwatch worth about $600. The charges were eventually dismissed before coming to trial.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cnn.com/ALLPOLITICS/1998/03/14/tripp.lewinsky/ |date=March 14, 1998 |accessdate=May 1, 2008 |title=Report: Tripp Didn't Disclose Arrest On Pentagon Job Form | work=CNN}}</ref> Years later, Tripp answered \"no\" to the question \"Have you ever been either charged or arrested for a crime?\" on her [[United States Department of Defense|Department of Defense]] security clearance form.<ref>[http://www.cnn.com/ALLPOLITICS/1998/06/29/tripp.bio/ Tripp: No Stranger To Controversy \u2013 June 29, 1998]. Cnn.com (June 29, 1998). Retrieved on 2015-10-14.</ref>\n\nShortly before Tripp was scheduled to appear before the [[grand jury]] in the Lewinsky investigation, in March 1998, Assistant Secretary of Defense for Public Affairs [[Kenneth Bacon]] and his deputy, Clifford Bernath, leaked to reporter [[Jane Mayer]] of ''[[The New Yorker]]'' Tripp's answer to the arrest question on her security clearance form. Following the Bacon\u2013Bernath leak to Mayer, the Department of Defense leaked to the news media other confidential information from Tripp's personnel and security files. The Department of Defense Inspector General investigated the leak of Tripp's security clearance form information and found that Bacon and Bernath violated the Privacy Act, and the DoD IG concluded that Bacon and Bernath should have known that the release of information from Tripp's security file was improper.<ref>Becker, Elizabeth. [https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9403E6D7123DF935A15756C0A9669C8B63 \"2 Officials Rebuked for Tripp Disclosures\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', May 26, 2000. Accessed November 12, 2007.</ref>\n\n===Termination from government employment===\nOn January 19, 2001, the last full day of the [[Clinton Administration]], Linda Tripp was fired from her job in the Pentagon.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archives.cnn.com/2001/ALLPOLITICS/stories/01/19/tripp.fired.03/index.html |title=Linda Tripp, like many others, loses federal job |publisher=[[CNN]] |date=January 19, 2001 |accessdate=2016-02-04 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20041207191131/http://archives.cnn.com/2001/ALLPOLITICS/stories/01/19/tripp.fired.03/index.html |archivedate=December 7, 2004 }}</ref> Tripp claimed that the firing was vindictive, but the Clinton administration said that all political appointees such as Tripp are normally asked to submit their resignation upon a new administration taking over.<ref>{{cite web | title=U.S. ambassadors appointed by Obama must quit by Inauguration Day | website=[[Reuters]] | date=January 6, 2017 | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-diplomats/u-s-envoys-appointed-by-obama-denied-extensions-past-inauguration-day-new-york-times-idUSKBN14Q0DU | access-date=November 15, 2017}}</ref> Those who refuse may be fired.\n\n===Lawsuit and settlement===\nTripp sued the [[United States Department of Defense|Department of Defense]] and the Justice Department for releasing information from her security file and employment file to the news media in violation of the [[Privacy Act of 1974]]. On November 3, 2003, Tripp reached a settlement with the federal government.<ref>\"[https://www.usatoday.com/news/washington/2003-11-03-tripp-lawsuit_x.htm Defense Department settles with Linda Tripp],\" ''USA Today'' (11/3/2003 9:35 PM).</ref>  The settlement included a one-time payment of more than $595,000, a retroactive promotion, and retroactive pay at the highest salary for 1998, 1999, and 2000. She also received a pension and was cleared to work for the federal government again. Her rights to remain part of a [[class action]] against the government were also preserved.\n\n==Life after the Clinton\u2013Lewinsky scandal==\nTripp was portrayed by [[John Goodman]] in recurring ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'' sketches. Tripp was amused by most of Goodman's impersonations of her, except for one, which hurt her feelings.<ref name=LarryKing/>\n\nSince the Clinton\u2013Lewinsky scandal, Tripp moved to Northern Virginia, married German architect Dieter Rausch in 2004 and later relocated to [[Middleburg, Virginia]].{{Citation needed|date=September 2018}}\n\nIn an appearance with [[Larry King]] on ''[[Larry King Live]]'' on December 1, 2003, Tripp talked about living with [[breast cancer]]. On the subject of her successful invasion of privacy lawsuit against the federal government, Tripp claimed that she actually came out behind financially because of attorneys' fees and the derailment of her government career. She also claimed that her violations of Lewinsky's privacy and the Clinton administration's violations of her privacy were not equivalent, as the Clinton administration's leaking of her employment history was illegal \u2014 noting that although her wiretapping was also illegal, she was able to avoid prosecution for such by accepting immunity in exchange for her testimony.<ref>[http://transcripts.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/0312/01/lkl.00.html CNN Larry King Live Interview With Linda Tripp] (Aired December 1, 2003)</ref>\n\n''[[The Washington Post]]'' reported that at an event in 2018, Tripp \u2014 in her first public address since 2000 \u2014 said \"she was the victim of 'a real high-tech lynching'\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Andrews-Dyer |first1=Helena |title=Linda Tripp says she was the victim of \u2018a real high-tech lynching\u2019 in first public address since 2000 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/reliable-source/wp/2018/07/30/linda-tripp-says-she-was-the-victim-of-a-real-high-tech-lynching-in-first-public-address-since-2000/?noredirect=on |work=Washington Post |date=July 30, 2018 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn the upcoming television series ''[[American Crime Story|Impeachment: American Crime Story]]'', Tripp will be portrayed by [[Sarah Paulson]].{{citation needed|date = April 2020}}</ref>\n\nTripp died from [[pancreatic cancer]] at the age of 70 on April 8, 2020.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Moore |first1=Mark |last2=Nelson |first2=Steven |title=Linda Tripp, whistleblower in Clinton-Lewinsky sex scandal, dead at 70 |url=https://nypost.com/2020/04/08/linda-tripp-whistleblower-in-lewinsky-scandal-near-death/ |website=New York Post |language=en |date= April 8, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url = https://www.ajc.com/news/breaking-linda-tripp-whistleblower-clinton-sex-scandal-dead-from-pancreatic-cancer/LGXMbINXPoywbGzpOJCHuI/|title = BREAKING: Linda Tripp, whistleblower in Clinton sex scandal, dead at 70 from cancer |last = Darnell|first = Tim|date = April 8, 2020|accessdate = April 8, 2020|work = [[The Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]}}</ref?\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite encyclopedia| title=Linda Tripp (Biography)| author=Scott P. Johnson| encyclopedia=Trials of the Century: An Encyclopedia of Popular Culture and the Law, Volume 1 ([[ABC-CLIO]] 2010) | pages=654\u2013655 }}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{Cite news|url=http://www.slate.com/articles/podcasts/slow_burn/2018/09/linda_tripp_who_taped_monica_lewinsky_on_slow_burn.html|title=Tell-All. Linda Tripp exposed Bill Clinton\u2019s affair with Monica Lewinsky. What was she thinking?|last=Neyfakh|first=Leon|date=2018-09-12|work=Slate|language=en-US|issn=1091-2339}} (Podcast based on a 2018 interview with Tripp)\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tripp, Linda}}\n[[Category:1949 births]]\n[[Category:American civil servants]]\n[[Category:Breast cancer survivors]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from East Hanover, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:People from Jersey City, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:People from Middleburg, Virginia]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Virginia]]\n[[Category:Women whistleblowers]]\n[[Category:Clinton\u2013Lewinsky scandal]]\n[[Category:Deaths from pancreatic cancer]]\n", "name_user": "Sunshineisles2", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLife after the Clinton\u2013Lewinsky scandal", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linda_Tripp"}
{"title_page": "Elias Fonsalada", "text_new": "[[File:BnF ms. 12473 fol. 125v - Elias Fonsalada (1).jpg|thumb|upright|Elias, from a 13th-century chansonnier]]\n'''Elias''' ('''de''') '''Fonsalada''' (fl. late 12th/first quarter of the 13th century)<ref>His two ''cansos'' have been assigned to the last years of [[Peter II of Aragon]] by Manfred Raupach (Jewers, 200 n29).</ref> was a [[troubadour]] from [[Bergerac, Dordogne|Bergerac]] in the [[P\u00e9rigord]] (the [[Diocese of P\u00e9rigueux]] according to his ''[[Vida (Occitan literary form)|vida]]'').<ref name=egan>Egan, 32. His entire ''vida'', in original [[Occitan]], goes: ''N'Elias Fonsalada si fo de Bragairac, del avesquat de Peiregors. Bels hom fo molt de sa persona, e fo fils d'un borges que se fetz joglar; e n'Elias fo joglars atressi. No bon trobaire mas noellaire fo; e saup benestar entre la gen.''</ref> Only two ''[[Canso (song)|cansos]]'' of his survive.\n\nHis ''vida'' goes further in describing him as a handsome man of the middle class, the son of a [[Bourgeoisie|burgher]] and [[jongleur]], who himself became a jongleur.<ref name=jones>Jones, 309.</ref> The biographer did not regard him as an accomplished ''trobaire'' (troubadour/composer/inventor of poetry) but as a ''noellaire''.<ref name=egan/> This word has been open to interpretation. Bouti\u00e8re and Schutz in their French compilation of the ''vidas'' of the troubadours translate it as \"auteur d'un genre particulier\" (author of a particular genre) or \"beau parleur\" (good conversationalist).<ref name=egan/> Later Levy traced its etymology to ''novelador'', \"auteur de novelles\" (author of ''novas'', novels), and Egan, in her English translation, has taken this up as \"storyteller\".<ref name=egan/> A ''nova'' was probably a [[narrative]], as opposed to [[lyric poetry|lyric]], work.<ref name=jewers195>Jewers, 195.</ref> Thus Elias' ''vida'' provides a rare glimpse of narrative vernacular writing in Occitan at the height of the troubadour art.\n\nThe poem ''En Abriu'' is assigned to Elias in manuscript ''C'' (a 14th-century work now known as f.f. 856 in the [[Biblioth\u00e8que nationale de France]], [[Paris]]).<ref>Gaunt et al., 324.</ref> This attribution, however, is contradicted by other sources and the poem is usually given to [[Marcabru]].\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n{{refbegin}}\n*Egan, Margarita (ed. and trans.) ''The Vidas of the Troubadours''. New York: Garland, 1984. {{ISBN|0-8240-9437-9}}.\n*Gaunt, Simon; Harvey, Ruth; and Paterson, Linda M., edd. ''Marcabru: A Critical Edition''. Boydell & Brewer, 2000.\n*Jewers, Caroline. \"The Name of the Ruse and the Round Table: Occitan Romance and the Case for Cultural Resistance.\" ''Neophilologus''. Vol. 81, No. 2 (Apr., 1997), pp.&nbsp;187&ndash;200.\n*Jones, W. Powell. [https://www.jstor.org/stable/458035 \"The Jongleur Troubadours of Provence.\"] ''Publication of the Modern Languages Association'', Vol. 46, No. 2. (Jun., 1931), pp.&nbsp;307&ndash;311.\n{{refend}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Troubadours]]\n[[Category:12th-century births]]\n[[Category:13th-century deaths]]\n[[Category:French male poets]]\n[[Category:Male composers]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:BnF ms. 12473 fol. 125v - Elias Fonsalada (1).jpg|thumb|upright|Elias, from a 13th-century chansonnier]]\n'''Elias''' ('''de''') '''Fonsalada''' (fl. late 12th/first quarter of the 13th century)<ref>His two ''cansos'' have been assigned to the last years of [[Peter II of Aragon]] by Manfred Raupach (Jewers, 200 n29).</ref> was a [[troubadour]] from [[Bergerac, Dordogne|Bergerac]] in the [[P\u00e9rigord]] (the [[Diocese of P\u00e9rigueux]] according to his ''[[Vida (Occitan literary form)|vida]]'').<ref name=egan>Egan, 32. His entire ''vida'', in original [[Occitan]], goes: ''N'Elias Fonsalada si fo de Bragairac, del avesquat de Peiregors. Bels hom fo molt de sa persona, e fo fils d'un borges que se fetz joglar; e n'Elias fo joglars atressi. No bon trobaire mas noellaire fo; e saup benestar entre la gen.''</ref> Only two ''[[Canso (song)|cansos]]'' of his survive.\n\nHis ''vida'' goes further in describing him as a handsome man of the middle class, the son of a [[Bourgeoisie|burgher]] and [[jongleur]], who himself became a jongleur.<ref name=jones>Jones, 309.</ref> The biographer did not regard him as an accomplished ''trobaire'' (troubadour/composer/inventor of poetry) but as a ''noellaire''.<ref name=egan/> This word has been open to interpretation. Bouti\u00e8re and Schutz in their French compilation of the ''vidas'' of the troubadours translate it as \"auteur d'un genre particulier\" (author of a particular genre) or \"beau parleur\" (good conversationalist).<ref name=egan/> Later Levy traced its etymology to ''novelador'', \"auteur de novelles\" (author of ''novas'', novels), and Egan, in her English translation, has taken this up as \"storyteller\".<ref name=egan/> A ''nova'' was probably a [[narrative]], as opposed to [[lyric poetry|lyric]], work.<ref name=jewers195>Jewers, 195.</ref> Thus Elias' ''vida'' provides a rare glimpse of narrative vernacular writing in Occitan at the height of the troubadour art.\n\nThe poem ''En Abriu'' is assigned to Elias in manuscript ''C'' (a 14th-century work now known as f.f. 856 in the [[Biblioth\u00e8que nationale de France]], [[Paris]]).<ref>Gaunt et al., 324.</ref> This attribution, however, is contradicted by other sources and the poem is usually given to [[Marcabru]].\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n{{refbegin}}\n*Egan, Margarita (ed. and trans.) ''The Vidas of the Troubadours''. New York: Garland, 1984. {{ISBN|0-8240-9437-9}}.\n*Gaunt, Simon; Harvey, Ruth; and Paterson, Linda M., edd. ''Marcabru: A Critical Edition''. Boydell & Brewer, 2000.\n*Jewers, Caroline. \"The Name of the Ruse and the Round Table: Occitan Romance and the Case for Cultural Resistance.\" ''Neophilologus''. Vol. 81, No. 2 (Apr., 1997), pp.&nbsp;187&ndash;200.\n*Jones, W. Powell. [https://www.jstor.org/stable